<FIRST>r a AM-MurderAcquittal     07-05 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Murder Acquittal,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Row Inmate Released to INS; May Face Deportation Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A death row inmate freed after serving eight
years for a murder he did not commit was turned over to federal
immigration authorities Wednesday for hearings on his deportation to
Canada, prison officials said.
   Jerry Bigelow's release was cleared last month by the state
Supreme Court when it ruled 6-1 not to review the state's appeal of
a lower court decision to acquit Bigelow of a murder for which he
was once sentenced to death.
   Bigelow, 28, a native of Canada who had been on Death Row at San
Quentin since 1981, was released to Immigration and Naturalization
Service officials at about 9 a.m. and taken to San Francisco, said
prison spokesman Lt. Cal White.
   ``Now he will face a deportation hearing and eventual return to
Canada,'' said Tony Marian, director of the detention and
deportation section of the INS.
   Bigelow's lawyer, Robert Bryan, said Bigelow would not oppose
deportation to Canada and could be deported as early as Thursday.
   Bryan said Canadian authorities have indicated they plan to
prosecute Bigelow for a 1980 prison escape. He said Bigelow had
served only one month of an 18-month robbery term before fleeing.
   But Bryan said he hoped Canada would take into account the years
Bigelow spent on Death Row for a murder he was later found not to
have committed.
   Formal deportation charges had not been filed against Bigelow,
but Marian said common charges include illegal entering the country,
overstaying a tourist visa or committing ``certain serious crimes.''
Bigelow has never been admitted to the United States for permanent
residence, Marian added.
   A bond hearing was planned before an immigration judge for
Thursday morning, said Marian. Bonds are set to ensure an
individual's appearance in court and, in some cases, to protect
public safety, Marian said, adding that authorities had not yet set
a bond amount for Bigelow.
   If Bigelow can post bond, he will be scheduled for a deportation
hearing in the future, Marian said. If he cannot or does not want to
post bond, Bigelow will be scheduled for a deportation hearing ``in
a matter of days,'' he said.
   Bigelow was serving a Canadian sentence for robbery when he
escaped and fled to California. He now faces possible deportation to
Canada to finish his sentence, White said.
   Bigelow was convicted of the Merced County murder of John Cherry,
then 26. Bigelow and Michael Ramandanovic were picked up hitchhiking
by Cherry, who was shot to death in a cornfield.
   Bigelow defended himself at his first trial, was denied a
court-appointed lawyer to assist him, and was convicted and
sentenced to death.
   Although state law requires all death sentences to be appealed to
the state Supreme Court, Bigelow asked the court to dismiss his
appeal. The court refused. Bigelow then tried twice to commit
suicide.
   In 1984, the court overturned his conviction and death sentence,
calling his trial a sham because of the failure to appoint a lawyer.
Bigelow remained on Death Row while facing retrial.
   A jury in Monterey County, where the retrial had been moved
because of publicity, came back with an innocent verdict on the
murder charge in May 1988.
   Citing inconsistencies in the case, Superior Court Judge Harkjoon
Paik refused to record the acquittal verdict and ultimately declared
a mistrial that would have allowed Bigelow to be tried again for
murder.
   But the 6th District Court of Appeal later unanimously upheld the
acquittal.
</TEXT>
