<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-Elections     07-05 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Elections,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ruling Party Recognizes First Gubernatorial Defeat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Institutional Revolutionary Party, which
has ruled Mexico for all its 60 years, on Tuesday recognized its
first defeat in a gubernatorial election, the government news agency
Notimex said.
   The party acknowledged that the conservative National Action
Party had won in Baja California in Sunday's regional balloting.
   Luis Donaldo Colosio, president of the governing party's national
executive committee, made the announcement in Mexico City.
   Since its founding in 1929, the party has never lost a
presidential election. It lost its first senate seats in the July 6
elections.
   Ernesto Ruffo, the National Action candidate, and Margarita
Ortega of the governing party, known as PRI, each had claimed
victory in the Baja California race. The electoral commission has
until Sunday to announce official returns.
   ``I feel like the governor because of the support of the
people,'' Ruffo, 37, a former mayor of Ensenada said earlier. He
claimed he was leading Mrs. Ortega by a 3-2 margin, with roughly
half the ballots counted.
   Ruffo also claimed his party, known as PAN, was winning the races
for mayors in the Baja California cities of Tijuana and Ensenada.
   Mrs. Ortega, 38, had claimed she was winning by a 9 percent
margin, with 87 percent of the votes counted and that her party's
candidates were leading in those two mayoral races.
   PRI also claimed it was winning a majority in the state
legislature, which has 15 elected members plus four chosen though
proportional representation.
   Opposition parties had said that if such claims were backed by
the electoral commission, they would consider the election stolen.
   The electoral commission, independent voting observers and PAN
all agreed there were numerous irregularities in the voting, such as
theft of ballot boxes, obstruction of opposition observers and the
early closing of some polling places.
   Sunday's elections in Baja California and four other Mexican
states were considered a test for President Carlos Salinas de
Gortari, who has promised clean elections in Mexico, even if it
means losses for the PRI.
   Two of the other states holding elections _ Zacatecas and
Campeche _ are traditional PRI strongholds, but in Michoacan the
leftist Democratic Revolutionary Party led by native son and former
presidential candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas was claiming victory.
   The Democratic Revolutionary Party claimed it had won at least 14
of Michoacan's 24 seats in the state assembly.
   In Ciudad Juarez, throngs of disgruntled PAN members staged a
90-minute demonstration Monday night at the local election board to
protest massive irregularities in the Chihuahua state elections for
mayors.
   PAN spokesman Gustavo Elizondo and other party leaders cited at a
news conference dozens of reports of voters having their thumbs
stamped with presumably indelible ink that could be washed off,
allowing them to vote more than once.
</TEXT>
