<FIRST>r w PM-BlackCatholics Bjt   07-05 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Black Catholics, Bjt,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Priest Who Started Black Catholic Congregation Suspended</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspended Roman Catholic priest says he'll
continue leading his unsanctioned African American Catholic
Congregation, contending that Washington's archbishop ``has failed
to deal with racism'' within the church.
   The Rev. George A. Stallings is forbidden to preach, celebrate
mass or administer any of the Roman Catholic Church's sacraments
including baptism, weddings or holy communion, church spokeswoman
Eileen Marks said Tuesday.
   The suspension was imposed by Cardinal James Hickey, archbishop
of the Washington diocese.
   But Stallings said Tuesday he will continue to hold Sunday
services for his new congregation, adding, ``The suspension only
affects my duties with the Roman Catholic Church.''
   ``The cardinal has failed to deal with racism in the Catholic
Church and hasn't responded to issues I have brought to his
attention,'' he said in an interview with WHUR radio.
   Stallings celebrated the African American church's first worship
ceremony in the chapel of a Washington law school on Sunday.
   Marks said Hickey's letter to Stallings, in which he imposed the
suspension, said the Sunday service was ``a public act of
disobedience.''
   Hickey said Stallings' act in establishing a separate group was
``a step toward separating yourself from the unity of the Catholic
Church.''
   The letter from the cardinal said the decision to suspend
Stallings was made partly to help him turn away from a
``destructive'' course of action. Marks said Hickey wants to leave
open the possibility of communication with Stallings despite the
suspension.
   Stallings said he created the new congregation, also known as the
Imani Temple, because he believes the Catholic Church is not
responsive to the cultural and spiritual needs of black parishioners.
   Sunday's ceremony was attended by about 500 people and included
traditional Catholic prayers and liturgy along with elements
borrowed from African and Southern black revival traditions. Black
representatives of other faiths, including Baptists and Muslims,
attended to show support for Stallings' move.
   Stallings, who announced plans for his separate congregation last
month, said Sunday, ``The church can't throw me out, and even if
they do throw me out, I have my own opinion ... they have theirs.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
