<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 0105EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     07-05 0934</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Look at the Dairy Cow of the Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The typical dairy cow of the 21st century will
be a much larger producer by today's standards, and might even turn
out some kinds of tailor-made milk, according to Agriculture
Department scientists.
   H. Duane Norman, animal research leader at the department's
Agricultural Research Service facility in Beltsville, Md., said
herds that yield as much as 40,000 pounds of milk per cow annually
(about 4,651 gallons) can be expected in the next century.
   Nationally, 1988 milk production averaged 14,213 pounds per cow,
or about 1,653 gallons.
   ``We've had individual cows already that produced 50,000
pounds,'' Norman said in the current issue of Agricultural Research
magazine. ``In 1945, we had 25 million dairy cows in the United
States; today we have about 10 million. But the milk yield per cow
is up from 4,600 pounds to an average of 14,000 pounds today.''
   The most controversial development is bovine somatotropin, or
BST, the so-called bovine growth hormone that is awaiting clearance
by the Food and Drug Administration before it can be used by dairy
farmers.
   Cows produce BST naturally in their pituitary glands, and it can
be made synthetically. Several companies are working on versions of
the chemical.
   Another Beltsville scientist, Henry F. Tyrell, said BST typically
would boost a cow's milk output by 15 percent, although on a
short-term basis it could rise by as much as 50 percent.
   ``I'd say we'll see basically a continuation of the same trends
of the last 50 years,'' Tyrell said. ``What I see is more emphasis
on tailoring milk to meet specific product demands.''
   Genetically, it is possible to change the relative proportions of
proteins in milk _ the casein, albumin and globulins.
   ``Part of the reason cheeses are different from each other is the
various proteins in the milk,'' Tyrell said. ``It's in this area,
altering the proportions in the milk for specific products, that
we'll see a change.''
   Vernon G. Pursel, a reproductive physiologist at Beltsville, said
he and others have been working for a year on targeting components
to the mammary glands of farm animals _ and that could mean some
rather exotic results.
   ``Depending on what gene you insert, you could have some of the
rare medical proteins produced in the mammary gland,'' Pursel said.
``These special proteins could be extracted from the milk and
purified.''
   One example, he said, is the blood-clotting factor used to treat
hemophilia, a rare protein that some day might be extracted from
milk.
   ``During the past year, we've transfered a gene for a mouse
protein into pigs. If the mouse gene functions correctly, the mouse
protein will be present in the milk produced by our transgenic
pigs,'' Pursel said.
   The next step, he said, will be to connect the regulatory part of
the mouse gene to part of a gene for rare medical protein so it can
be produced in the milk.
   ``The final step will be to transfer such a gene into the dairy
cow,'' Pursel said. ``If the regulatory part of the mouse gene
works, it could also be used to modify the composition of the milk.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newly discovered bee with a long tongue is
turning out to be a friend of rabbiteye blueberry producers, says
the Agriculture Department.
   The department said Monday that honey bees can't pollinate
rabbiteye blueberries because their tongues are too short. But the
new bee's tongue is longer and can reach into the blueberry's flower
for nectar.
   As it probes the flower with its long tongue, the bee also buzzes
it to loosen a cloud of pollen, said Jerry A. Payne, an entomologist
with the department's Agricultural Research Service.
   When the bee moves on, it carries pollen from one blueberry
flower to another, achieving pollination. Payne, who works at the
agency's Southeastern Fruit and Tree Nut Research Laboratory, Byron,
Ga., said in a report issued here that poor crops of rabbiteye
blueberries often result from poor cross pollination.
   The ground-nesting bee, Habropoda loboriosa, was found during a
three-year study with Auburn University in Alabama. The bee is
prevalent in the southeastern United States where rabbiteye
blueberries are grown on approximately 5,000 acres.
   Payne said the bee, which has been named the Southeastern
blueberry bee, is larger than a honey bee but smaller than a bumble
bee. The female has a black face minus a cream-colored dot that
distinguishes the male. Only the female gathers pollen.
   Depending on the season, consumers pay from $2 to $5 a pint for
rabbiteye blueberries.
   ``We don't know much about the bee's nesting habits,'' Payne
said. ``Therefore, we don't have any way yet to reintroduce it if
nests are destroyed. So we advise growers not to use insecticides
when blueberries bloom.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department has asked for public
comments for designing the 1990 feed grains program.
   Officials say that one of the main items will involve how much
land farmers will be required to set aside in order to qualify for
price supports and other benefits on 1990 crops of corn, sorghum,
oats and, if designated, barley.
   The 1985 farm law requires the annual set-aside to be at least
12.5 percent and no more than 20 percent of a producer's acreage
base when corn inventories exceed the level of 2 billion bushels at
the beginning of the season. The set-aside was 20 percent for 1989.
   Comments can be sent by Sept. 5 to: Director, Commodity Analysis
Division, USDA-ASCS, Room 3741-S, P.O. Box 2415, Washington D.C.,
20013.
</TEXT>
