<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0412,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE withclosing Mikkei, dollar
figures. Picks up graf 4 pvs, `Dealers said ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar edged down today against the
Japanese yen while the key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose
moderately.
   The dollar ended trading at 140.20 yen, down 0.75 yen from
Tuesday's 140.95 yen. It opened at 141.20 yen and ranged between
139.85 yen and 141.25 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 119.33 points, or 0.36
percent, finishing at 33,309.71. The index lost 46.04 points Tuesday.
   Dealers said trading in Tokyo was mixed with selling and buying,
after the index quickly gained more than 130 points in early trading.
   A dealer with New Japan Securities Co. said Japanese investors
were cautious due to concerns over elections for the upper house of
Parliament scheduled for July 23. The governing Liberal Democratic
Party is expected to lose many of its seats in the upper house of
Parliament, and possibly give up its majority.
   In currency dealings, the dollar fell as market players sold it
to buy European currencies, said Minori Takeuchi, a trader with
Chemical Bank in Tokyo.
   ``Since discount rate hikes of major European currencies last
week, the dollar has become weaker as investors have been less
attracted by it,'' she said, ``This also resulted in the dollar's
weakness against the yen.''
   Last week's concerted discount rate increases in Europe included
a 0.5 percentage point increase in West Germany and France.
   Ms. Takeuchi said Japanese investors would continue to make
technical adjustments and avoid major moves until Friday, when U.S.
unemployment figures for June are to be released.
</TEXT>
