<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     07-05 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Up, Dollar Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index more than made
up the previous day's losses today, while the dollar fell against
the Japanese yen for the third consecutive day.
   The dollar closed at 140.20 yen, down 0.75 yen from Tuesday's
140.95-yen finish. It opened at 141.20 yen and fluctuated between
139.85 yen and 141.25 yen.
   The dollar now has fallen 3.75 yen in three trading days.
   Today, investors were selling dollars and buying West German
marks, which resulted in the yen's gain against the dollar, said
Toru Kanai, a foreign exchange analyst with New Japan Securities, Co.
   ``The yen has been bought back since Monday, when the result of
Sunday's election for the Tokyo Metropolitan Assembly came out,'' he
said, adding that most investors had sold dollars too heavily before
the election, anticipating the losses by the ruling party.
   On Sunday, the governing Liberal Democratic Party won just 43 of
128 seats in the assembly, losing 20 seats.
   Kanai said investors still were reluctant to buy yen before
elections July 23 for half the seats in Parliament's upper house.
   ``But the dollar-buying incentive is even weaker before the
release of the U.S. unemployment report on Friday, which Japanese
investors think will determine U.S. monetary policy,'' he said.
   Many investors are anticipating an easing of U.S. interest rates,
which makes dollar-denominated investments less attractive to
foreign investors.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, a 46.04-point loser Tuesday, gained 119.33 points, or 0.36
percent, closing at 33,309.71.
   ``Trading was directionless and inactive,'' said Masahiro
Umemori, an analyst with Nomura Securities, Japan's largest
brokerage.
   ``Although the Nikkei rose today, the market lacks energy because
Japanese investors feel insecure about making major moves ahead of
the July 23 election,'' he said.
   The governing party is expected to suffer setbacks in the wake of
an influence-peddling scandal that forced former Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita to resign, an unpopular sales tax and allegations
that new Prime Minster Sousuke Uno kept paid mistresses.
   Other dealers said the yen's rise against the dollar had
reassured investors and contributed to the index's rise.
   Trading was thin, with first section volume estimated at 650
million shares, up from Tuesday's 550 million. Among gainers were
steel, shipbuilding and construction issues.
</TEXT>
