<FIRST>r a PM-Names SUB a0419 07-05 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names, SUB, a0419,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd item to UPDATE with further comments by Schaffer and
Morris.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The producer of the film ``The Thin Blue Line'' is
``hurt and upset'' that the man whose murder conviction was thrown
out after it was questioned in the movie is suing him for rights to
his life story.
   Randall Dale Adams' lawsuit, filed two weeks ago, claims producer
Errol Morris lost his rights to Adams' life story in ecember 1988,
when he failed to exercise a two-year option purchased from Adams
for $10 in December 1986.
   ``Morris left $10 in Adams' commissary account in jail,'' Randy
Schaffer, Adams' lawyer, said late Tuesday. ``A carton of cigarettes
was what that amounted to.''
   Adams was convicted of murdering a Dallas policeman and served 12
years in prison before an appeals court overturned the conviction.
The court acted after the release of the movie, in which another
inmate all but confessed to the slaying. Adams was freed in March,
and prosecutors declined to retry him.
   ``I worked very, very hard for a number of years to see that
justice was done in this case and to see that Randall Adams walked
out of prison,'' Morris said.
   The producer said his profits from the film, which was not widely
distributed, were ``nil'' and added that he is still paying off
debts from the movie.
   Morris said he is willing to renegotiate the rights to Adams'
story. ``There is a desire on my part to settle this quickly and
without acrimony,'' he said.
   Schaffer said Morris doesn't seem to be the problem in current
negotiations aimed at given Adams clear title to any future rights
to his story. He said Morris had sold all rights he owned, including
those of Adams' to Mirimax Productions Co., also listed as a
defendant in the lawsuit.
   ``We just want to clear up who owns the rights,'' Schaffer said.
   Schaffer said his 40-year-old client is not seeking royalties,
only a declaration that he owns the right to his own life story so
he can pursue offers estimated ``in the neighborhood of six
figures.''
</TEXT>
