<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     07-05 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JAMESTOWN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fisherman who cast his line for a catch
he could sink his teeth into instead reeled in a fish that could
sink its teeth into him.
   The three-pound piranha Greg Dell'Aria caught at a stone quarry
near this southwest Ohio town later devoured every goldfish in a
bait shop tank where Dell'Aria had stored the fish.
   ``He's got teeth as big as your bottom ones,'' the 32-year-old
fisherman said last week.
   Dell'Aria said he and some friends were fishing for bass on June
26 when he caught the piranha in about three feet of water. ``It
blew my mind; I'll tell you that,'' he said.
   Dell'Aria put the piranha in a tank at a friend's bait shop to
keep it alive. But the friend's wife had a baby the next day, so the
bait shop was closed for three days.
   When Dell'Aria's wife finally picked up the fish four days later,
she was told that ``it ate all of his goldfish _ cleaned him out,''
Dell'Aria said.
   By then Doug Maloney, fish management supervisor for the state
Fish and Wildlife District 5 office in Xenia, confirmed that the
fish was indeed a piranha.
   ``They were really surprised,'' Dell'Aria said. ``Everybody was
saying piranhas don't get that big. But I guess if they get old
enough and people feed them enough, they do.''
   The fish and wildlife experts theorized that someone bought the
piranha in a pet store and released it into the stone quarry.
   The piranha lived for several days in a beverage cooler filled
with water before it died. Dell'Aria says he will have his catch
mounted.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHOTEAU, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wanted: family practitioner with a yen for
country living and the qualifications to deliver babies. Reward of
$10,000 offered for information leading to hiring.
   Teton Medical Center, borrowing a tactic long used by law
officers to locate fugitives, has promised a bounty of $10,000 to
anybody whose tip leads to the hiring of a doctor of medicine or
osteopathy with obstetrics qualifications to practice in this
northwest Montana town of 1,800 people.
   The hospital hopes the reward offer will encourage residents to
join the search and make the process of recruiting a physician to a
rural hospital less painful, administrator Roz Bushman said.
   ``It's very difficult to get a doctor into rural areas,'' she
said. Rural physicians have to work long hours, are on call around
the clock seven days a week and earn substantially less than their
urban counterparts, she said.
   Bushman said Teton Medical Center, which serves about 6,500
people in Teton County and the Augusta area, needs another family
practitioner to handle a growing obstetrics practice and to spell
the current family practitioner whenever he leaves town.
   The advertisement featuring the medical center's reward ran twice
in late June in Choteau's weekly newspaper. Bushman said she has
received a couple of responses that she is tracking.
   The idea of posting a reward was suggested by the corporate
office of Lutheran Health Systems, which leases the 14-bed hospital
and its adjoining nursing home, Bushman said.
   The corporate office got good responses from several other small
hospitals that offered rewards and hired doctors within 90 days,
Bushman said.
</TEXT>
