<FIRST>r a PM-FireDeaths     07-05 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fire Deaths,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Children Die in House Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto LX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KRISTI D. SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators of an early-morning house
fire that killed six unattended children suspect a candle used to
light the house may have caused the city's deadliest blaze in 26
years.
   The victims ranged from age 9 to 14, said Capt. Mike Brown of the
Louisville Fire Department. No adults were home when the fire
started Tuesday, he said.
   The fire was accidental and started in a couch in a front room,
said Capt. Henry Ott, supervisor of the arson unit. It may have been
caused by a candle or a smoldering cigarette, he said.
   Electricity had been shut off because of overdue bills and
candles apparently were being used to light the house, Ott said.
   Chuck Randall, manager of district operations for Louisville Gas
&amp; Electric Co., said the electricity had been disconnected for an
undetermined amount of time.
   The deaths might have been prevented had batteries been in a
smoke detector found inside the home, Brown said.
   A smoke detector found on a mantle inside the home looked like
the type given out by the fire department, said Maj. Dayle Fortney,
chief investigator of the arson bureau.
   Batteries in another smoke detector weren't working, said fire
Maj. Donald Cummins.
   ``We provided a smoke detector at that residence in 1985 ... and
also checked an existing detector,'' Brown said.
   Assistant Jefferson County Coroner Sue Wurst identified the
victims as Shantee Watkins, 14; his cousin, Angie Watkins, 9; her
brother, Dion Watkins, 9; Latrice Gaither, 10; her brother, Don Juan
Gaither, 12; and a cousin of the Gaithers, Ginger Anderson, 10.
   Autopsies showed all died of smoke inhalation, Wurst said.
   Four of the children were found in separate bedrooms and the two
10-year-olds were found in the kitchen near the back door, which was
locked with a deadbolt that could be opened only with a key,
officials said.
   ``It's hard to say if they tried to get out,'' Brown said.
   The fire broke out about 3:30 a.m. The two-story frame house was
engulfed in flames when firefighters arrived and nothing could be
done to save the children, Brown said.
   An uncle of three of the children tried to get inside the house
and was jailed after scuffling with a police officer who tried to
restrain him.
   A woman, apparently a parent who lived at the home, arrived
shortly after the fire began. ``She was in shock, running up and
down the street screaming,'' Fortney said.
   A neighbor, Teresa Smith, 31, said the mother rarely left her two
children alone at the home. The four other children were cousins who
visited frequently, she said.
   ``They were a close family,'' Mrs. Smith said.
   Col. Jesse Spratt of the fire department said it was the city's
deadliest fire since 1963, when seven children were killed at a home
just a few blocks from the site of Tuesday's blaze.
</TEXT>
