<FIRST>r a PM-AmtrakShooting     07-05 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Amtrak Shooting,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seattle Man Fatally Shot Aboard Amtrak Train</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE WALES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Seattle man was fatally shot on an
Amtrak train and grieving relatives are questioning security
measures that would allow a man to board with a handgun.
   Ward Boole, 64, was shot while in a vestibule between passenger
and crew cars of the Amtrak Silver Star, said Polk County Sheriff's
Sgt. Roy McGuirt.
   ``He got on that thing thinking he was safe,'' said the victim's
brother, Bill Boole. ``The man served in three wars and never got
wounded. Then he goes up to a person like that and gets shot for no
reason. That is the tragedy of this country.''
   Boole said the federal government should require everybody who
boards public transportation to be searched for guns.
   Claude Paige, 69, of Fort Lauderdale, gave his .32-caliber
revolver to an Amtrak employee immediately after the shooting Monday.
   Paige was charged with second-degree murder, McGuirt said,
because there was no evidence the killing was planned.
   Passenger John Nelson said he, Paige and Boole met one another
for the first time on the train and were drinking in the train's
lounge just before the shooting.
   Nelson said Paige was talking to himself and had a revolver
tucked in his right front pants pocket just before the shooting.
After noticing the gun, Nelson said, he left Boole and Paige and
returned to his seat.
   Moments later, Nelson said, Boole left the lounge and walked into
the vestibule, with Paige following. Nelson said he heard a gunshot
and saw Boole fall to the floor.
   It may have been the first passenger murder on the federally
subsidized rail system, said Pat Duricka, an Amtrak spokeswoman in
Washington, D.C.
   ``No one can recall something like this happening,'' she said.
   Paige was held in the Polk County jail in lieu of $15,000 bail,
McGuirt said.
   The Silver Star, which originated in Miami and carried 241
passengers, was stopped immediately after the shooting just west of
Lake Wales and held for 2{ hours.
   Boole had visited relatives in Florida and was en route to see
some of his grandchildren in South Carolina. He died early Tuesday
at Winter Haven Hospital from the blast to his right eye, officials
said.
</TEXT>
