<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     07-05 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar recovered somewhat in European
dealings early today after plunging earlier amid profit-taking in
Asian markets. Gold prices were higher.
   Dealers said the dollar dropped in Asian trading as dealers
continued to take profits in dollar-yen trading, but buying interest
in the European markets was limited and the dollar regained ground
despite speculation that the U.S. Federal Reserve will lower
interest rates as soon as Thursday.
   Dealers said activity was moderately active after Tuesday's light
trading during the Fourth of July holiday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.75 Japanese yen to a closing 140.20 yen. Later, in
London, it eased further to 140.05 yen.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.9110 West German marks, down from 1.9220
   _1.6395 Swiss francs, down from 1.6527
   _6.4845 French francs, down from 6.5375
   _2.1502 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1710
   _1,383.50 Italian lire, down from 1,393.50
   _1.1915 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1935
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.60, up from $1.5870 late
Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at $379.40 a troy ounce, up from $376.50
bid late Tuesday. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion
dealers fixed a recommended price of $378.40.
   In Zurich, the late bid price was $378.75, up from $376.50 bid
late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.02 to close at $379.33.
   Silver bullion rose in London to $5.25 a troy ounce, up from
$5.24 bid late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
