<FIRST>r a PM-FatFish     07-05 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fat Fish,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gluttonous Grouper Celebrates Truly Independent Fourth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A greedy grouper whose seemingly
insatiable appetite for his expensive tankmates made him famous
celebrated Independence Day by swimming free in his new home _ the
ocean.
   Eighteen months ago, a foot-long, 3-pound brown-spotted jewfish _
a member of the grouper family _ was plucked from the waters off the
Florida Keys. Terry Haley, owner of an aquarium store in Lansing,
Ill., bought it and took it north.
   He fed the fish five pounds of smelt every other day. But
evidently that wasn't enough for Flazey _ the fish's name, short for
fat and lazy.
   Between meals, he snacked on $5,000 worth of exotic fish that
shared his aquarium. That took six months. Flazey even tried to
consume a two-foot shark.
   The fish grew to 3{ feet and 35 pounds. Haley grew tired of
replacing costly tropical fish.
   So Flazey was returned to the ocean Monday, released from a thick
yellow net off Fort Lauderdale. Haley had flown the fish south
several days before.
   Wearing scuba gear, the store owner accompanied his famous charge
into the waves, and patted him one last time. Flazey then drifted
away.
   ``It was nice of him to hang around for a while,'' Haley said.
   Newspaper and television photographers captured the poignant
parting from a nearby Florida Marine Patrol boat.
   Haley said it was hard to watch Flazey disappear into the
darkness.
   ``I feel kind of bad, to tell you the truth,'' he said. ``It's
hard to explain. Even though it's a fish, it's like any other pet
you care for.''
   Flazey traveled to the site in a 50-gallon tank aboard a 24-foot
boat owned by Noyes Marine Life, the Fort Lauderdale aquarium
supplier that caught the fish and sold it to Haley.
   The store owner said he got phone calls from folks who didn't
want to see Flazey released, fearing he might be caught by an
angler. But Haley decided to return the grouper to his natural home.
   ``If we had never taken him out of the ocean, he would have had
just as equal a chance for survival,'' Haley said. ``He'll do fine.''
   Shortly after letting Flazey go, Haley seemed a bit wistful as he
thought of his former pet.
   ``It'd be great to know where he is right now,'' he said. ``He's
probably looking at the menu.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
