<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-Elections 1stLd-Writethru   07-05 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Elections, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0468,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>For First Time in 60 Years, PRI Party Loses Governor's Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES thruout with PRI history, presidential spokeswoman's
quotes. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time in its 60 years, the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party has accepted defeat in a
gubernatorial race.
   Luis Donaldo Colosio, president of the party's national executive
committee, said results compiled by the party showed the
conservative National Action Party (PAN) candidate had won Sunday's
race in Baja California state.
   Since its founding in 1929, the party known by its Spanish
initials as PRI has never lost a presidential election, so
dominating Mexican politics that its name became synonymous with
government.
   Only a year ago did the party suffer its first Senate losses, in
Michoacan state and the Mexico City federal district.
   Sunday's elections in five states were seen as a major test of
whether after seven months in office, President Carlos Salinas de
Gortari would make good on his promise to recognize opposition
victories and clean up the electoral process.
   A presidential spokeswoman said Salinas passed the test.
   ``The president made the decision to plunge into the democratic
game,'' she said, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``It is an
unprecedented change in the history of Mexico.
   ``It marks the beginning of a new step in the political life of
the country. ... This opens new channels for political competition
in Mexico and living together in a multiparty system.''
   Official vote results are to be released Sunday, but Colosio's
statement was considered de facto recognition of the PRI loss in
Baja California.
   Salinas, the presidential spokeswoman said, ``is the first
president in the contemporary era of Mexico who has the courage and
the ability to recognize a defeat of his own party at the state
level.''
   Jesus Antonio Rivera, president of PAN's state committee in Baja
California, said he received the news of the victory with ``total
joy.''
   The victorious Ernesto Ruffo, a former mayor of Ensenada, and the
PRI's Margarita Ortega had each claimed victory in the gubernatorial
race.
   Opposition parties had said that if the PRI claim of victory were
backed by the electoral commission, they would consider the election
stolen.
   The PRI in recent years has been increasingly criticized for
alleged widespread vote-manipulation, rigging of elections and
repeated balloting irregularities.
   The party had in the past maintained its strength through a
network of labor unions and organizations of farm workers,
government employees and other groups that turned out the vote in
exchange for jobs, political posts, access to funds and other perks.
   Elections last July showed PRI's power was fading.
   United behind a single candidate for the first time, Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas, the left held Salinas to 50 percent of the vote. The PRI
held onto its congressional majority, but lost the two-thirds needed
to rubber stamp constitutional reforms.
   The electoral commission, independent voting observers and PAN
all agreed there were numerous irregularities in Sunday's voting,
such as the theft of ballot boxes, obstruction of opposition
observers and the early closing of some polling places.
   Two of the other states holding elections _ Zacatecas and
Campeche _ are traditional PRI strongholds, but in Michoacan the
leftist Democratic Revolutionary Party led by Cardenas was claiming
victory.
   The Democratic Revolutionary Party claimed it had won at least 14
of Michoacan's 24 seats in the state assembly.
   In Ciudad Juarez, across the border from El Paso, Texas, throngs
of disgruntled PAN members staged a 90-minute demonstration Monday
night at the local election board to protest massive irregularities
in the Chihuahua state elections for mayors.
   PAN spokesman Gustavo Elizondo and other party leaders said
dozens of voters reported having their thumbs stamped with
presumably indelible ink that could be washed off, allowing them to
vote more than once.
</TEXT>
