<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 0810EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Shibley     07-05 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Shibley,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>George Shibley, Sirhan Sirhan's Defense Lawyer, Dead at 79</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Shibley, a defense attorney who
represented Robert F. Kennedy's assassin, Sirhan Sirhan, and helped
defend 12 Hispanics in the ``Zoot Suit'' murder case of the 1940s,
has died of cardiac arrest at 79.
   Shibley died Tuesday at Good Samaritan Hospital, where he had
undergone heart surgery June 8.
   He was a supporter of Kennedy's presidential campaign when the
senator was shot to death in 1968 in Los Angeles hours after winning
the California Democratic primary.
   But he took on Sirhan's case after Mary Sirhan appealed for help
when her son was sentenced to death.
   Sirhan's sentence was reduced to life in prison when the
California Supreme Court, ruling in an unrelated case, said the
state Constitution prohibited the death penalty. The state has since
restored capital punishment.
   In the 1940s the lawyer, who had graduated from Stanford
University only a few years before, helped defend 12 young Hispanics
in the murder of a Mexican immigrant in what came to be known as the
``Zoot Suit'' case because of the long, baggy suits worn in the
barrio. The case became the basis of a movie and play.
   Newspapers of the era fanned prejudice against the defendants,
who were convicted despite the efforts of seven defense attorneys.
But Shibley, who had filed a rash of objections during the trial,
successfully appealed.
   ``Depending on how you look at it, the case made me famous or
infamous,'' Shibley recalled in 1986. ``It also made the forces of
law and order hate me.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
