<FIRST>r a PM-Deaf-MuteRescued     07-05 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deaf-Mute Rescued,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sign Language Used to Save Deaf-Mute Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police talked a depressed deaf-mute man down from
the rooftop ledge of a 32-story building with help from two sisters
who know sign language.
   Police were called to the building in upper Manhattan on Tuesday.
Tina and Brenda Pedraza, who live in the neighborhood and heard of
the problem, offered to help.
   Officers Henry Medina and Ray Ruiz told Tina Pedraza, 31, what
they wanted to say. In sign language, she passed it on to Brenda
Pedraza, 22, who signed it to Victor Bruno, 24.
   ``We told him that we had experienced suicide in our family,''
said Tina Pedraza, ``and that he was young and had a life to live.''
   Bruno said he was depressed and wanted to visit his sister in
Michigan, Medina said.
   The officers told Bruno they had a plane ticket to Detroit for
him and threw a watch onto the ledge to show him the flight would
leave soon. When Bruno went to pick up the watch, the officers
grabbed him.
   He was taken to Harlem Hospital for observation, police said.
</TEXT>
