<FIRST>r a PM-KennelFire     07-05 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kennel Fire,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Races Through Kennel, Dozens of Animals Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dogs and cats yelped and scratched
firefighters trying to carry them to safety as a fire raced through
a packed kennel, killing nearly three dozen animals, officials said
today.
   Firefighters saved 35 pets in Tuesday's blaze at the Townhouse
for Dogs, which was filled for the long holiday weekend, said Fire
Battalion Chief Joe Milligan. Thirty-five pets were killed and 16
others were missing.
   At least 10 of the rescued animals were treated by veterinarians
for shock and smoke inhalation, Milligan said.
   The fire broke out in a storage building owned by the Hychem Co.
and spread to the adjacent kennel, burning for about two hours and
causing an estimated $1.2 million in damage, Milligan said.
   Pet owners waited anxiously outside the building as an occasional
dog bolted out, chased by firefighters.
   Barbara Christiansen of La Canada scanned the gutted shelter
entrance. ``I have a Scottie named Brindy. I've been taking her here
for years,'' she said. ``I'm sure she would get out if she could.''
   Christiansen wept when she learned the dog had died.
   ``Initially, we could hear the dogs yelling and screaming,'' said
fire Capt. John Higby, whose hands were covered with scratches from
a cat he saved. ``We could barely see anything.''
   The storage building, which contained cleaning chemicals, was
destroyed, but the fire was confined to the rear of the kennel, the
chief said.
   The cause of the blaze was under investigation.
   One firefighter was treated after receiving an electric shock.
Another suffered heat exhaustion.
</TEXT>
