<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Crash-Reaction     07-05 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Crash-Reaction,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Belgium, Netherlands, West Germany Criticize Moscow on MiG Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAF CASERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Belgium, the Netherlands and West
Germany today criticized Moscow for failing to inform them that a
pilotless MiG-23 jet was flying over their territory. The jet
crashed in Belgium, killing one person.
   The three NATO nations lodged stern protests, asking their Soviet
ambassadors why they had to wait for 10 hours Tuesday to get a
reaction to the MiG-23 crash through the official news agency Tass.
   Wreckage of the Soviet plane, meanwhile, was being removed from
the crash site on the French-Belgian border, 55 miles west of
Brussels. Officials said remains will be returned to the Soviet
Union.
   ``There was an extreme slowness in information,'' Foreign
Minister Mark Eyskens told reporters after he summoned Felix
Bogdanov, the Soviet ambassador.
   ``In the age of glasnost, transparency and information without
reserve,'' must be more quickly forthcoming, he added of President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of openness.
   In Bonn, foreign ministry spokesman Hanns Schumacher said his
government summoned a Soviet diplomat and expressed its annoyance
that ``nothing was done to inform governments involved about the
incident.''
   The Dutch foreign ministry asked ``the Soviet Union for
clarification on the incident ... and for measures that will prevent
any such incident in the future.''
   Eyskens called for improved East-West cooperation. ``My
conclusion, corroborated by the Soviet ambassador, is that
information systems have to be improved between the two blocs,'' he
said, adding Belgium will raise the issue with its allies in the
Western alliance.
   Soviet Defense Minister Dmitri Yazov had no explanation why
Warsaw Pact defense forces failed to detect the runaway jet. ``It is
difficult to say why it was not shot down, why it was not
detected,'' Yazov said in Moscow.
   ``A large-scale investigation should be carried out,'' he said.
Investigators were on their way to Kolobrzeg airfield in Poland,
where the plane took off on a training flight.
   ``The afterburner spontaneously switched off during the takeoff
and the plane began to decelerate,'' Yazov said. ``Following the
bail-out, a sufficient thrust, in all probability, developed and the
plane continued its flight.''
   The errant combat plane flew for about an hour over densely
populated areas of West Germany, the Netherlands and Belgium before
crashing into a house a few miles from a major urban sprawl, killing
one resident.
   ``The Warsaw Pact had over an hour to warn us,'' said Eyskens.
``They did not. It is regrettable.''
   NATO officials said two American jets intercepted the runaway MiG
over West Germany, but did not shoot it down because it was over a
densely populated area, Tass said.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
