<FIRST>u a PM-Reagan-Horses 1stLd-Writethru a0467 07-05 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Reagan-Horses, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0467,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan a Horse Fancier From Way Back</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead and ADDS two grafs to CORRECT `than' to `as' in quote
and give the full remark.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Reagan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE M. PETERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Reagan once said, ``There is
nothing so good for the inside of a man as the outside of a horse.''
   He may not feel that way today following his Fourth of July toss
from a horse at a ranch in Mexico that resulted in minor bruises and
abrasions.
   Reagan spokesman Mark Weinberg said the horse Reagan was riding
bucked on a rocky downhill slope, throwing the 78-year-old former
president to the ground.
   Weinberg said Reagan called the incident ```My own private
rodeo,''' adding that ``he's an excellent rider and he held on quite
a while.''
   Although Tuesday's ride may have been a rough one, Reagan has
generally found serenity on the back of a horse.
   ``That's how he charges his batteries,'' said former Reagan
spokesman Jim Lake in a 1980 newspaper interview. ``He doesn't go
out and drink or carouse or party or entertain, he likes to go up
there in the loneliness of his 677-acre ranch, riding his horses,
building his fences being with his wife. ... I think it's his sense
of personal accomplishment and achievement, his physical handling of
the world.''
   Aides have said that Reagan did much of his thinking about the
problems a president might face in the days prior to his successful
1980 campaign while riding a horse around his ranch 30 miles west of
Santa Barbara.
   Reagan took up riding when he was a young sportscaster in Des
Moines, Iowa in the 1930s, and pursued it enthusiastically right
through his presidency. He would often take off one afternoon a week
to go riding at the Marine base in Quantico, Va.
   As California governor, Reagan rode several times in the annual
trek of the Rancheros Vistadores, a 65-miles ride that was started
as a way for men who enjoy the atmosphere of the old West to get
away for a few days.
   In 1976, when he made his ill-fated presidential run, Reagan told
reporters his Secret Service guards were joining him on rides.
   ``I give them riding lessons,'' he said.
   During his eight years as president, Reagan on a horse was a
familiar sight, serving as a reminder to the nation that its elderly
president was in robust health.
   In September 1985, Reagan joked about taking his first horseback
ride since undergoing colon cancer surgery two months earlier.
   He told reporters, ``My horse and I had a chance to get
reacquainted and I had time to reflect once again on an old truth
from the cavalry _ there is nothing so good for the inside of a man
as the outside of a horse.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890705-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 0925EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru   07-05 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0439,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Jet Fighters Attack Rebel Positions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Afghan air force bombing rebels
around Jalalabad. Pickup 6th graf `The fighter-bombers...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan jet fighters bombed guerrilla
positions around Kabul and the eastern city of Jalalabad today, a
day after the government claimed the resistance was preparing a
major offensive.
   Also today, at least eight rockets slammed into Kabul, killing at
least five people, said an official of the Soviet-backed government.
   Two rockets hit a residential area 1,000 yards from the
Continental Hotel in northwestern Kabul, where most visiting
foreigners, including journalists, live. There were no immediate
reports of casualties near the hotel.
   Diplomatic sources and witnesses said the dawn air strikes on the
guerrilla positions near Kabul were the most intensive in weeks, but
there was no immediate report of casualties.
   The Supreme Defense Council, reporting the bombings around
Jalalabad, said its forces ``were combatting with high morale and
inflicting retaliatory blows'' to defend the city, which has been
under guerrilla siege since March 7.
   The statement gave no word on casualties.
   The government official, who demanded anonymity, said the air
force and artillery units battled the U.S.-backed guerrillas
Jalalabad.
   The city is 75 miles east of the capital and 45 miles west of the
border with Pakistan, where many of the guerrillas are based.
   The fighter-bombers were seen flying off from Kabul and nearby
Baghram air base in formations of two and three for the Paghman
Mountains northwest of the capital. The mountains serve as a
sanctuary for resistance fighters.
   Thirty to 35 planes took part in an operation that began at dawn
and continued for 90 minutes, witnesses said.
   Afghan government officials were not available for immediate
comment.
   Some of the aircraft headed for the eastern province of
Nangarhar, where the guerrillas launched their first major attacks
three weeks after the Soviet Union completed its troop withdrawal
from Afghanistan on Feb. 15.
   Jalalabad, scene of fierce battles between the resistance and
government troops, is the capital Nangarhar and the country's fifth
largest city.
   It is considered of strategic importance because of its proximity
to Pakistan, where the most powerful guerrilla groups are based.
   The government claims it broke the rebel siege on Jalalabad last
month, but official Kabul Radio has reported fighting around the
city for the past two weeks. The radio said guerrillas on Tuesday
fired artillery and rockets into residential areas of Jalalabad,
killing four people, including two children, and wounding eight,
including two soldiers.
   The government said Tuesday that Moslem rebels were planning
simultaneous ``massive attacks'' on Kabul and other major cities,
and asked the United Nations to intervene to stop the ``impending
bloodbath.''
   In a letter to U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar,
Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil said the guerrillas were planning to
launch the assault in mid-July.
   Wakil said the rebels were being aided in their planned attack by
U.S. and Pakistani army officers. He did not elaborate.
   ``The grave consequences (of the attack) which will include
bloodshed, killings and destruction, will be shouldered by the
Pakistani militarists and overseas designers of the attack,'' Wakil
said in a statement Tuesday.
   The ruling People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan seized power
in an April 1978 coup. In December 1979, the Soviet Union intervened
to prop up the Marxist regime.
   Soviet troops left Afghanistan after a U.N.-mediated accord.
</TEXT>
