<HEAD>Mother Charged in Death of 11-Year-Old Daughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JONESBORO, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who blamed the deaths of her four
children on ``bad luck'' has been charged with murdering her eldest
daughter in 1982.
   Martha Ann Johnson, 34, was arrested Monday and jailed without
bail in the death of 11-year-old Jennyann Wright, Clayton County
police said.
   Jennyann's death was originally attributed to ``probable
asphyxia'' of undetermined cause.
   Death certificates said the girl's 2-year-old brother and
3-month-old sister died of sudden infant death syndrome in 1977 and
1980. A 2-year-old brother in 1981 died of a seizure disorder of
unknown causes.
   The case was reopened in December after inquiries by The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
   Sgt. Ken Stewart said he has ``good information on two of the
four'' deaths but refused to discuss the information or say whether
other murder charges will be filed.
   Authorities said that before each death Mrs. Johnson's husband at
the time, Earl S. Bowen, had moved out. Mrs. Johnson ascribed the
deaths to ``bad luck.''
