<FIRST>r i PM-Sihanouk     07-05 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sihanouk,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sihanouk Says Guerrillas Will Keep Fighting After Vietnam Withdraws</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Baker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodian resistance leader Prince Norodom
Sihanouk today ruled out a separate peace agreement with the
Vietnamese-installed government in Phnom Penh and promised to keep
fighting.
   He told a news conference that Vietnam's promised September
withdrawal of its troops is a farce.
   And Sihanouk clung to his Khmer Rouge allies, saying any
settlement must include the communists who killed perhaps a million
of their countrymen while they were in power 1975-78.
   ``I tell you very clearly that I will not go to Phnom Penh,''
Sihanouk said at his mansion in Beijing, one of several
homes-in-exile.
   ``I refuse to cooperate with Hun Sen on a bilateral basis,'' he
said of Cambodia's prime minister.
   Vietnam, which invaded Cambodia in 1978 to oust the Khmer Rouge,
has said it will pull the last of its troops out in September.
However, Sihanouk claimed that 130,000 Vietnamese soldiers will
remain disguised as Cambodian soldiers and peasant militia.
   He insisted that no settlement can be reached until all
Vietnamese have left, including 1 million Vietnamese civilian
settlers, and until Hun Sen agrees to a coalition including the
Khmer Rouge.
   ``The problem will not be solved after the 30th of September,''
Sihanouk said.
   ``No one can stop the resistance from fighting. It is not because
we don't have compassion for our people,'' he said. ``We are not for
war. We are fighting for peace. But peace without independence is
meaningless.''
   In talks in May, Hun Sen had proposed changes to make the
Cambodian Constitution more acceptable to the prince and suggested
that Sihanouk return to Phnom Penh as head of state after the
Vietnamese withdrawal.
   Hun Sen has refused to accept Khmer Rouge participation in a
post-Vietnamese coalition government including Sihanouk and a third
resistance group led by non-communist Son Sann.
   Sihanouk, who was held under house arrest when the Khmer Rouge
were in power, appeared in May to flirt with the idea of dropping
his communist allies. However, he said today such a move would put
``the oxen before the cart.''
   ``We must concentrate on fighting the Vietnamese,'' he said. He
said critics focus on Khmer Rouge atrocities but ignore Amnesty
International reports alleging torture and murder by Hun Sen's
government.
   Sihanouk is under international pressure, including from
Southeast Asian nations that support him, to reach an agreement
before the Vietnamese withdraw, but he said he is not optimistic.
   The prince rejected Hun Sen's proposed constitutional amendments
as ``cosmetic,'' saying they would leave the government ``very
Vietnamese-style communist.''
   He said the resistance is preparing its own draft to present at
July 24 peace talks in Paris. It will provide for a ``liberal
parliamentary democracy'' modeled on France, with a president chosen
by direct popular election for a seven-year term.
</TEXT>
