<HEAD>Precede KENNEBUNKPORT</HEAD>
<HEAD>President Ends Maine Holiday</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 14 grafs with return to Washington, Mrs. Bush comments;
picks up at pvs 10th graf, Bush looked</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush returned to the White House
today to work on pre-summit briefings following five exercise-filled
days that his wife said were not exactly restful, ``but a lot of
fun.''
   From his vacation home in Kennebunkport, Maine, on Tuesday, Bush
placed a call to former President Reagan, who was slightly scraped
and bruised when thrown from a horse in Mexico earlier in the day.
   First lady Barbara Bush told reporters today that the president
could not reach Reagan directly by telephone, but sent best wishes
to him through security personnel and Reagan messaged him back.
   Mrs. Bush also disclosed that the five-day Fourth of July
vacation at last produced a successful presidential fishing
excursion.
   After four days with nary a bite, Bush caught five bluefish on
Tuesday, she said, holding her hands about 18 inches apart to
indicate their size.
   The president, who spent his vacation in an almost non-stop whirl
of tennis, golf, running, boating and swimming, hosted 70 people for
dinner one night, including extended family and local friends, the
first lady said.
   She joked that she was going home to rest after the hectic
vacation.
   ``Three grandchildren, two dogs and 500 relatives is not rest,''
Mrs. Bush told reporters flying home with the president. ``But a lot
of fun,'' she added.
   The White House doctor traveling with the president, Dr. Lawrence
Mohr, said Bush's frenetic pace was typical.
   ``I never saw him tired the whole weekend,'' Mohr said, although
Bush himself admitted to reporters he was tired at the end of one
day that had begun with a 6:30 a.m. jog and included boating,
tennis, swimming, golf, fishing and church services.
   Mrs. Bush brushed aside a question on her own feelings regarding
the Supreme Court decision Monday giving the states power to
regulate and restrict abortions.
   ``I go with my president,'' she said. Bush applauded the court
decision as a good step.
   Bush had no public schedule today but was planning to meet with
top advisers for briefings on the upcoming economic summit in Paris.
   He leaves Sunday for Poland, where his call this week for
withdrawal of Soviet troops was apparently designed to have public
appeal.
   Bush looked ahead to his East European trip in an interview with
Polish journalists that was released by his staff on Monday.
   In the interview, Bush urged the Soviet Union to take ``an
historic opportunity to help end the postwar division in Europe.''
   He proposed for the first time that the Soviets remove their
troops from Poland.
   Bush told the Polish reporters that in their homeland, ``there's
an historic opportunity now to help end the postwar division of
Europe.''
   Bush has promised economic incentives for Poland in response for
its recent steps toward democracy. However, he has released no
specific figures or proposals.
   His trip comes just a few days after Poland saw its Solidarity
union become the first independent opposition to enter an East bloc
legislature since the late 1940s.
   After Poland, Bush travels to Hungary, France and the Netherlands.
</TEXT>
