<FIRST>r i PM-Baker 1stLd-Writethru   07-05 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baker, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0496,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Arrives For Talks on Cambodia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 7th pvs, `In Beijing...' to CORRECT spelling of Sihanouk.
Pickup 8th pvs, `Baker and...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANDAR SERI BEGAWAN, Brunei (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A.
Baker III today arrived for talks on achieving peace in Cambodia
once Vietnam completes the scheduled withdrawal of its forces in
September.
   Baker and his colleagues from the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations are anxious to avoid an outbreak of civil war among four
contending factions in Cambodia after the Vietnamese are gone.
   Baker arrived in this tiny sultanate after a one-day visit to
Japan. He plans meetings with his colleagues from ASEAN's six member
states _ Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore and
Thailand.
   The association concluded its annual meeting Tuesday and is
comparing notes with the United States and other outside parties in
talks Thursday through Saturday.
   An ASEAN communique issued Tuesday night called for a
comprehensive settlement to the Cambodian conflict. To achieve that
goal, France has suggested a meeting among the contending factions
later this month in Paris.
   The Southeast Asian group has been active in bringing the various
Cambodian factions together for settlement talks, but it is far from
certain that goal can be achieved.
   In Beijing, Cambodian resistance leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk
today ruled out a separate peace agreement with the
Vietnamese-installed government led by Hun Sen and pledged to keep
on fighting with his Khmer Rouge allies. Hun Sen suggested that
Sihanouk return as head of state after Vietnam withdraws but
rejected Khmer Rouge participation in a new government.
   Baker and the ASEAN countries say an effort must be made to
prevent a return to power of the Khmer Rouge, whose bloody 3{-year
rule in the 1970's claimed the lives of 1 million Cambodians. The
Khmer Rouge were ousted by Vietnamese invading forces a decade ago.
   A reported Bush administration plan to provide lethal aid to
non-communist forces in Cambodia has touched off heated debate in
Congress. These forces have been receiving non-lethal U.S. aid since
1985.
   Defending the proposal for lethal aid, Rep. Stephen Solarz,
D-N.Y., chairman of the House Subcommittee on Asian Affairs, says
the Khmer Rouge could take power once again and turn Cambodia into
an ``Asian Auschwitz.''
   But Sens. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Foreign
Relations Committee, and Alan Cranston, D-Calif., have proposed
legislation to ban U.S. military aid to the non-communist factions.
   All representatives at the conference want a political settlement
in Cambodia before the Vietnamese forces pull out.
   China could play a key role in determining the outcome in
Cambodia because it is the major supplier of aid to the Khmer Rouge.
   China had been distancing itself from the Khmer Rouge, but U.S.
officials aboard Baker's plane said China's willingness to cooperate
with the ASEAN-led effort in Cambodia is less certain following the
political victory last month of hard-liners in Beijing over more
moderate forces.
   China was one of the topics of discussion between Baker and
Japanese Prime Minster Sosuke Uno in Tokyo. The two countries appear
to have much the same view of the Chinese situation.
   Both have loosened their ties with the Beijing government since
the June 3-4 crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators, but neither
plans any additional measures for the time being, according to an
official traveling with Baker.
   The official, insisting on anonymity, said Baker and Uno agreed
that despite the ``outrage'' committed by Chinese authorities, it
would be a mistake to try to isolate China from the outside world.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
