<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Strikes 1stLd-Writethru a0453 07-05 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Strikes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0453,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rail, Subway Workers Stage 24-Hour Strike, Buses Disrupted</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with British Industry estimate,
British Rail profits, other details. Pickup 6th pvs, ``London has ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hyde and Regent's parks became temporary parking
lots today as rail and subway workers again staged 24-hour strikes
and London's bus services were disrupted by a one-day walkout by
maintenance crews.
   Army teams laid metal sheeting over the grass in the two parks to
provide 7,000 extra parking spaces to ease congestion as commuters
who normally take public transportation took to their vehicles.
   Another 1,000 park-and-ride spaces were made available on
London's outskirts, but police said: ``Only drive into London if you
must.''
   Investment manager Jeremy Soutter and three colleagues traveled
to work along the River Thames straddling a 13-foot-long inflatable
tube towed by a speedboat. Their suits got a bit wet, but Soutter
said they enjoyed the meandering, seven-mile ride.
   The Confederation of British Industry estimated nearly 75 percent
of London workers showed up today.
   Many commuters booked hotels and taxis. Some companies hired
buses.
   Harrods department store postponed its summer sale for fear the
strikes would prevent shoppers getting into central London.
   State-owned British Rail announced record profits of $486 million
today, but said most of the surplus was reinvested and not used for
pay rises.
   London has been beset by 24-hour strikes on its subway system for
three months. But today was only the second time that workers on the
three major transport networks struck at once.
   The rail strike was the third one-day nationwide stoppage in
three weeks.
   Union militancy in Britain is on the upsurge following a decade
of reverses as Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative
government curbed union powers.
   On Tuesday, public services from slaughterhouses to libraries
operated by city halls were disrupted throughout Britain by a
one-day walkout over pay. The National Association of Local
Government Officers said 90 percent of its 500,000 members on city
payrolls stayed home.
   The 17-union Confederation of Shipbuilding and Engineering
Unions, meanwhile, has threatened strikes against selected companies
to demand a shorter working week and morepay for 2 million workers.
   Unions say 4,000 North Sea oil workers are involved in a dispute
over pay and safety measures, and dock workers have threatened a
national strike over government plans to abolish their long-standing
jobs-for-life guarantee.
   Strikes this year have regularly shut passport offices and
disrupted news and current affairs programs at the British
Broadcasting Corp.
   Referring to Wednesday's strikes, Mrs. Thatcher told the House of
Commons on Tuesday: ``I think the unions have given no thought to
the general public.''
   But Neil Kinnock, opposition Labor Party leader, accused
Conservatives of seeking to exploit public anger over the strikes
for their own political ends.
   Today's strike by 10,500 London subway employees was their ninth
in 13 weeks to demand extra pay for operating trains without a
guard. They want a $101 weekly increase while management has offered
$47 plus 14 days extra annual vacation, with the raise tied to
increased productivity.
   The 75,000-member National Union of Railway Workers wants a 10
percent pay increase. Management is offering 7 percent, which is
less than inflation.
</TEXT>
