<FIRST>u a PM-FiresRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0519 07-05 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fires Rdp, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0519,0770</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Residents Return to Survey Fire Damage; Acres Charred
Elsewhere</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf pvs, ``When you ...' to fix `of' to `have.'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HACIENDA HEIGHTS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents returned to their
canyon neighborhood, thankful that a wind-whipped fire that leveled
13 homes and caused an estimated $4.3 million in damage wasn't more
devastating.
   Elsewhere, crews battled forest and brush fires in mostly remote
areas of Utah, where a blaze galloped toward gas lines, and in
Colorado, Wyoming and New Mexico.
   Firefighters declared the Hacienda Heights blaze contained
Tuesday afternoon after completing a line around the smoldering
hills, said Los Angeles County Fire Department spokesman Joe Silva.
   Most of the firefighters who had battled the flames since Monday
were released, but 100 remained to hold the containment lines on the
1,500-acre blaze.
   Residents whose houses were passed over by flames hopscotching
through the neighborhood Monday returned to their homes to protect
them from looters. Four people were arrested for looting late
Monday, Silva said.
   ``I cannot believe they would want to take more from people who
already have lost almost everything,'' he said.
   Among those returning to the affluent area was George Podunovich,
who dug a shovel into what remained of his house. ``My birth
certificate, my diploma,'' he said. ``All my records _ they're
gone.''
   Also returning was Paul Lukather, who was grateful to discover
that his two-story Spanish-style house was untouched by
flames.Flames fanned by erratic winds came within 20 yards of the
house and consumed a small detached recreation room, he said.
   ``When you think what could have happened, this really was a
blessing,'' he said.
   Also returning was Don Younger, who was visiting friends on
Monday when he saw a plume of black smoke coming from his
neighborhood. When he tried to drive to his home, fire officials
would not allow him through, so he drove to a hill where he could
watch.
   ``I saw the firefighters down on their bellies saving my home. I
wish I could hug them all,'' he said.
   Authorities who surveyed the area Tuesday said 13 homes were
destroyed and eight were damaged. Losses were estimated at $4.3
million.
   Although as many as 600 people were evacuated Monday night, only
10 people spent the night at Los Altos High School, where the
American Red Cross opened an evacuation center.
   Fire officials said the cause was under investigation but was
probably man-made.
   Elsewhere in California, about 200 firefighters were dispatched
to the San Bernardino National Forest to battle a 150-acre blaze in
Santa Ana Canyon, 70 miles east of Los Angeles. It was declared 75
percent contained early today.
   In southeastern Utah, a fire about 20 miles west of the Colorado
line quadrupled in size Tuesday, consuming 7,000 acres by today in
the Flume Canyon Wilderness Study Area, said Mary Plumb of the
Bureau of Land Management.
   Plumb said that the fire, which at one point advanced two miles
in 40 minutes, was a half-mile from two gas compressor stations
owned by Northwest Pipeline and that the company was shutting down
the gas lines.
   A ranch and eight cabins were jeopardized when a 650-acre fire 20
miles north of Roosevelt grew to 1,800 acres in shifting winds, said
BLM spokesman Ray Tate. But winds died down late Tuesday, giving
fire officials time to hose down buildings and set back-burning
blazes.
   In southwestern New Mexico, a wind-driven fire charred about
5,000 acres in the Gila National Forest. More than 650 people, six
air tankers and seven helicopters fought the fire, which was started
by lightning Friday and spread by 30 mph wind.
   Fire officials earlier believed that Gila trout, which are listed
as an endangered species, were threatened by the blaze. But plans to
net the fish and take them to a hatchery were put on hold because
fire crews were able to build a buffer and protect their stream,
said Ken Palmrose, spokesman for the U.S. Forest Service.
   Several fires in Colorado had been contained or controlled, but a
fire south of Dinosaur National Monument grew to 1,800 acres and
entered the Skull Creek Wilderness Study Area.
   Officials said early today that the fire was about 70 percent
contained and they hoped to have it fully surrounded by tonight.
   Wyoming firefighters were investigating whether a fire that had
scorched 1,000 acres in the Bridger-Teton National Forest by this
morning was started by fireworks, said Forest Service spokesman Fred
Kingwill.
</TEXT>
