<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Legislature     07-05 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Legislature,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Legislature Rejects Another Cabinet Candidate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet legislators today rejected the nomination of
Nikolai S. Konarev to keep serving as minister of railways,
criticizing the safety record and shoddy service of railroads during
his administration, Tass said.
   It was the second rejection of a candidate put forth by Premier
Nikolai I. Ryzhkov in two days. On Monday, the Supreme Soviet voted
against Vladimir M. Kamentsev, who was nominated to oversee foreign
economic policy.
   ``Deputies expressed many sharp critical remarks concerning the
state of railways, traffic safety and the quality of passenger
service during the discussion of the candidate, who headed the
country's railway transport since 1982,'' the official news agency
said.
   Among the rail disasters reported under the policy of glasnost or
greater openness was an explosion that killed 600 people on June 4.
Authorities say the blast was caused by a spark from a railroad
electrical line, which ignited a highly flammable mixture of benzine
and propane-butane gas that leaked from a pipeline in the Ural
mountains near the city of Ufa.
   In May, an undisclosed number of people died when two freight
trains collided near Alma Ata, Kazakhstan, touching off an explosion.
   Last year, at least 118 people died in reported rail accidents,
including two incidents of trains carrying explosives blowing up in
rail yards.
   The vote against Konarev, who had been approved by parliamentary
committees and commissions, was 204-130, with 40 abstentions, Tass
said.
   The Supreme Soviet approved three other candidates for
ministerial posts, Tass reported.
   After a long discussion over pollution caused by the
metallurgical industry, the deputies approved the nomination of
Serafim V. Kolpakov as minister of metallurgy, Tass said.
   Since July 1985, five months after President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
came to power, Kolpakov, 56, had headed the Ferrous Metallurgy
Ministry, which was combined recently with the Ministry of
Non-Ferrous Metallurgy.
   Also approved were Boris M. Belousov, 55, as minister of defense
industries and Oleg Shishkin, 55, as minister of machine building.
   ``A long list of candidates remains to be scrutinized: there are
some 40 names on it,'' Tass said.
   Since the Supreme Soviet convened June 26, replacing the old
rubber-stamp parliament of the same name, members have questioned
most Cabinet nominees and criticized many.
   Ryzhkov withdrew the names of seven nominees last week after
unfavorable committee hearings.
</TEXT>
