<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     07-05 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Student Accused of Shootings, Arab Collaborator Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court said today that an Israeli accused of
shooting two Palestinians near Tel Aviv is a Jewish seminary student
who was freed on bail after being questioned about the slaying of an
Arab teen-ager.
   In the West Bank, Palestinians killed one Arab and tortured
another with razor blades and lighted cigarettes after accusing both
of collaborating with Israeli secret police, hospital officials and
Arab reports said.
   Arab reports today said the leader of the Palestinian Writers'
Association in the occupied lands was detained by troops for
refusing a soldier's order to paint over pro-Palestine Liberation
Organization grafitti outside his house.
   An Israeli army spokesman would not confirm or deny the reported
arrest of the official, magazine editor Assad Al-Assad.
   A Tel Aviv magistrate's court today lifted a gag order on
publishing the name of the 23-year-old Jewish settler who confessed
to shooting and wounding two Arab workers at a bus stop near Tel
Aviv on June 20.
   The settler, Rafi Solomon, was free on bail at the time after
being questioned about another shooting. Solomon said on army radio
today that he shot the two but denied taking part in other crimes.
   Solomon, who lives in the Yitzhar Jewish settlement in the West
Bank, is among eight students of Joseph's Tomb seminary arrested in
connection with an armed attack on Palestinians in the West Bank
village of Kifl Harith on May 29 in which a girl was killed and
another Palestinian wounded.
   Solomon is now in jail in connection with the shooting of the two
Arab workers. The court today extended his detention 10 days.
   Jewish settlers have been blamed for a series of raids on Arab
villages in recent weeks in apparent retaliation for stones and
firebombs thrown at their cars in the occupied lands.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, the body of Jamil Kadoumi was
found in the central market today. His skull had been crushed and
his hands were tied behind his back, the reports said. The
32-year-old man was taken from his house by masked youths overnight,
his family said.
   Doctors in a Nablus hospital said a 17-year-old, Anjad Naaneesh,
received razor cuts and cigarette burns after masked youths abducted
him from his home Tuesday night. Both his arms and legs were broken.
   The two victims were suspected of collaborating with Israel's
Shin Bet secret police, Palestinian sources said.
   The attacks in Nablus came less than a day after Palestinians
killed money-changer Khalil Ata Najar, 47, who disobeyed orders from
the underground leadership of the uprising to sell currency at a
fixed price.
   Money-changers in Nablus did not open for business today in fear
of attacks, Palestinians said.
   The deaths in Nablus brought to at least 542 the number of
Palestinians killed in the nearly 19-month uprising against Israeli
rule in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Twenty-three Israelis also
have been killed in the unrest.
</TEXT>
