<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 1201EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-ForeignMedia     07-05 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Foreign Media,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Orders Hotels to Halt Foreign News Broadcasts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has ordered major joint-venture hotels in
Beijing to unhook satellite dishes that receive foreign news
broadcasts, mainly from Cable News Network, hotel officials said
today.
   Some hotels also receive the U.S. Armed Forces Radio and
Television Service and the Japan Broadcasting Corp.
   Anyone with a satellite dish can receive the programming, and
hotels do not pay the networks or Chinese government for the service.
   An official at Beijing's Travel and Tourism Bureau said satellite
service was ordered cut because it is unfair.
   ``It is not universal in Beijing hotels. The Chinese hotels do
not have this service,'' said the official who identified himself
only as Sun.
   But Vito Maggiolo, CNN managing editor in Beijing, said: ``Our
guess is that they are concerned that the hotel staff is seeing it.''
   China is engaged in an intensive propaganda campaign to discredit
Western news accounts of a seven-week student movement for democracy
and a military crackdown on June 3-4.
   Chinese media have said nearly 100 soldiers and police died in
the crackdown and that thousands were injured, while about 100
civilians died and nearly 1,000 were injured. Chinese witnesses and
Western intelligence sources said the death toll may have been as
high as 3,000.
   Sun said the order to cut cable reception was issued in January
but was enforced only in the past few days after the government
realized hotels had not heeded the first order.
   Hotels in Shanghai and Guangzhou said they have not been ordered
to cut satellite reception.
   Beijing hotel officials agreed the government order was issued
about six months ago but said there have been no previous attempts
to enforce it.
   The Great Wall Sheraton was the first to cut its satellite
service last month. It restored the service briefly this week,
reportedly because it realized other hotels were ignoring the order,
but cut it again less than 24 hours later.
   The Jiangguo Hotel, China's first joint-venture hotel, suspended
service Friday, the day after CNN broadcast a videotape of exiled
student leader Wu'er Kaixi saying he will never give up the struggle
for democracy in China.
   A hotel circular a few days later blamed technical difficulties
for the loss of programming.
   At least four other Beijing hotels _ the Shangri-La, Palace,
Kunlun and Holiday Inn Lido _ have cut satellite service.
   Questions and complaints from hotel guests elicited a variety of
responses, from blank looks to talk of mysterious technical problems.
   ``We are upset about it. But what can we do? We have to accept
it. We cannot fight it,'' a Jianguo hotel official said on condition
of anonymity.
   Sun said hotels that refuse to follow the order will not be
punished, but added that hotels in China should obey Chinese law.
   Joint ventures in China are between the government and private
foreign companies.
</TEXT>
