<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-North     07-05 0147</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-North,150</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today refused to comment on the
sentence imposed against former White House aide Oliver North and
the White House brushed aside questions about the possibility of a
pardon.
   Bush was in a meeting with White House aides when press secretary
Marlin Fitzwater went to the Oval Office to tell him that North had
received a three-year suspended prison sentence and a $150,000 fine
for his role in covering up his involvement in the Iran-Contra
affair.
   ``He didn't have any comment,'' Fitzwater said.
   The press spokesman said ``we don't think it's appropriate'' to
comment, noting the possibility of appeal for North.
   Fitzwater said the decision not to comment was ``coming from the
president. ... I know his thoughts on this.''
   As for a pardon, Fitzwater said, ``We haven't discussed a pardon.
There's been no discussion. It hasn't ever been discussed.''
</TEXT>
