<FIRST>u a PM-WeatherpageWeather 2ndLd-Writethru a0534 07-05 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0534,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Soaks East Coast; Record Heat in The West</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with train service disrupted. PICKS
UP 5th graf pvs, `Hamilton County ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain pounded the Middle Atlantic region today, stopping trains
along Amtrak's busy Northeast corridor. The West braced for another
scorcher after Independence Day heat set records from North Dakota
to California.
   The Philadelphia area was soaked with more than 8 inches of rain
in 24 hours, with some suburbs reporting 5 to 7 inches in two hours
this morning. A street in Essington, Pa., was under 3 feet of water.
Heavy rain also fell in Maryland-Delaware area, the mountains of
Virginia and the central Gulf Coast.
   Water rushed over tracks along several sections of Amtrak's line
between Washington and New York. Some trains were canceled and
others had to reverse direction and return to the station.
Passengers were bused between stations.
   Trains ordinarily leave Washington and New York every half hour,
carrying about 20,000 passengers a day.
   On Tuesday, showers and thunderstorms drenched much of the
Atlantic and Gulf coasts, flooding roads and swelling rivers and
streams.
   Hamilton County, Tenn., was pelted with 1.35 inches of rain in 40
minutes; 1{ inches of rain fell in two hours in New Paris, Pa.; 6\
inches poured down on Grandfather Mountain in North Carolina in a
24-hour period.
   Flash flood watches were in effect this morning for most of
Virginia and Maryland and parts of North Carolina, West Virginia and
Pennsylvania.
   Lakes and rivers continued to flood in Louisiana because of heavy
rains during the past week. Four feet of water covered about five
miles of Highway 9, which was closed between Campti and Creston.
   A large upper-level high pressure system brought record heat from
the upper Mississippi Valley across the Plains to California.
   It was 121 degrees at Blythe, Calif., and the 118-degree high in
Phoenix broke a 17-year-old mark for the date. Record highs also
were recorded at Tucson, Ariz.; Jamestown, N.D. and Laramie, Wyo.
Heat records for the date were tied in Duluth, Minn., and Salt Lake
City.
   The forecast Wednesday was for scattered showers and
thunderstorms from much of the Atlantic Coast across the
Appalachians into the Tennessee and lower Mississippi valleys, with
strong thunderstorms from North Dakota to northern Minnesota.
   Predicted highs: 70s across northern Maine; 70s and 80s in the
northern Rockies and Pacific Northwest; 80s in much of the
Southeast, the Great Lakes and northern Atlantic Coast; above 90 in
southern Georgia and Florida, from the upper Mississippi Valley
across the Plains, and from the central and southern Rockies to
inland California; and over 100 from the Rio Grande Valley into
southern California; and 110 to 120 in the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 49
degrees at Yellowstone, Wyo., and Olympia, Wash., to 97 at Glendale,
Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 71 foggy; Boston 68 foggy; Buffalo 69 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 74 fair; Cincinnati 70 foggy; Cleveland 68 foggy;
Detroit 68 foggy; Miami 75 cloudy; New York 72 partly cloudy;
Philadelphia 72 cloudy; Pittsburgh 69 foggy; Portland, Maine 63
foggy; Washington 74 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 84 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 77 foggy; Denver 78
fair; Des Moines 71 fair; Indianapolis 71 foggy; Kansas City 71
fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 75 fair; Nashville 70 foggy; New Orleans
71 foggy; St. Louis 75 hazy.
   _West: Albuquerque 76 fair; Anchorage 51 partly cloudy; Las Vegas
87 fair; Los Angeles 66 fair; Phoenix 95 fair; Salt Lake City 69
fair; San Diego 67 fair; San Francisco 55 fair; Seattle 54 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 70 cloudy; Toronto 68 foggy.
</TEXT>
