<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--Train-CraneAccident     07-05 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Train-Crane Accident,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>TA Employee Injured When Crane Hits Subway Train</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crane operator was knocked to the ground and
critically injured Wednesday when the counterweight of his crane
smashed a hole in a passing subway train, authorities said.
   Frank Davila, 54, of the borough of Queens, was in critical,
guarded condition at Kings County Hospital, said a hospital
spokeswoman, Lucille Parris. Transit Authority officials said he
suffered head and hand injuries.
   No other injuries were reported.
   The crane, a light piece of equipment that can ride on the rails
or on the street, was operating on one subway track adjacent to
another in Brooklyn when the accident occurred about 10 a.m., said
Bob Previdi, a Transit Authority spokesman.
   The counterweight, the backside of the crane's arm, struck the
train and ``it punched a hole 4 feet wide and 1 foot deep into the
train,'' said another TA spokesman, Jared Lebow. Davila suffered his
injuries when he was knocked to the ground.
</TEXT>
