<SECOND>PM-Washington Fourth, 1st Ld Writethru, a0432,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Shot During Firewords Show on Washington Mall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graph with injuries and conditions. Picks up 3rd
graph, Police were. ^By JENICE ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police are investigating the shooting of two
persons on the Washington Monument grounds during a Fourth of July
fireworks display that drew about 425,000 people.
   Authorities said Stephen Hill, 17, was taken to the Washington
Hospital Center with a gunshot wound to the buttocks, while
Dahkishan Rollins, 15, was taken to Children's National Medical
Center with a gunshot wound to the knee. Both were from Landover, Md.
   Police were searching for five to eight male teen-agers believed
to have been involved in the shooting, said Park Police Sgt. Robert
Kass.
   Several people were trampled in the incident, said district
police spokesman Sgt. Joe Gentile. They were treated at the scene
for minor injuries.
   The annual fireworks show had been in doubt for most of the day
because of rain, and only about 20,000 people attended the
traditional parade down Constitution Avenue on Tuesday afternoon.
   However, the rain let up in time to permit the fireworks, which
were the finale to an outdoor concert by the National Symphony
Orchestra on the Capitol grounds at the other end of the Mall.
   Altogether, police reported about a dozen arrests Tuesday, mostly
for disorderly conduct and vending violations.
   The sparse parade crowd was cheerful about the weather, donning
plastic sheeting, umbrellas and makeshift trashbag ponchos to watch
the marching bands and floats go by.
   ``Everybody was smiling and being more congenial because we had
the bad weather as a common denominator,'' said John Shaw, who came
from Augusta, Maine, with his wife Sue.
   Street vendors were less pleased.
   David Gomez, who came from Atlanta to sell plastic American flags
which he carted around on two wooden placards, said, ``It's not as
many people as I'd like to be out here.'' It took him two hours to
sell 10 flags.
</TEXT>
