<FIRST>u a AM-MigrantHousing Bjt   07-05 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Migrant Housing, Bjt,0723</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farm Workers Find Housing Shortage In Crookston</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FO1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF MEYER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CROOKSTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Migrant farm workers, drawn by the hope
of work and good pay, have poured into the Red River Valley this
year in what may be record numbers, but what they've found is a
shortage of work and housing.
   ``We enjoy coming here,'' said Gracie Gallegos, who augments her
salary as a school secretary in Crystal Springs, Texas, by working
two to three weeks each summer in the Minnesota sugar beet fields.
   ``We have bills to pay like everybody else. But it's sad this
year because we've had so much difficulty finding a home.''
   City officials acknowledge the housing market is tight. But they
say providing new housing is beyond the community's means and will
require state and federal assistance.
   ``We have neither the resources nor the inclination to build
housing for transients ... (housing) that would only be occupied for
a few months each year,'' said Mike McDonald, city zoning
administrator. ``It would be unfair to local residents to pay for
such housing.''
   In the meantime, migrant workers overwhelm a homeless shelter
operated by Sister Justina Violette, who believes the city is not
doing enough to provide affordable housing for migrants and other
low-income people who stay in the area from May through July. This
year, they began arriving in March.
   As many as 70 migrants spend the night in the crowded shelter,
and another 20 sleep in a 16- by 32-foot army tent on the lawn
outside. Others sleep in their cars and pickups in the center's
parking lot and some sleep under trees in an adjacent city park.
   Gallegos, 40, and her family have been coming to the Crookston
area for 35 years and have never had difficulty finding a home to
rent. This year they were forced to seek shelter at Sister Justina's
center.
   Migrant workers, mostly Hispanic Texans, have been making the
1,500-mile trek to the Red River Valley and this northwestern
Minnesota town of about 8,500 for decades. They are paid to thin and
weed sugar beets that are grown for local processing plants. Workers
can earn as much as $90 a day.
   But farmers use mechanical thinners now, and chemicals are
replacing labor for controlling weeds, said Armando Cuellar, migrant
labor counselor for the Minnesota Department of Jobs and Training.
   That means less demand for workers, except in a drought year like
last season when chemicals did not work as well. Last year's high
demand may have lured migrants to the valley this year with false
hopes, Cuellar said.
   As many as 5,000 workers this year are in the valley in Minnesota
and North Dakota, said Richard Fitzsimons, executive director of the
Red River Valley Sugarbeet Growers Association.
   About 1,900 people looking for work have registered with the
Department of Jobs and Training in Crookston and East Grand Forks,
Cuellar said. Last year at this time, 600 to 800 workers had signed
up. Cuellar was unable to estimate how many migrants would be able
to find steady work.
   ``I've been here 13 years and this is the most (available) labor
I've had,'' Cuellar said. ``This is an unusual year ... the
chemicals have worked very well because the weather has been
perfect. That's meant less field work.''
   In the past, growers provided housing for the workers on their
farmsteads.
   However, strict new federal regulations have made that more
difficult in recent years, leaving migrants with nowhere else to go
but into the communities.
   Sister Justina accuses some Crookston residents of being
prejudiced in their treatment of the Hispanic workers. She notes
some landlords require large damage deposits and longterm rental
contracts for migrants.
   ``People in small towns are used to seeing only one color,'' she
said. ``I don't think they realize how beautiful a rainbow is. The
minute they see someone of a different color they look down on
them.''
   McDonald said he does not see the problem as being racial in
nature.
   ``This never was a racial issue,'' he said. ``I see it as a group
issue. We've got a large number of people coming into a system that
is ill-equipped to deal with them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
