<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Politics 2ndLd-Writethru   07-05 0850</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Politics, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0567,a0573,a0575,0873</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Shamir Accepts Conditions On Election Plan For Occupied Lands</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines urgent series. Raises higher Shamir's demand that settlements
continue, elements of the original election plan, PLO reaction. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir today
turned back a challenge to his leadership by hard-liners in the
Likud bloc who opposed his election plan for peace negotiations.
   But in reaching a compromise, Shamir accepted the positions of
his rivals and may have burdened his Middle East peace initiative
with conditions that make it unacceptable to Palestinians.
   In a rousing speech before the party's central committee, Shamir
endorsed opponents' demands that east Jerusalem Arabs be excluded
from voting and that the violence of the Palestinian uprising be
ended as a pre-condition for peace negotiations. He also pledged to
continue Jewish settlements and said Israel would not accept a
Palestinian state or the participation of the PLO.
   Moshe Katzav, a Shamir backer, said the compromise was to include
the principles in the speech without voting on amendments to put the
hard-line stands into the peace initiative.
   But Trade Minister Ariel Sharon, who had led the opposition, said
on Israel radio after the meeting: ``This decision is binding on the
representatives of the Likud in the Cabinet.''
   The plan was approved 20-6 on May 14 by the coalition Cabinet,
which includes the left-of-center Labor Party.
   The compromise was a victory for Shamir, who had threatened to
resign if the rebel faction voted against his plan.
   But it may have limited his room for maneuver in future
negotiations. Shamir's policy speech, which included four points
demanded by the rebels, was adopted with an overwhelming show of
hands in support.
   Officials have said the peace plan's lack of specifics was
designed to appeal to Palestinians by leaving controversial points
to later negotiations.
   But the points raised in Shamir's speech, especially his pledge
to continue Jewish settlements and exclude east Jerusalem Arabs,
were certain to alienate Palestinians.
   ``The settlements will continue,'' said Shamir, rebuffing U.S.
requests that Jewish settlements are an obstacle to peace. ``I want
to send heartfelt, warm blessings to settlers in Judea, Samaria
(West Bank) and Gaza, and I tell you, your suffering is not in vain
... be strong.''
   The election plan, which has U.S. support, calls for choosing
Palestinians in the occupied lands to negotiate an autonomy plan
with Israel. After three years, separate talks would be held on the
final status of the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Palestinians and the
PLO have criticized the proposal, saying it does not lead to their
goal of an independent state.
   Demanding an end to the Palestinian uprising, Shamir said:
``There will be no negotiations as long as there is violence ... We
shall wipe it out.''
   The nearly 19-month uprising has led to the deaths of more than
540 Palestinians and 23 Israelis.
   Bending to the demand of his rivals that Arab east Jerusalem not
be allowed to vote in the elections, Shamir said: ``Jerusalem is not
part of the initiative. Jerusalem is the eternal capital of our
people and our state.''
   A key Palestinian demand has been giving the vote to 140,000 Arab
residents in the city's eastern sector, which was captured from
Jordan in the 1967 Middle East War.
   Shamir drew loud applause and chants when he called on the United
States to end its dialogue with PLO leaders, who he said ``have not
deviated one inch from their criminal ways.''
   Chaim Morad, a Sharon backer, said the challenge was meant to
ensure Shamir will not be pushed by the United States into making
too many compromises to achieve peace. ``The prime minister is being
pushed too far to the left,'' he said. ``We want him to be able to
stand up to the Americans and say: `I can't do any more. My party
won't let me.'''
   Shamir's media adviser, Yossi Ahimeir, said the prime minister's
plan was intended to outmaneuver his rivals by making his speech the
issue of the vote, thus avoiding a direct challenge to the peace
plan.
   Since introducing the elections proposal in April, Shamir has
repeatedly said he would not give up land in the occupied West Bank
and Gaza or agree to negotiate with the PLO.
   But he had also insisted on no changes in his election plan.
   The United States has supported the plan as a way of getting the
stalled Middle East peace process moving and has tried to sell the
plan to the PLO and Arab states.
   But Secretary of State James A. Baker III has called on Israel to
accept the U.S.-backed policy of trading land for peace as a way of
persuading the Palestinians to agree to the vote.
   Before today's committee vote, Avi Pazner, Shamir's spokeman,
said that the challenge was serious. ``It is a real political test
for Shamir and his peace plan. One goes with the other,'' Pazner
said in an interview.
   Aides said privately that a vote against Shamir could have
jeopardized the plan and forced Shamir to resign.
</TEXT>
