<FIRST>r a PM-CoalStrike 1stLd-Writethru a0473 07-05 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coal Strike, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0473,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede ST. PAUL, Va.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Judge Slaps Union With More Fines; Explosion Hits Warehouse</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with additional fines, explosion at warehouse.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABINGDON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today fined the United Mine
Workers and two union officers an additional $720,000 for violating
his ban on forming convoys to slow down trucks delivering coal.
   Also today, an explosion damaged a McClure warehouse owned by the
strikebound Pittston Coal Group, State Police said. No injuries were
reported.
   It was not clear whether whether the 2:30 a.m. blast was related
to the four-month strike against the company by 1,900 miners in
Virginia, West Virginia and Kentucky. Police said the explosion was
under investigation.
   U.S. District Judge Glen Williams on June 26 fined the UMW and
two officers $240,000 for organizing convoys of cars and trucks to
block coal traffic, and threatened fines of $120,000 for each day
the traffic jams continued.
   Williams said the union violated his order for six days with
bumper-to-bumper traffic on roads used by coal haulers. Most of
those in the convoys have been UMW members from other states on
sympathy wildcat strikes.
   State Police Special Agent Larry Waddell testified that troopers
wrote nearly 200 tickets for impeding traffic last week.
   ``Despite all the massive ticketing, it's all just sort of
whistling Dixie,'' the judge said. He raised the daily fine to
$550,000 for further violations.
   UMW attorney Mike Passino said the union will appeal the fines,
which now total $960,000. Jackie Stump, president of the union's
Virginia district, said the fines are excessive.
   On Tuesday, the union garnered support from United Farm Workers'
President Cesar Chavez.
   ``Your struggle is our struggle,'' Chavez told more than 5,000
striking miners and supporters at a rally. ``And your victory is our
victory and victory for every worker in this country.''
   Chavez said the UMW's commitment to non-violence during the
strike and the use of civil disobedience has captured the attention
of organized labor.
   ``People know about it in the workplace, even on the West
Coast,'' he said of the labor dispute that began April 5. The public
and all organized labor will be on the UMW's side as long as
non-violent tactics persist, Chavez said.
   Pittston miners had been working without a contract for 14 months
when they went on strike over wages, benefits and working
conditions. The walkout has spawned sympathy strikes by 37,000
miners in the Midwest and Appalachia.
   Pittston President Michael Odom said the company is feeling no
pressure to return to the bargaining table. The sympathy strikes in
have ``zero effect on us,'' Odom said. He added that Pittston
continues to operate with replacements.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
