<FIRST>r a AM-LouisianaAbortion     07-05 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Louisiana Abortion,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislature Goes Into Session But Abortion Not On Agenda</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Fla Abortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Louisiana Legislature, where
anti-abortion sentiment is overwhelming, went into special session
Wednesday, but abortion failed to make the agenda because of the
state's financial problems.
   Gov. Buddy Roemer refused to amend his instructions for the
six-day tax session to include abortion in light of Monday's U.S.
Supreme Court decision that allows states to place more restrictions
on abortions.
   He said there was too little time to deal with the subject but
said he wants legislative committees to look at possible revision of
the state's laws.
   In Florida, Gov. Bob Martinez said Wednesday he will call a
special legislative session to consider legislation further
restricting abortions.
   Louisiana's anti-abortion forces are so strong that the state is
expected to be among the first to tackle new abortion legislation.
   Rep. Alphonse Jackson, a Democrat and a pro-choice leader,
predicted that anti-abortion forces will be able to pass anything
they want.
   ``There is no question that the pro-life forces are in charge of
this Legislature,'' Jackson said. ``They will prevail.''
   Louisiana has laws similar to the ones in Missouri that the
Supreme Court upheld on Monday, blocking the use of state money or
faciliites for abortions.
   Unlike Missouri's laws, however, the ones in Louisiana remained
in effect during the challenge in Washington, so no abortions were
performed at the state's charity hospitals or by state employees.
   Since the Supreme Court's 1973 Roe vs. Wade ruling legalizing
abortions, Louisiana has passed stacks of restrictive legislation,
but only one other law has stood the constitutional test. It
requires that parents be notified if their children try to obtain
abortions.
   Louisiana also passed a provision that all pre-1973 laws, making
abortions criminal, go back on the books if the Supreme Court ever
reverses Roe v. Wade.
   Jackson, chairman of the House committee that would hear abortion
bills, said the abortion issue cannot come up until the 1990 regular
session unless the governor calls another special session.
   ``There are no plans for that,'' said P.J. Mills, the governor's
chief of staff. ``He would do so if there was a public necessity.''
</TEXT>
