<FIRST>u i PM-Peru-Soviets 1stLd-Writethru   07-05 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Peru-Soviets, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0557,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>20 Soviets Injured When Bomb Explodes Under Tour Bus</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads throughout to UPDATE with 20 injured, police saying bomb
placed under bus. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded today under a tour bus carrying
sailors of the Soviet fishing fleet, injuring 20 of the fishermen
and damaging two other buses with Soviet visitors, police said.
   The explosion occurred when the fishermen were boarding the bus
after shopping in a Lima suburb, police and witnesses told radio
stations.
   No group claimed responsibility for the bombing, but police
blamed the Maoist Shining Path guerrillas group, which has targeted
Soviet citizens and diplomats in the past.
   Gen. Oswaldo Diaz Salvador, Lima police chief, said two young men
carefully placed a package under the bus and then raced off as the
bomb exploded.
   Bomb experts said the explosion was caused by about 12 pounds of
dynamite. Two other buses with Soviet fishermen aboard were damaged
by the explosion, which occurred at 10 a.m., police said.
   Eight of the 20 sailors were seriously injured, police said.
Witnesses said the explosion maimed the sailors' legs and lower
bodies.
   Diaz Salvador said the bombed bus was carrying 49 people when the
attack occurred and 35 sailors were on two smaller buses. The buses
were owned by a tourism service.
   In 1986, a guerrilla was killed after breaking into the grounds
of the Soviet Embassy when the bomb he was carrying exploded.
   Also in 1986, several Soviet fishermen were injured when a bomb
went off in a store frequented by the sailors in the port city of
Callao.
   Lima is a resupply point for the Soviet fishing fleet operating
off the west coast of South America.
   The Shining Path views the Soviet government as traitors to true
Marxism and regards the Soviets as enemies because they have been a
major supplier of arms to Peru for the two decades. More than 15,000
people have been killed in Peru's nine-year guerrilla insurgency.
</TEXT>
