<FIRST>r w AM-Namibia     07-05 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>US State Department Registers Concerns Over Reports of SWAPO Torture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Wednesday it was
deeply concerned about allegations that Namibia's guerrilla movement
tortured prisoners and said it had asked for an accounting from
neighboring African governments.
   Some of the 150 people freed after years of imprisonment said
many others were tortured and beaten to death while held in
underground pits in neighboring Angola. They said they were among
thousands of dissidents imprisoned by the South-West Africa People's
Organization (SWAPO) during its guerrilla war for independence from
South Africa.
   The State Department has been in the forefront of pushing for
independence for the territory. Elections are scheduled in November.
   Several freed prisoners estimated SWAPO still holds more than
2,000 detainees.
   Guerrilla leaders say they held just 201 dissidents and have
released them all. The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugeees says it
accepts the SWAPO figures, although a relatives' committee in
Namibia has given U.N. officers the names of more than 300 missing
SWAPO members.
   Asked about the situation, Richard Boucher, a State Department
spokesman, said: ``We are deeply concerned about the allegations of
mistreatment of Namibians by SWAPO. We've asked for a full
accounting of the status of all detainees.''
   Boucher said two U.N. groups were investigating.
   ``We have raised the question of accounting for all SWAPO
detainees with several countries in the region and have asked them
to use their influence with SWAPO to ensure the safe repatriation of
all SWAPO detainees to Namibia,'' the U.S. official said.
   ``We again call upon the concerned parties and governments to
encourage SWAPO to make a full accounting of the detainees.''
   Boucher said the State Department was not dealing directly with
SWAPO, the major black nationalist group in Namibia and likely to
take control of the emerging nation.
</TEXT>
