<SECOND>PM-Amtrak-Rain, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0537,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heavy Rains Disrupt Amtrak Service In Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: TOP 8 grafs new with some service resuming; picks up 7th graf,
He said.    By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rains disrupted Amtrak passenger service
along the railroad's busy northeast corridor today, requiring busing
and long delays that affected nearly 10,000 passengers, a spokesman
said.
   Engineers opened a single track north of Wilmington, Del., in
early afternoon after all three tracks through the area were flooded
for several hours, said spokesman Cliff Black. The other tracks
would have to be repaired, he said.
   Trains were creeping through the area 1{ miles north of
Wilmington at 5 mph, and Metroliner express service between
Washington and New York was cancelled between 11 a.m. and 2 p.m.,
Black said. The Metroliner normally runs every hour from both New
York and Washington, traveling through Philadelphia, Wilmington and
Baltimore.
   Service was being resumed with the 3 p.m. trains, but delays of
about a half-hour were expected through the rest of the day, Black
said.
   ``Travel in that whole area is badly snarled and Amtrak train
operations severly disrupted,'' the spokesman said shortly before
noon.
   Later, he said the rains had abated and the single track was
re-opened. Black said 20 trains were either delayed or canceled,
affecting 10,000 passengers.
   Special buses set up to carry passengers between Wilmington and
Philadelphia and between Wilmington and Baltimore also had
difficulty because of flooding on roads near the tracks, he said.
   The normally 25-minute trip between Wilmington and Philadelphia
was taking more than two hours, Black said.
   He said several trains have had to reverse direction and return
to the stations they left, including two in Baltimore, several in
Philadelphia and one at Wilmington.
   In some cases, a train was turned around and replaced for another
train that was supposed to go in the opposite direction, picking up
bused passengers, he said.
   There was no service between Philadelphia and Wilmington for
several hours, and trouble also spread south of Wilmington, he said.
   He said water covered all three tracks just north of Wilmington,
and trains carrying crushed stones were standing by to repair
roadbeds if necessary.
</TEXT>
