<HEAD>4 Killed During Police Raid Near U.S. Ambassador's Residence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers raided an apartment Wednesday
near the home of the U.S. ambassador, and police said four people
were killed in grenade blasts and gunfire.
   No U.S. Marines guarding the residence of U.S. Ambassador Thomas
McNamara fired their weapons and no one at the embassy or residence
was hurt, said embassy spokesman Steven Gangstead.
   McNamara had left for Miami before the raid took place, an
immigration officer at the El Dorado International Airport told
Bogota radio station RCN. McNamara would not comment on the report.
   Soldiers had arrived in front of an apartment building a block
from the ambassador's residence to raid an apartment when someone on
the seventh floor began firing at the troops, according to a major
with the national police.
   The soldiers, armed with submachine guns, returned the fire, the
major told RCN. The major identified himself only by his last name,
Villamil.
   It was not known if the four people reported dead were in the
apartment being raided.
   Colombia is under a state of siege because of activity by leftist
guerrillas and drug traffickers. This gives the armed forces
authority to arrest civilians.
