<FIRST>r a AM-Misty'sHeir     07-05 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Misty's Heir,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Filly Joins `Misty of Chincoteague' Family</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANHEIM, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black Mist is just a pony, but her owners say
she is a bit of history.
   Her mother, Misty II, is a granddaughter of Misty, a wild
Assateague Island pony immortalized in Marguerite Henry's 1947
children's book ``Misty of Chincoteague.''
   That book and its sequel, ``Stormy, Misty's Foal,'' concern the
wild horses on Assateague and Chincoteague islands off the coast of
Maryland.
   Misty II, now 15, gave birth June 17 to her fifth foat, Black
Mist, at Keith and Kendy Allen's farm near Manheim in Lancaster
County.
   The Allens say Misty II and her new foal will never leave their
farm.
   Mrs. Allen said she takes Misty II to area elementary schools,
and said she gets mail addressed to ``Misty II, R.D. 4, Manheim.''
   Black Mist could not be named Misty III because she doesn't carry
the original Misty's distinctive marking, a spot shaped like a map
of the United States on one flank.
   The original Misty died in 1972.
   The Allens have vowed to carry on the Misty line.
   Black Mist's sire is a 34-year-old Chincoteague pony named Rebel.
   ``We called his owners that morning and they and some of their
friends had a celebration,'' she said. ``They made his favorite food
_ blueberry pancakes _ in honor of the baby.''
</TEXT>
