<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-North     07-05 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-North,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Declines Comment On Oliver North</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-North,Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush refused to comment Wednesday on
the sentencing of former National Security Council aide Oliver
North, and the White House said the possibility of granting him a
pardon had not been discussed.
   Bush learned of the sentencing shortly after North had received a
three-year suspended prison term and a $150,000 fine for his role in
the Iran-Contra affair.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said he informed
Bush about North's sentence at the end of a meeting in the Oval
Office.
   ``He didn't have any comment,'' Fitzwater said.
   Bush, who returned to the White House after a five-day stay at
his vacation home in Kennebunkport, Maine, spent the day at the
White House in meetings with aides. He also had his weekly luncheon
with Vice President Dan Quayle.
   During the day, Bush made no appearances where reporters could
ask him about North.
   Fitzwater said the White House would not comment on the
sentencing. ``We don't think it's appropriate,'' he said, noting
later that North had the right to appeal his conviction.
   Pressed on why there was no comment, Fitzwater said, ``That's
coming from the president. ... I know his thoughts on this matter.
   As for a presidential pardon for North, Fitzwater said, ``We
haven't discussed a pardon. There's been no discussion. It hasn't
ever been discussed.''
</TEXT>
