<FIRST>r a AM-CruseSentencing 1stLd-Writethru a0595 07-05 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cruse Sentencing, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0595,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shopping Center Killer Back in Court</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to update with Cruse's first public comments,
picking up at the 4th graf previous, `The judge...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MELBOURNE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In his first public show of remorse, a
convicted killer told a judge Wednesday he was sorry for the 1987
shooting rampage that killed six people and wounded 10 at two Palm
Bay shopping plazas.
   ``I'm sorry that all this happened,'' William Bryan Cruse sobbed.
   ``Anything else?'' prompted Circuit Judge John Antoon, who had
said he wanted to hear from Cruse before drafting a sentencing order.
   ``That's all that I can say,'' Cruse added as he choked back
tears.
   The brief exchange came at the end of a 3{-hour hearing at which
lawyers for both sides argued for and against imposition of the
death penalty, which was recommended by the jury that convicted
Cruse.
   The alternative is a sentence of life in prison without parole
for at least 25 years. Formal sentencing for the 61-year-old former
librarian is July 28.
   ``The judge is being supercautious in this case of mass murder,''
said State Attorney Norm Wolfinger. ``He is protecting the record,
getting everything down ... and frankly asking for assistance in
writing his order.''
   Cruse was convicted April 5 of 32 counts of murder, attempted
murder and kidnapping.
   Cruse sat quietly at the defense table. He has been held in the
Brevard County Jail since the morning after the rampage on April 23,
1987.
   His temporary insanity defense was rejected by the jury but he
has been diagnosed as mentally ill. While this in itself is not a
trial defense under Florida law, Cruse lawyers argue it should be a
major factor in deciding whether he should be executed or imprisoned.
   But chief trial prosecutor Chris White argued the ``net result of
his mental illness'' was limited to his belief that other people
considered him a homosexual.
   ``He appreciated what he was doing, the consequences of what he
was doing and that it was wrong,'' White said in summing up the
state's arguments that Cruse should be electrocuted.
   The shootings were part of a cold, calculating, premeditated
plan, and were carried out in heinous, atrocious and cruel fashion,
White said.
   Assistant Public Defender Marlene Alva said there was ``evidence
that he suffered from a mental illness, and part of that was the
belief that people were out to malign him ... that he felt morally
justified because of his twisted and psychotic mind.''
   She argued that Cruse's actions were the result of a boiling-over
of pent-up resentments and emotions rather than ``a master plan
against Palm Bay.''
   Cruse bought guns and ammunition but did not know his victims,
Ms. Alva noted.
   And, she added, shooting people is not heinous, atrocious and
cruel under the law.
   ``The state is asking the court to find that these victims
suffered great pain ... there is no evidence of that,'' she said.
</TEXT>
