<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 1625EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Scotus-DeathAppeal     07-05 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Death Appeal,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justices Will Use Arkansas Case to Rule on State Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court will use the case of a
convicted Arkansas mass murderer who says he is ready to die to
decide whether state appeals courts must review all death sentences.
   The court has agreed to review an appeal in behalf of R. Gene
Simmons, sentenced to die for killing 16 relatives and acquaintances
in 1987.
   The justices took the action Monday in the wind-up to their
current term, but the announcement went largely unnoticed as the
court ruled in a key abortion dispute and also decided an important
church-state controversy.
   The court will hear arguments in the Simmons case in its next
term, which begins in October. A ruling is likely in 1990.
   Simmons has said he wants his death sentence carried out.
   ``I only ask for what I deserve. Let the torture and suffering
end. Please allow me the right to be at peace,'' he said.
   After a judge determined Simmons was mentally competent to waive
his right to appeal, the Rev. Louis Franz asked the Arkansas Supreme
Court to block the execution.
   The state Supreme Court said Franz, who ministers to Arkansas
death row inmates, lacked legal standing to make the appeal in
Simmons' behalf.
   The state court also said Simmons ``understands the choice of
life and death and has made a knowing and intelligent waiver of his
right to appeal.''
   Three days before Simmons was to be executed last March 16,
another Arkansas death row inmate, Jonas H. Whitmore, asked the
state court to spare Simmons. The request was denied.
   On the eve of Simmons' scheduled execution, the U.S. Supreme
Court granted Whitmore's emergency request to spare Simmons in order
to give the high court time to decide whether it would review the
case.
   In his appeal to the high court acted on Monday, Whitmore said
the Constitution's ban on cruel and unusual punishment requires a
state appellate court to review all capital cases, even when the
defendant has asked to die.
   Lawyers for Whitmore said Arkansas is alone among the 37 states
with the death penalty in not requiring mandatory appellate review.
   If the justices rule for Whitmore, Arkansas will have to join the
other states. If he loses, other states would be free to abandon
mandatory appellate review.
   Whitmore's lawyers noted that Utah added a requirement for such
review after Gary Gilmore was executed in 1977. Gilmore, who did not
challenge his death sentence, was the first person executed in the
United States since the Supreme Court reinstated capital punishment
in 1976.
   Lawyers representing Simmons asked the high court to reject
Whitmore's appeal.
   ``With all due respect, .... society demands that capital
punishment be enforced fairly and expeditiously or ... be abolished
in its entirety,'' they said.
   Among Simmons' victims were Kathy Kendrick, 24, who was shot to
death at a Russellville, Ark., law office on Dec. 28, 1987.
   Police said she had spurned Simmons' advances more than a year
earlier when both worked at a motor freight office.
   In what prosecutors called a murderous rampage through the
college town of Russellville, Simmons shot four others on Dec. 28,
one fatally.
   After arresting Simmons, police went to his home in nearby Dover
and found the bodies of Simmons' wife, their three sons, four
daughters, a son-in-law, a daughter-in-law and four grandchildren.
   Seven of the bodies were found in a shallow grave near the house,
two in plastic bags in the trunks of abandoned cars and five in the
house.
   The case is Whitmore vs. Arkansas, 88-7146.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890705-0096 </DOCNO>
