<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     07-05 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Imposes Censorship on Local Journalists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sri Lanka on Wednesday banned local
journalists from writing anti-government articles, and an official
linked the order to newspaper reports predicting a military takeover.
   The censorship rules will not apply to foreign correspondents,
according to a Department of Information statement that gave few
details, other than to say President Ranasinghe Premadasa has
appointed four government officials as censors.
   A senior government official linked the censorship to reports on
an ongoing transport workers' strike believed instigated by
Sinhalese extremists.
   The decision was taken, he said, after ``several anti-government
reports appeared in newspapers saying the transport strike had
crippled the government and that a military takeover was on the
cards.''
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
censors will stop publication mainly of articles about the strike,
about violence by Sinhalese extremists and current peace
negotiations between the government and separatist Tamil rebels.
   He did not name offending newspapers, but at least one Sinhala
language daily, The Dinerasea, has severely criticized the
government's handling of the strike and peace negotiations. It is
published by the opposition Sri Lanka Freedom Party.
   Journalists last were censored in July 1983 when ethnic violence
between the Buddhist Sinhalese and mostly Hindu Tamils claimed
hundreds of lives.
   The strike for higher wages by about 50,000 workers of
state-owned transport services has spread among other workers and is
paralyzing the island nation.
   Two weeks ago, Premadasa imposed a nationwide state of emergency
to crush the strike, which his government blames on ultranationalist
Sinhalese.
   The government also blames the extremists, from the left-wing
People's Liberation Front, for assassinations of 3,500 government
workers and ruling party officials and supporters in a two-year
campaign to protest peace overtures to the minority Tamils who
dominate the northeast.
   The biggest Tamil rebel group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam, last week agreed to a cease-fire and peace talks.
   This week, the government postponed until Jan. 29 a referendum on
whether the northern and eastern provinces should merge.
   It was scheduled for Wednesday in Eastern Province, which has
many ethnic groups. Tamils say both provinces form the traditional
Tamil homeland.
   The postponement was requested by the Tamil Tigers and the Tamil
group that has run the provincial government since it accepted
limited autonomy in exchange for ending the rebellion. The Tamil
Tigers still want an independent homeland.
   Tamils comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and
accuse the majority Sinhalese of discriminating against them.
   At least 9,000 people have been killed in the six-year war.
</TEXT>
