<SECOND>AM-BRF--Marine Shooting,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marine Guard Shot in Bizarre Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Marine standing guard in a nuclear
weapons compound was accidentally shot to death by a fellow guard,
according to officials at Cecil Field Naval Air Station.
   The second guard was treated for shock and remained hospitalized
Wednesday.
   The shooting occurred Tuesday afternoon at the Yellow Water
Weapons Storage Area where 140 nuclear missiles are believed to be
stored. The Navy refuses to comment on the location of nuclear
weapons.
   ``Preliminary information ... is that one shot was fired,'' said
Bert Byers, a spokesman for Cecil Field. The weapon used was a 9mm
pistol, the weapon commonly issued to the base's Marine security
staff.
   Detectives from the Naval Investigative Service were treating the
shooting as an accident, Byers said.
   Navy officials refused to discuss how many guards were on duty in
the area, citing security concerns. The names of the men were
withheld until their families could be notified.
