<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 1631EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     07-05 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administrator Won't Release Prisoners Until He's Sure SWAPO Has</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa's territorial administrator
said Wednesday he won't free about 30 political prisoners until he
is sure Namibia's guerrilla movement has released all its detainees.
   More than 150 people detained by the South-West Africa People's
Organization returned home from Angola on Tuesday and said more than
2,000 others still are held under harsh conditions in guerrilla
camps in Angola, Tanzania and Zambia.
   Administrator-General Louis Pienaar ``is determined to ascertain
if all SWAPO dissidents will be released before he will release
political detainees here,'' said Pienaar's spokesman, Eberhard
Hofmann.
   SWAPO says it has released all 201 of its prisoners, whom it
accused of spying for Pretoria during its 23-year bush war to end
South African administration.
   The State Department said Wednesday it is asking concerned
countries to help account for SWAPO detainees.
   Spokesman Richard Boucher said: ``We are deeply concerned about
the allegations of mistreatment of Namibians by SWAPO.
   ``We have raised the question of accounting for all SWAPO
detainees with several countries in the region, and have asked them
to use their influence with SWAPO to ensure the safe repatriation of
all SWAPO detainees.''
   Boucher said two U.N. groups are investigating the claims. Some
Namibians say U.N. officials are reluctant to follow up allegations
against SWAPO.
   Andreas Shipanga, a politician and former SWAPO member imprisoned
in the 1970s, said Tuesday the head of the U.N. refugee operation in
Namibia, Nicholas Bwakira of Nigeria, ``refuses to be helpful, even
though we want to give him the names'' of people believed held by
SWAPO.
   U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said Wednesday his organization has
been investigating claims for weeks. ``It's a matter of ongoing
review,'' he said without elaborating.
   SWAPO spokesman Theo Ben-Gurirab said, ``The party urges the U.N.
special representative (Martti Ahtisaari) to prevail on the
administrator-general and the South African government to fulfill
their obligations.
   ``We have released all our detainees and we find the
administrator-general's conditions totally unacceptable,'' he said.
   Freed detainees join thousands of SWAPO-supporting refugees and
other Namibians returning to vote in U.N.-supervised independence
elections in November. SWAPO is expected to win.
   The territorial authorities hold 28 or 31 political prisoners who
support SWAPO. The different figures involve a dispute over
political versus criminal violation of the law. Pienaar has charge
of the territory until a new government is installed. But U.N.
monitors can veto decisions that would interfere with free and fair
elections.
   Also Wednesday, Pienaar sought a court interdict to stop a strike
by regional government employees in northern Ovamboland. They
stopped work Tuesday to protest the presence in the South-West
African Police force of former paramilitary police known as Koevoet.
   Koevoet was disbanded in January, but most members transferred to
the regular police. SWAPO supporters in Ovamboland _ Namibia's most
populous region and where SWAPO garners most of its support _ say
they continue to harass residents. Ahtisaari has said their presence
could interfere with elections.
   Pienaar refuses to dismiss them. He says he'll discuss the matter
with U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar when he visits
Namibia on July 19.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890705-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 1635EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Pig-Court     07-05 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pig-Court,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Julia the City Pig to Have Her Day in Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Julia, a 300-pound pig who loves to have her
tummy scratched and drinks diet cola from a can, is a pet, says her
owner. She's a hog, say city officials, and can't live within city
limits.
   So now Julia's fate will be decided in court.
   Two weeks ago, at the request of Athens' animal control director,
Ron Ultz, a Municipal Court judge ordered veterinarian Bruce Young
to comply with ordinances against raising pigs in the city and to
send Julia to the country.
   Young, who found the injured piglet a year ago and took her home,
appealed to Limestone County Court and asked that a jury be allowed
to decide. ``I think I can convince a reasonable jury that she's my
pet _ and not just a ham,'' Young said Monday.
   A County clerk said because Young asked for a jury he will get
it. No court date has been set.
   ``She's a real pet who comes in the house and likes to roll over
on her back and get her tummy scratched, and I'm not going to let
her go,'' Young said.
   Young, who called Julia ``more intelligent than a lot of other
pets,'' has learned to drink diet Sun Drop Colas from a can. ``She
can't get enough of the stuff,'' said Young, who nursed the porker
on the soda.
   Julia awaits her fate while rooting inside a chain-link fence
behind Young's house, half a block from City Hall.
   Ultz said the pig's pen is unsanitary and smells bad. ``You know
what pigs are like; you know how pigs can smell,'' he said.
   Young's appearance in municpal court was the result of a
neighbor's complaint and an inspection of Julia's pen, Ultz said.
   ``The judge didn't fine him, he just ordered him to remove the
pig and that's when Bruce filed his appeal _ and I guess we go to
county court from here,'' Ultz said.
</TEXT>
