<FIRST>r w AM-North-Scene     07-05 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North-Scene,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Trial: Throngs of Reporters, But Button Sales Are Low</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-North Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From the knot of demonstrators chanting for TV
cameras to the shorts-clad tourists hoping for a glimpse of a
celebrity, the streets outside the courthouse where Oliver North was
sentenced had the look of news in the making.
   Except for the presence of any of the principals in the case.
   After U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell announced his
sentence for the 45-year-old former National Security Council aide
on Wednesday, North and his attorneys left the building through a
side door and clambered into a waiting van, saying nothing to
reporters.
   One voice shouted over the crowd, ``Ollie North, you're a hero!''
and the ex-Marine lieutenant colonel could be seen through the van's
dark-tinted windows smiling.
   Minutes earlier, chief prosecutor John Keker was equally
closed-mouth as he burst through scores of reporters and camera
crews at the courthouse's front entrance and ducked into a car.
   ``It's kind of ridiculous to have all these cameras and all of
this expense, just to see a guy walk out,'' said Bernie Doll, a
Washington psychiatrist at the scene because he was on jury duty and
awaiting assignment to a trial. ``It's a crazy world and getting
crazier.''
   Gesell had set the time of sentencing for 10 a.m. By 9 a.m. about
20 North supporters, clean-cut, well-dressed and mostly in their
20s, had mustered outside the drab gray courthouse at the foot of
Capitol Hill. Some carried printed ``Oliver North American Hero''
signs. Others toted hand-painted banners, and one hoisted a yellow
``Don't Tread on Me'' flag depicting a coiled rattlesnake.
   Polite and orderly, peering intermittently at the muggy overcast
skies for signs of a possible downpour, they erupted when cameras
came into view.
   ``Pardon North now,'' they chanted. ``North American hero.''
   The largest contingent outside the building, by far, was the
press. Nearly 30 television cameras were poised at the front
entrance, along with scores of reporters and photographers. Another
throng lurked at the side door.
   A handful of tourists gathered.
   ``I wanted to see what he looked like personally,'' Betty
Donovan, visiting town from Woburn, Mass., said of North.
   Frank Enten, a 58-year-old retiree from Bethesda, Md., and a
self-described ``Ollie North supporter from day one,'' set up a
sidewalk stand and began selling buttons to the faithful.
   ``The Duke would have loved Ollie,'' said one that depicted North
and the late actor John Wayne, their visages tilted heavenward.
Others portrayed Fawn Hall, North's former secretary, a flag
unfurled behind her and the inscription, ``Thanks for your support _
Fawn Hall.'' Others implored, ``Victory Over Communism'' and ``I'm a
Contra Too.''
   ``I thought there'd be a bigger crowd,'' said Enten, who said
business had been slow. ``I guess a lot of people couldn't get off
work.''
   Rep. Robert Dornan, R-Calif., a conservative and North supporter,
attended the sentencing, left the courtroom and stepped up to the
cluster of microphones positioned outside the building.
   ``He did not seem overly dejected,'' Dornan said when asked about
North's reaction to the sentence. The lawmaker said he believed the
sentence, which included no jail time, was ``on the low side of what
we expected.''
   Dornan spent much of his time explaining that he would not
immediately send a letter to President Bush that he had distributed
to reporters before the sentencing. The letter, signed by 58 members
of Congress, said North should spend no time in prison, and asked
Bush to pardon him.
</TEXT>
