<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Design     07-05 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Design,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>World's First Design Museum Explains Why Things Look The Way They
Do</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From the Shaker chair to the latest style of
seating device, the world's first museum exclusively dedicated to
design opens Thursday with a three-dimensional history of everyday
comforts and high-tech gadgets.
   ``I want to make people aware of everyday things and see them as
life-enhancing,'' said Sir Terence Conran, founder of the Design
Museum who made a fortune from his Habitat store chain. ``It's the
culmination of a dream.''
   Conran, 57, has turned a derelict 1950s warehouse at Butlers
Wharf _ ``a concrete monstrosity infested with rats'' he said _ into
a gleaming showplace of consumer civilization on the south bank of
the Thames river by Tower Bridge.
   ``Everything man-made has been designed and this is the first
museum in the world to show how mass-produced consumer objects were
designed and the first to explain why and how they work and look as
they do,'' the millionaire retailer said.
   ``It shows how design contributes to the quality of our lives,''
he said in an interview Wednesday before the museum's official
opening by Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   One floor of the $11 million museum displays technological
marvels like pocket all-world radios and suitcase computers, the
smartest thing in baby strollers, lampstands, tableware, bicycles
and TV receivers.
   There is the famous 1927 red telephone booth of Sir Giles Scott,
now discarded by up-to-the-minute British Telecom but so loved by
ordinary Britons that public uproar forced authorities last year to
give more than 1,000 of them official protection from scrapping.
   A permanent collection of 400 exhibits shows how modern objects
evolved: from flat irons to railway timetables, paperback books,
newspaper pages, sewing machines, motor scooters, soapflake
packaging, iceboxes, washing machines and fountain pens.
   There are 44 different chairs, starting with a 1900 American
Shaker design on rockers from the Christian sect that believed in
communal living.
   Reproductions of such famous icons as Leonardo da Vinci's ``Mona
Lisa'' on a tablemat, and designers of home furnishings seeking
museum treasures to copy onto drapes and cushion covers, show
culture and commerce coming together.
   A video screen unrolls well-known British TV commercials for
autos, coffee and jeans that newspapers discuss endlessly because
their readers say the advertisements are better than the programs
they are designed to interrupt.
   Besides lectures and seminars on creativity, work and technology,
the museum will run movies featuring the sets of famous designers.
   Many of the latest products shown are Japanese.
   ``It's not surprising, because after 30 years of looking,
listening and copying, the Japanese are developing their own design
culture, which is enormous and remarkable,'' said Conran.
   The museum grew out of the Boilerhouse Project, the first venture
of Conran's charitable Conran Foundation, which ran 23 exhibitions
on design at the Victoria and Albert Museum in 1982-1986, seen by
more than 1.5 milion people.
   Bayley, 37, who ran the Boilerhouse, described the new museum as
a ``classroom dedicated to the present and future of everyday life.''
   Museum visitors can see through its big windows the 900-year-old
Tower of London and the modern office blocks of the City financial
district.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890705-0106 </DOCNO>
