<FIRST>r i AM-Africa-US     07-05 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Africa-US,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. African Policy Chief Hopeful For Peace in Angola</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT WELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba's troop withdrawal from Angola
is on schedule and Washington believes negotiations to end the civil
war there will succeed, U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Herman
Cohen said Wednesday.
   Cohen said the U.S.-brokered peace accord signed by Angola, Cuba
and South Africa ``is working very well. The retreat of Cuban forces
is exactly on schedule ... the same thing for South Africa.''
   He arrived in Abidjan, the Ivorian capital, after visiting South
Africa and Namibia. He will attend a meeting of the commission
monitoring the withdrawal Friday in Luanda, Angola.
   Under the agreement, the more than 50,000 Cuban troops are to
leave Angola by July 1991. South Africa pulled out its forces from
Angola and is withdrawing from Namibia under a U.N. independence
plan for the territory.
   Cuba has helped Luanda's government fight Jonas Savimbi's
U.S.-backed guerrillas and incursions by South African troops
supporting Savimbi.
   At an African summit in Zaire last month, Savimbi and Angolan
President Jose Eduardo dos Santos called a cease-fire and agreed to
negotiate an end to 14 years of civil war that has devastated the
Southern African nation.
   They suffered a setback last week when dos Santos accused
Savimbi's fighters of breaking the truce.
   Cohen said tough negotiations lie ahead, ``but I believe they are
both committed to a solution, a political solution.''
   He also said hopes for peace are improving in Mozambique.
   Angola and Mozambique both have Marxist governments and have
suffered civil wars since the 1970s, when Portuguese colonizers
hastily withdraw, leaving opposing guerrilla armies that warred for
independence to fight it out. Wars in both countries have turned
into a stalemate.
   Cohen said he hoped to discuss peace prospects next week during
talks with Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano.
   ``We support the government of Mozambique and I will be
consulting with him to see if we can be helpful. I believe a
pre-negotiating situation exists there and I am hopeful that it will
move onto a real negotiating situation.
   ``Mozambique also can resolve its conflict through a political
solution. A military solution is impossible,'' he said.
   Guerrillas of the Mozambique National Resistance said Tuesday
they are ``ready and willing'' for peace talks with no prior
conditions as long as the government accepts the same arrangement.
   Chissano has ruled out direct talks, but has permitted indirect
contacts through church leaders.
</TEXT>
