<DOCNO> AP890705-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 1736EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-ArmsTalks     07-05 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arms Talks,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Officials Say Verification Key Issue in START Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief U.S. negotiator in U.S.-Soviet
talks in Geneva on long-range nuclear weapons assured NATO allies
that verification is a key issue.
   Negotiator Richard Burt discussed at length the American
proposals offered since the Strategic Arms Reduction Talks resumed
late last month, according to a U.S. official.
   The allies questioned the negotiators about such issues as mobile
missiles and sea-launched cruise missiles as well as verification,
said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Burt told the allies that any U.S.-Soviet agreement has to be
based on a ``good strong verification regime,'' the official said.
   Burt and another negotiator, Henry F. Cooper, met privately with
representatives of the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization
in Brussels. It was the first time that Burt, the former ambassador
to West Germany, talked to the allies in his new job.
   NATO's press office said the allies ``welcomed the opportunity
for confidential exchanges on developments in the Geneva talks, on
the basis of a detailed report made by the U.S. negotiators.''
   The U.S.-Soviet talks, which resumed after a seven-month recess,
are expected to end in early August.
   President Bush has suggested Washington and Moscow begin testing
verification procedures during the arms negotiations, rather than
waiting until an agreement is wrapped up.
   They could carry out trial inspections at each other's missile
sites and discuss equipment needed for assuring compliance with a
treaty.
   The Bush proposals are designed in part to build support in the
Senate for ratification of an eventual accord.
   Several arms control deals, including the 1979 SALT 2 treaty on
limiting long-range nuclear arsenals, were never ratified because of
Senate concerns about adequate verification methods.
   The START negotiations, which began in March 1985, are aimed at
reducing U.S. and Soviet strategic or long-range bombers, missiles
and nuclear submarines by 30 percent to 50 percent.
   The pact is intended to cover nuclear weapons that the two
superpowers could use to strike each other, including sea- and
land-based missiles as well as heavy bombers.
   In earlier rounds of talks, both sides agreed to lowered ceilings
of 6,000 nuclear wearheads and 1,600 delivery vehicles _ missiles
and bombers _ for each side. Outlines of a system for monitoring
compliance were also set.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
