<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 1812EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AfricanCongress     07-05 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-African Congress,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>African National Congress To Open Information Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The African National Congress, an outlawed
South African anti-apartheid group, intends to open an information
office in Washington this year, an official of the organization said
Wednesday.
   The decision is likely to generate controversy in light of
opposition from conservative American groups to Soviet support for
the ANC and to what they regard as the group's Marxist orientation.
   The Defense Department listed the ANC among 52 terrorist
organizations worldwide in a report entitled ``Terrorist Group
Profiles,'' which was released in January. The State Department
expressed reservations about inclusion of the group in the report,
saying the United States supports the ANC's goal of ending the
apartheid system of racial discrimination in South Africa but
opposes its violent methods.
   ``We need to establish ourselves strongly in this city,'' said
Dumi Matabani, a South African who has been representing the ANC
from his home here for the past eight years.
   Matabani said an office would be opened before the end of the
year, once funding and space for the facility have been organized.
   Matabani is registered with the Justice Department as a foreign
agent representing the ANC for lobbying and information purposes.
The new office will also be registered, in keeping with U.S. law, he
added.
   The ANC, which also gets help from African and European
countries, hopes recent actions by the administration of George Bush
herald a more conciliatory approach toward the organization.
   Former Secretary of State George Shultz met with ANC leader
Oliver Tambo several years ago and there have been other official
contacts with the organization, which also maintains an office at
the United Nations. But Matabani said he does not have any regular
contacts with the State Department, adding that U.S. officials are
not generally ``eager to hear what we have to say.''
   The Bush administration, unlike the Reagan one, has taken an
active role in seeking to promote negotiations between the black
majority in South Africa and the white-dominated government.
   Last week, Bush hosted a leading anti-apartheid activist,
Albertina Sisulu, at the White House. F.W. de Klerk, who is expected
to assume the country's presidency later this year, is expected to
visit the United States next month and become the first South
African leader to do so in 30 years.
   The ANC, founded 75 years ago, was outlawed by South Africa in
1960 and its leader, Nelson Mandela, was jailed. The group began a
sabotage campaign one year later, claiming it had no alternative
against the government.
</TEXT>
