<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 1813EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MissilesScrapped     07-05 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missiles Scrapped,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last Of Pershing 1A Missiles To Be Scrapped</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KARNACK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army's destruction of its last Pershing
1A ballistic missile on Thursday will eliminate an entire class of
nuclear weapons for the first time.
   Weather permitting, in separate firings at the Longhorn Army
Ammunition Plant, two missile sections strapped horizontally on
reinforced stands will consume their solid fuel propellant. After
the firing renders the missile useless, the sections are to be
crushed.
   The operation comes under provisions of the Intermediate-range
Nuclear Forces treaty between the United States and the Soviet
Union, signed in December 1987 by President Reagan and Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   A 10-member Soviet inspection team was scheduled to monitor
Thursday's event, which marks the destruction of the 169th and last
Pershing 1A, plant spokeswoman Dorothy Grant said.
   The INF treaty, which took effect June 1, 1988, requires
elimination of 859 American intermediate-range and shorter range
missiles and 1,752 similar Soviet missiles within three years.
   The missiles marked for destruction, which have a range of 300 to
3,400 miles, are unarmed. Nuclear warheads and electronic guidance
systems were removed, with the warheads being stored by the
Department of Energy.
   The destruction of the 5,500-pound Pershing 1A is being handled
by Utah-based Morton Thiokol Inc., which built many of the Pershing
motors at Longhorn.
   Larger Pershing 2 missiles will continue to be destroyed under
terms of the treaty. At Longhorn, Ms. Grant said nine Pershing 2
missiles have been eliminated, with 234 more headed for the junk
heap worldwide. In addition, hundreds of ground-launched cruise
missiles will be destroyed by the Air Force, she said.
   Besides Longhorn, Pershing 2 missiles also are being eliminated
from an Army depot near Pueblo, Colo. Other missiles are being taken
out of service at Davis-Monthan Air Force Base, Ariz., and near
Frankfurt, West Germany.
   The Soviets began destruction of several classes of similar
missiles a year ago.
   The treaty allows the missiles to be burned in place and then
crushed, to be destroyed with explosives or to be launched without
warheads. American officials have said they chose burning in place
because it is the cheapest and cleanest method.
   Thursday's affair was expected to be a much lower-key event than
the first destruction at Longhorn Sept. 8, 1988.
   Then-Vice President Bush made the first missile's demise a stop
on a campaign swing through Texas. Trailing him were about 300
reporters and photographers. Bush hailed the event as ``the day we
began to reverse the arms race ... the day we began destroying the
weapons of destruction.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890705-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 1918EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Cuba     07-05 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecution Demands Death Penalty in Cuban Court Martial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGIO CARRASCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military prosecutor is demanding the death
penalty for seven Cuban officers, including war hero Maj. Gen.
Arnaldo Ochoa, court-martialed on charges of high treason, drug
trafficking and corruption.
   The prosecutor, Brig. Gen. Juan Escalona also asked for prison
terms of 15 to 30 years for seven others before resting his case
Tuesday night, the Cuban government news agency Prensa Latina said
in dispatches from Havana.
   The Prensa Latina dispatches, monitored here Wednesday, did not
say when the three-man military court expects to render a verdict.
   Escalona demanded the death penalty for Ochoa, Antonio de la
Guardia, Jorge Martinez, Amado Padron, Antonio Sanchez, Eduardo Diaz
and Alexis Lago, and asked for 30-year prison terms for de la
Guardia's twin brother, Patricio, a brigadier general, and Capt.
Rosa Maria Abierno, the only woman in the group.
   He also asked for 25 years imprisonment for former officers
Leonel Estevez, Jose Luis Pineda, Gabriel Prendes and Miguel Ruiz,
and 15 years for Antonio Rodriguez.
   All of them have been stripped of rank and decorations and
dishonorably discharged from the armed forces. Ochoa, 57, was a
much-decorated hero of Cuban military intervention in Angola and
Ethiopia and special missions in Nicaragua and Venezuela.
   According to testimony at the trial, the 14 belonged to a special
Interior Ministry unit that smuggled hospital equipment, medicines
and other scarce but essential items into Cuba. The items were
smuggled to circumvent a U.S. trade and economic embargo that has
battered Cuba's economy since it was imposed in the 1960s.
   But Escalona told the court the accused also smuggled cocaine and
other drugs into the United States, dealt in contraband diamonds,
ivory and fine woods on the side for their own profit.
   ``The evidence and testimony confirming the crime of treason is
overwhelming,'' Escalona was quoted as saying as he summed up the
case before the court Tuesday night.
   About $1.2 million and 423,000 pesos in cash were seized when the
accused were arrested, as well as 39 expensive automobiles, a
motorcycle and 186 firearms, Prensa Latina said. It said
investigators also located a secret bank account held by Ochoa in
Panama, and the money was transferred to Cuba.
   Testimony from witnesses and confessions from the accused
indicated they dealt with Colombia's Medellin cartel, the world's
largest drug trafficking ring. For 2{ years they allowed tons of
contraband cocaine from Colombia and shiploads of marijuana from
Jamaica pass through Cuban territorial waters and airspace into the
United States.
   Ms. Abierno also confessed that she helped smuggle cocaine
concealed in computers by speedboat to Florida.
   Escalona said these and other felonies constituted ``hostile
acts'' against the United States, Mexico, Colombia and Panama. He
said they ``robbed and deceived'' Nicaragua's Sandinista government,
with which Cuba's communist regime maintains close ties.
   Escalona told the court that Ochoa ``deceived the Nicaraguans,
robbing them of big sums of money,'' and ``robbing the Sandinistas
also means betraying Cuba.''
   Calling Ochoa the main culprit, Escalona said the cashiered
general also ``weakened the prestige and defense of the Cuban
revolution.''
   ``Ochoa's betrayal of Cuba was even more serious when he betrayed
the Angolans by black market deals when he was chief of the Cuban
military mission in that African country,'' Escalona said.
   Escalona said Ochoa planned to ``build a mansion with fine woods
from the Angolan jungles and enjoyed all the human and divine
pleasures by incurring in multiple immoral acts.''
</TEXT>
