<FIRST>r w AM-BRF--Library-Tocqueville     07-05 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Library-Tocqueville,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Original Printing of de Tocqueville Classic Acquired</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Library of Congress has acquired the only
known set of the first edition of Alexis de Tocqueville's classic
``Democracy in America'' in its original paper bindings, the library
announced Wednesday.
   The two-volume set was bought from a Parisian bookseller for
$80,000 last spring, using public and private funds reserved for
special library acquisitions, officials said. The rare first
editions will be displayed in an exhibition opening Sept. 8 on
Tocqueville's works.
   Tocqueville, a French historian and political theorist, wrote
``Democracy in America,'' a four-volume interpretation of democratic
institutions in the United States, after an extensive tour of
America in the 1830s.
   The first two volumes, published in 1835, deal with the influence
of the doctrine of equality on politics and law. Of the handful of
first editions that survive, library officials said, the newly
acquired set is believed to be the only one that exists in pristine
condition, with original paper bindings.
</TEXT>
