<FIRST>r w AM-FarmExpenses     07-05 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Expenses,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farm Production Expenses Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers spent $118.4 billion on production
expenses last year, up 7.5 percent from $110.1 billion in 1987, a
preliminary report by the Agriculture Department said Wednesday.
   Despite the increase, 1988 expenditures were still far below the
record level of $131.8 billion in 1981, just before the general
financial crunch that stalled expansion in the nation's agricultural
sector.
   By 1986, annual spending by farmers dropped to less than $106
billion, indicating massive cutbacks in capital investments as land
values plummeted and debts burdened so many.
   According to the latest report by the department's National
Agricultural Statistics Service, 1988 expenditures were higher for
all major categories except interest, which decreased 3.7 percent to
$8.37 billion, and building and fencing, which dropped 10.3 percent
to $2.23 billion.
   Farm services, which include rent, accounted for the largest 1988
expenditures by farmers, totaling $24.6 billion, or 21 percent of
the total. That was up 2.7 percent from 1987.
   Spending on feed for livestock totaled $17.9 billion was up 20
percent from 1987 and accounted for 15 percent of last year's total.
   Overall, 1988 production expenditures averaged $54,956 per farm,
an increase of $4,165 from 1987, the report said.
   The analysis dealt only with production expenditures and did not
include figures for net income or profits.
</TEXT>
