<FIRST>r a AM-FlagBurnerFree     07-05 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Burner Free,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Jailed for Flag-Burning Freed from Federal Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Puerto Rican nationalist sentenced to the
federal prison in Atlanta for burning an American flag has been
freed since the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that such a protest is a
legal exercise of freedom of speech.
   Greg Bogdan, a spokesman for the U.S. Bureau of Prisons in
Washington, D.C., confirmed Wednesday that Carlos Mendoza-Lugo, 36,
was freed last week.
   Mendoza-Lugo had filed a petition in U.S. District Court seeking
release after the U.S. Supreme Court issued its ruling June 21.
   Bogdan said the Puerto Rican magistrate who sentenced
Mendoza-Lugo to the maximum one year in prison reduced the sentence
to seven months, making him eligible for release.
   But he said he did not know when the judge reduced the sentence
or whether the reduction was tied to the Supreme Court ruling. He
said Mendoza-Lugo was freed June 30, when the notification arrived
in Atlanta.
   Mendoza-Lugo, a professional photographer, was convicted of
burning a flag in front of the U.S. Post Office in his home town of
Anasco, Puerto Rico, on March 16, 1987.
   Wind kept blowing out his matches and he only singed the flag,
but he pleaded guilty to one charge of flag desecration.
   Mendoza-Lugo said he was protesting continued American control of
Puerto Rico and pressing for Puerto Rican independence.
   ``I never intended to degrade the American people,'' he said from
jail last week. ``It wasn't an act of vandalism. I was protesting.
It's unconstitutional for me to be in jail when I was making use of
my freedom of speech.''
   Federal judiciary officials have said that others jailed on the
same charge likely also will be freed as a result of the Supreme
Court ruling.
   The Bureau of Prisons said the number of people jailed on the
charge is very small, but that such statistics are not kept
separately.
 
</TEXT>
