<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--HolidayTraffic     07-05 0149</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Holiday Traffic,0153</SECOND>
<HEAD>Holiday Weekend Traffic Toll Exceeds 500</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 550 people died nationwide in traffic
accidents over the long Fourth of July weekend.
   California reported the most fatalities, 78, followed by Texas
with 34 and Ohio with 25 during the four-day weekend beginning at 6
p.m. local time Friday and ending at 12:01 a.m. Wednesday.
   Two states reported no fatalities _ Alaska and Montana.
   The national toll was lower than expected by the National Safety
Council. The council estimated last week that 570 to 670 people
would die in accidents during this year's holiday weekend.
   Last year, there were 463 highway deaths during the three-day
Fourth of July weekend.
   The highest toll for a four-day Fourth of July holiday period was
recorded in 1972, when 758 people were killed. The highest toll for
a three-day Independence Day weekend was 638 deaths in 1971.
</TEXT>
