<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 1936EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Legislature     07-05 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Legislature,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Soviet Rejects Another Cabinet Candidate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the new Soviet legislature voted down a
second Cabinet nominee Wednesday and roundly criticized another
before approving him.
   On Monday, the Supreme Soviet refused to confirm incumbent
Vladimir M. Kamentsev as minister of foreign economic policy.
   Before voting 204-130 on Wednesday to reject Nikolai S. Konarev
as railway minister, Tass said, legislators cited the industry's
poor safety record and shoddy service. He has had the job since 1982.
   More than 600 people on two trains were killed June 4 when a
spark from a railroad line ignited a highly flammable mixture of
benzine and propane-butane gas that had leaked from a pipeline into
a Ural Mountain valley. At least 118 people died in rail accidents
reported last year.
   The official news agency said members of the Supreme Soviet
accused Vladimir Chirskov's agemcy of safety and environmental
lapses, including responsibility for the Urals gas explosion, but
confirmed for another term as minister of oil and gas construction.
   Culture Minister Vasily G. Zakharov, Sports Committee chairman
Marat Gramov and six other nominees were withdrawn last month after
failing to win support from committees of the legislature, which
replaced the former rubber-stamp Supreme Soviet this spring.
   One minister confirmed had a familiar name. Vladimir Brezhnev,
minister of transport construction since 1985, said in response to a
question that he was a cousin of the late Leonid I. Brezhnev, who
now is blamed for corruption and economic stagnation.
   Brezhnev, 58, said his mother and the late leader's mother were
sisters, Tass reported, but an editor at Tass said the surnames were
coincidence.
   Seven other ministerial candidates were approved: Nikolai
Kotlyar, 54, incumbent fisheries minister; Igor Koksanov, 61,
incumbent minister of shipbuilding; Yuri Volmer, incumbent merchant
marine minister; Vladimir Shimko, 51, radio industry; Serafim
Kolpakov, 56, metallurgy; Boris Belousov, 55, defense industries,
and Oleg Shishkin, 55, machine-building minsiter.
</TEXT>
