<HEAD>USDA Names Top Foreign Sales Manager</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private grain trade executive, F. Paul
Dickerson, was named Wednesday as general sales manager and
associate administrator of the Agriculture Department's Foreign
Agricultural Service.
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter said Dickerson's 27 years
of marketing and trading experience in the United States and abroad
``makes him a natural to carry out the demanding duties'' of the
sales manager.
   Dickerson most recently was a consultant and marketing agent in
the Pacific Northwest, Yeutter said. From 1978 to 1986, he was
president and chief operating officer of Columbia Grain Co.,
Portland, Ore. Before that, beginning in 1967, he worked for Cook
Industries Inc., in Portland; Memphis, Tenn.; and Tokyo.
   From 1960 to 1967, Dickerson woarked for Cargill Inc., in
Chicago, Ill.; Des Moines, Iowa; Portland, Ore.; and Mexico City. He
is a native of Inglewood, Calif.
   As the agency's general sales manager, Dickerson will be
responsible for administering foreign market development activities,
export credit programs and the Food for Peace aid program.
