<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     07-05 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pravda: Strike, Demonstrations Hurt Economy of Nagorno-Karabakh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of the predominantly Armenian enclave of
Nagorno-Karabakh have lost the equivalent of about $53.5 million in
wages because of a two-month general strike in the region, Pravda
said Wednesday.
   The newspaper also reported that Armenians continue to hold
illegal demonstrations that threaten to trigger more ethnic clashes
in the enclave.
   Nagorno-Karabakh is an autonomous region within the republic of
Azerbaijan. The Armenian enclave is largely Christian but the rest
of the republic's residents mainly are Moslems, and ethnic tensions
in the region stem from the religious differences.
   The strike has cost Stepanakert, the autonomous region's capital,
about $38 million worth in manufactured goods, most of them intended
for the surrounding region, Pravda said.
   ``Industrial enterprises and construction projects, organizations
and institutions do not work,'' the newspaper said. ``Road transport
is partially idle.''
   It said the situation in Nagorno-Karabakh remains tense because
of continued demonstrations and rallies demanding that the Armenian
enclave be reunited with Armenia.
   ``Inter-ethnic conflicts in areas inhabited by Armenians and
Azerbaijanis, the disquieting situation on the roads, ill-considered
publications from both sides and unauthorized demonstrations and
rallies greatly complicate the situation in Nagorno-Karabakh,''
Pravda said.
   A commission on Nagorno-Karabakh established by the new Congress
of People's Deputies will review seven proposals for solving the
ethnic conflict, Soviet television news reported Wednesday.
   On May 9, authorities lengthened a curfew after ethnic clashes
between Armenians and Azerbaijanies. Authorities also have
established a special government committee to try to end the
violence.
</TEXT>
