<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 1939EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-CNN     07-05 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-CNN,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Cuts Off Satellite Reception in Hotels</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has ordered major hotels in the capital to
unhook satellite dishes that receive foreign news broadcasts,
including Cable News Network, hotel officials said Wednedsday.
   In addition to CNN, some hotels also receive the U.S. Armed
Forces Radio, Television Service and, in a few cases, the Japan
Broadcasting Corp. Only the hotels that are partly owned by foreign
business concerns have satellite dishes.
   ``The Chinese hotels do not have this service,'' said an official
at Beijing's Travel and Tourism Bureau who identified himself as Sun.
   Anyone with a satellite dish can receive the programming, and the
hotels do not pay cable networks or the Chinese government for the
service. The tourism official, said satellite service was ordered
cut because it was unfair.
   ``Our guess is that they are concerned the hotel staff is seeing
it,'' said Vito Maggiolo, CNN's managing editor in Beijing.
   China is engaged in an intensive propaganda campaign to discredit
Western news accounts of a seven-week student movement for
democratic reform and a military crackdown on June 3-4. The Chinese
government has said up to 200 people, half of them soldiers, died in
the crackdown, while Chinese witnesses and Western intelligence
sources say the death toll may have been as high as 3,000.
   Sun said the order to cut cable reception was issued in January
by the State Bureau of Travel and Tourism and the Ministry of Radio,
Film and Television. But he said it was enforced only in the past
few days after the government realized hotels had not heeded the
first order.
   Beijing hotel officials said the government order was issued
about six months ago but that there had been no attempts to enforce
it.
   Hotels in Shanghai and Guangzhou said, however, they have not
been ordered to cut satellite reception.
   The Great Wall Sheraton was the first to cut its satellite
service last month. It restored the service briefly this week,
reportedly because it realized other hotels were still ignoring the
order, but cut it again less than 24 hours later.
   The Jiangguo Hotel, China's first joint-venture hotel, suspended
service on Friday, one day after CNN broadcast a videotape of
fugitive student leader Wu'er Kaixi saying from exile he would never
give up the struggle for democracy in China.
   The hotel issued a circular a few days later, saying that
technical difficulties were responsible for the loss of programming.
   At least four other Beijing hotels _ the Shangri-La, Palace,
Kunlun and Holiday Inn Lido _ also have cut satellite service.
   Questions and complaints from disappointed and angry hotel guests
elicited a variety of responses, ranging from blank looks to talk of
technical problems.
   ``We are upset about it. But what can we do? We have to accept
it. Everyone is in the same boat. We cannot fight it,'' a Jianguo
hotel official said on condition of anonymity.
   ``There is no way we can say no,'' said the manager of another
hotel. ``Our guests are angry. We can only tell them it is beyond
our control.''
   Sun said any hotels that still refuse to follow the order will
not be punished, but said that hotels in China should obey Chinese
law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
