<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Politics     07-05 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Politics,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliamentary Election Campaigns Begin; Uno Keeps Low Profile</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders took to the streets Wednesday to
kick off campaigns for nationwide elections. Prime Minister Sousuke
Uno, fighting scandal and new allegations of tax evasion, stayed at
party headquarters and promised reform.
   Analysts and much of Japan's media have predicted his Liberal
Democratic Party, which has governed Japan since the party was
formed in 1955, will suffer heavy losses in the July 23 elections
for half the seats in the upper house of Parliament.
   In a 15-minute speech, Uno promised reform and apologized for the
widespread Recruit influence-peddling scandal that tainted many
Liberal Democratic Party leaders and led to the resignation of his
predecessor, Noboru Takeshita, one month ago.
   But he told voters not to listen to those ``who would change
Japan's system ... and lead the nation to isolation from the
international community.''
   He was referring to opposition parties, which have been gaining
in local elections in the wake of the scandal and voter anger over a
3-month-old sales tax.
   Soon after becoming prime minister, Uno was accused of keeping
paid mistresses. He denied doing anything immoral.
   ``By breaking the Liberal Democrats' majority, the upcoming
elections will be a historic first step,'' said Socialist Chairwoman
Takako Doi.
   ``The current government is not valid in the eyes of the world,''
she told a rally in Nagoya, central Japan. ``Prime Minister Uno is
holding office only because all his party's executives' hands are
dirty.''
   The mass-circulation newspapers Asahi and Yomiuri reported Uno
misreported property holdings and underpaid his taxes by $7,000
between 1977 and 1985.
   The papers said Uno continued for several years to claim as a
rice paddy property he converted into a parking lot in 1977. The
reports said he was taxed at the lower rates for farmland.
   The Asahi report, based on public announcements of all Cabinet
ministers' assets Tuesday, also alleged he violated a government
regulation by acting as president of his family brewery for several
months while holding a Cabinet post.
   Meanwhile, a Liberal Democratic Party official, who asked not to
be further identified, said it was ``rare'' for the party president
not to go out stumping the first day of such a major campaign. He
said Uno had no plans to attend any support rallies in the near
future.
   ``The sex scandal has absolutely nothing to do with it,'' said
another official at the party's campaign headquarters. ``He is busy
preparing for the summit.''
   Uno is scheduled to attend the Paris summit of seven major
industrialized nations, beginning July 14.
   The Tokyo branch of the Liberal Democratic Party last week asked
Uno to keep away from the campaign for the Metropolitan Assembly,
fearing the mistress question could scare off support. He did, but
when votes were counted Monday, the party lost nearly one-third of
its 63 seats in the 128-member assembly, while the Socialists, the
No. 1 opposition party, tripled their strength to 36.
   Of the 126 seats being contested in the 252-seat upper house, the
Liberal Democrats hold 66, the Socialists 22, the Komeito (Clean
Government Party) 12, the Communists eight, minor parties 13 and
independents five.
   Before Takeshita's resignation, three Cabinet ministers were
forced to step down due to links to the Recruit Co., a publishing
conglomerate that allegedly doled out millions of dollars in
political donations and underpriced stock shares in exchange for
favors.
   Uno reiterated his support for the new sales tax, which the
Liberal Democrats forced through Parliament late last year, but said
he was willing to ``re-examine'' certain aspects.
   The Liberal Democrats hold a comfortable majority in the more
powerful lower house, where elections do not have to be held before
next year.
</TEXT>
