<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 1953EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Hastings     07-05 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hastings,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Won't Bar Start of Judge's Senate Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge refused Wednesday to bar the
Senate from beginning the impeachment trial of U.S. District Judge
Alcee L. Hastings of Miami next Monday.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell ruled that he had no
jurisdiction to rule on Hastings' claims that the Senate procedure
for hearing the impeachment evidence violated due process.
   Hastings faces Senate trial on 17 articles of impeachment,
including allegations that he lied during his 1983 bribery trial,
which ended in his acquittal, and that he obstructed a corruption
investigation by disclosing wiretap information.
   The Miami jurist had sought an injunction to bar the proceeding
on the ground that appointment of a 12-member special impeachment
committee by the Senate violated his constitutional right to a trial
of the evidence by the full Senate.
   But Gesell said the Constitution gives the Senate the power to
devise the procedures for conducting impeachment trials.
   ``The Constitution simply does not specify in detail what is
required for the trial before the Senate,'' the judge said. ``Absent
evidence that the Senate is violating the Constitution, the court
should stay its hand.''
   He noted that the same committee procedure, with some
modificatins, was used in 1986 during the impeachment trial of
former U.S. District Judge Harry Claiborne of Nevada.
   Several senators voted against Claiborne's impeachment, saying
they objected to the committee procedure.
   But Gesell said that issue was for the Senate, not the courts, to
debate.
   ``It is not this court's function to tinker with the Senate's
procedures or to anticipate problems that could arise,'' Gesell
wrote. ``The procedures adopted do not by their terms violate any
constitutional rights or offend fundamental notions of justice.''
   Gesell also rejected Hastings' claims that he is a victim of
double jeopardy because the Senate is considering many of the same
charges for which he was acquitted during the criminal trial.
   But Gesell said Hastings' argument is based on a ``fundamental
misapprehension'' because ``impeachment is not a criminal
proceeding.''
   ``Impeachment proceedings are not restricted by principles of
double jeopardy any more than conviction always necessitates
impeachment,'' Gesell said.
</TEXT>
