<FIRST>u i AM-Gorbachev 1stLd-Writethru   07-05 0752</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0663,0771</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev and Mitterrand Call for Truce in Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: DELETES redundant 12th graf, `But he...' Pick up 13th pvs, ``The
idea...' Changes headline</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos PAR2,5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidents Mikhail S. Gorbachev of the Soviet Union
and Francois Mitterrand of France on Wednesday called for an
immediate truce in Lebanon and a halt to arms deliveries to Lebanese
groups involved in the conflict.
   In a statement issued at a joint news conference after two days
of talks, the two men said they were ``convinced that Lebanon must
remain sovereign, independent, united, with its territorial
integrity respected.''
   Gorbachev also indicated on Wednesday that he was prepared to
meet with leaders of Poland's Solidarity union movement and said the
Soviet Union would accept governments in the Soviet bloc that were
not dominated by the Communist Party. He said ``the right to free
election ... is of vital importance.''
   ``How the Polish and Hungarian people decide to structure their
society and their lives will be their affair,'' he said.
   The Gorbachev-Mitterrand statement on Lebanon supported Arab
League attempts to settle the civil war but also said their
countries were available to help with other efforts to reach a
peaceful settlement ``notably in the framework of the United Nations
Security Council.''
   France and the Soviet Union, together with the United States,
China and Britain, make up the five permanent members of the
Security Council.
   ``We are not going to take the place of those on the spot,''
Mitterrand said, referring to the continuing efforts of the Arab
League. ``But we're not going to leave things as they are, that is
clear.''
   Answering questions about President Bush's call for a withdrawal
of all Soviet troops from Poland, Gorbachev said Moscow and
Washington should avoid dealing in propaganda.
   ``We're trying to do business so as not to engage in
propaganda-type initiatives,'' he said.
   Gorbachev's comments on propaganda were not directly aimed at
Bush's appeal, although a simultaneous translation into English
provided at the news conference made it appear they had been.
   Gorbachev, making a three-day visit to France with his wife
Raisa, recalled dealing with Bush's predecessor, Ronald Reagan,
``when attempts were made to give us lessons, to make
prosecutorial-type accusations against us.''
   ``The idea is not to score propaganda points but to really
understand that we are coming out of a complex period of Cold War
encumbered with mistrust, confrontation and all of this has to be
gotten rid of. For this we have to be very wise and very
courageous,'' the Soviet president said.
   Bush, who visits Warsaw on Sunday, urged the Soviet Union to
withdraw military units it has stationed in Poland since the end of
World War II.
   On behalf of the NATO alliance, Bush called last month for
sweeping reductions in conventional forces in Europe that would cut
the number of U.S. and Soviet troops on the Continent to 275,000 for
each superpower.
   The Soviets would have to remove 325,000 men under the ceiling.
The Americans would have to cut only 30,000.
   During nearly 10 hours of talks over two days, Gorbachev and
Mitterrand discussed reducing conventional forces and signed 22
agreements covering cultural, scientific, business and military
cooperation.
   The statement on Lebanon ``called for an immediate cease-fire,
rigorously respected, as an indispensable condition for the
establishment of a constructive inter-Lebanese dialogue, aiming at
national reconciliation and peaceful building of a country founded
on a balance of the interests of all Lebanese communities.''
   The 14-year-old civil war in Lebanon, a former French possession,
has pitted Christians against Moslems and Druse militias. Since the
latest outbreak of fighting in March, Druse forces and Syrian troops
in Lebanon have battled the Christian army of Gen. Michel Aoun. Aoun
has demanded withdrawal of the Syrians, in Lebanon under a 1976
peacekeeping mandate.
   Moscow is the main arms supplier for Syria as well as Iraq, which
has been arming the Christian forces.
   Gorbachev told reporters he supported a decision by the Soviet
Writer's Union to publish Alexander Solzhenitsyn's ``Gulag
Archipelago'' and hinted that the exiled Nobel literature laureate
may have his Soviet citizenship restored.
   On Wednesday morning, Gorbachev met with French intellectuals at
the Sorbonne and challenged them to help create a new, more peaceful
world.
   He said the new Soviet political and economic system he is
fashioning would be ``a fusion of socialism and democracy ... It's
more difficult than we thought at the beginning, but it's working.
The country is changing, rapidly and irreversibly.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890705-0132 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 1956EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i LegislatureUrgesBritaintoOfferRefugetoHongKongResidents
    07-05 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>Legislature Urges Britain to Offer Refuge to Hong Kong Residents</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Hong Kong legislature Wednesday unanimously
urged Britain to offer refuge to the colony's people, who face
Communist Chinese rule in 1997.
   The Legislative Council adopted the motion despite London's
refusal to give the vast majority of Hong Kong's 5.7 million people
the right to live in Britain.
   Hong Kong residents have demanded that right since the Chinese
government used military force to crush a pro-democracy movement in
Beijing on June 3-4.
   Members of the Legislative Council said Britain was not doing
enough to restore confidence in the future of the colony, which
London returns to China in eight years. Much of their anger was over
the nationality issue.
   ``We must not allow Britain to wash her hands of Hong Kong,''
said Council member David Li. ``Britain must restore to the people
of Hong Kong their birthright as British subjects. The fight for the
right of abode is not over; it has just begun.''
   Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe of Britain returned home
Wednesday after a three-day visit to Hong Kong and told Parliament
in London that Hong Kong residents feared for their future because
of Beijing's crackdown on political dissent.
   ``It is of the first importance that the Chinese government take
early, tangible and sustained action to begin restoring confidence
in China's intentions towards Hong Kong. We shall be pressing them
strongly on this,'' he said.
   But Howe also reiterated Britain's stance against allowing Hong
Kong residents _ including the 3.25 million who hold British
passports _ the right to live in Britain after 1997.
   Britain has said it could not absorb the immigrants, an argument
rejected by Allen Lee, the Hong Kong Legislative Council's senior
member.
   ``We have stressed time and again that people of Hong Kong do not
want to leave this territory. All we want is the provision of an
escape route in case of need,'' he said.
   Lee also said proposals under which only certain groups in Hong
Kong could qualify for residency in Britain would not be in the
interest of the territory.
   The comments came in speeches on a motion that said, ``The
British government should urgently take adequate and appropriate
measures to ensure a safe and secure future for the people of Hong
Kong, including restoration of full British citizenship to British
subjects in Hong Kong.''
   The 56-member legislature adopted the motion by voice vote.
   The Legislative Council considers bills proposed by the colonial
administration and debates public policy. A majority of members are
government officials and appointees; the rest are chosen by special
interest groups.
</TEXT>
