<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-US     07-05 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-US,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Ambassador's `No' to Communists Draws Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador Peter Secchia says that in
Washington, at least, people are judged by their first 100 days in
office.
   But it took the Michigan businessman-turned-diplomat only 100
hours to draw fire by reiterating U.S. opposition to communist
participation in the Italian government.
   Christian Democratic Premier Ciriaco De Mita resigned May 19 and
has since been trying to resurrect the same five-party coalition
that excludes the communists. With political parties maneuvering for
position, Secchia's statement opened up the floodgates for the
communists.
   Asked if any change was expected in U.S. policy toward the
Italian Communist Party, the ambassador replied that while that it
was up to the Italian people to decide, ``it is clearly our
preference that the communists not enter the government for a number
of reasons, specifically the positions taken on key strategic
issues.''
   He told a Monday news conference that unless that changed, he had
no intention of meeting with Achille Occhetto, Italy's Communist
Party chief who visited America in May but was not received by the
Bush administration.
   The Communist Party daily L'Unita, which described Secchia as an
industrialist promoted diplomat for financial reasons, called it his
``first diplomatic incident'' and published a series of attacks.
   ``He's like a Japanese soldier in the jungle, it seems he hasn't
understood that the cold war is over,'' L`Unita quoted independent
leftist deputy Franco Bassanini as saying.
   ``It's interference in the affairs of our country while there is
a delicate political crisis,'' said Renato Zangheri, the Communist
whip in the Chamber of Deputies.
   Asked about criticism of his appointment, Secchia said Monday,
``I ask you to give me a chance and judge my performance, and maybe
100 days from now we can meet again.''
   Secchia was restating longstanding U.S. policy that had been
reiterated by his predecessor, Maxwell Rabb, when Occhetto went to
the United States.
   The Communist Party has opposed NATO's deployment of cruise
missiles in Sicily and attacked a plan to transfer to southern Italy
a U.S. Air Force F-16 wing forced to leave Spain.
</TEXT>
