<SECOND>AM-Hong Kong-Britain,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislature Urges Britain to Offer Refuge to Hong Kong Residents</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Retransmitting a0678 to fix slug</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Hong Kong legislature Wednesday unanimously
urged Britain to offer refuge to the colony's people, who face
Communist Chinese rule in 1997.
   The Legislative Council adopted the motion despite London's
refusal to give the vast majority of Hong Kong's 5.7 million people
the right to live in Britain.
   Hong Kong residents have demanded that right since the Chinese
government used military force to crush a pro-democracy movement in
Beijing on June 3-4.
   Members of the Legislative Council said Britain was not doing
enough to restore confidence in the future of the colony, which
London returns to China in eight years. Much of their anger was over
the nationality issue.
   ``We must not allow Britain to wash her hands of Hong Kong,''
said Council member David Li. ``Britain must restore to the people
of Hong Kong their birthright as British subjects. The fight for the
right of abode is not over; it has just begun.''
   Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe of Britain returned home
Wednesday after a three-day visit to Hong Kong and told Parliament
in London that Hong Kong residents feared for their future because
of Beijing's crackdown on political dissent.
   ``It is of the first importance that the Chinese government take
early, tangible and sustained action to begin restoring confidence
in China's intentions towards Hong Kong. We shall be pressing them
strongly on this,'' he said.
   But Howe also reiterated Britain's stance against allowing Hong
Kong residents _ including the 3.25 million who hold British
passports _ the right to live in Britain after 1997.
   Britain has said it could not absorb the immigrants, an argument
rejected by Allen Lee, the Hong Kong Legislative Council's senior
member.
   ``We have stressed time and again that people of Hong Kong do not
want to leave this territory. All we want is the provision of an
escape route in case of need,'' he said.
   Lee also said proposals under which only certain groups in Hong
Kong could qualify for residency in Britain would not be in the
interest of the territory.
   The comments came in speeches on a motion that said, ``The
British government should urgently take adequate and appropriate
measures to ensure a safe and secure future for the people of Hong
Kong, including restoration of full British citizenship to British
subjects in Hong Kong.''
   The 56-member legislature adopted the motion by voice vote.
   The Legislative Council considers bills proposed by the colonial
administration and debates public policy. A majority of members are
government officials and appointees; the rest are chosen by special
interest groups.
