<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Hostages     07-05 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Hostages,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hezbollah Leader Criticizes Kidnapping</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIAD KAHWAJI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior leader of the fundamentalist
Hezbollah organization said Wednesday the abduction of foreigners in
Lebanon was inappropriate and ``not a good method.''
   Sheikh Subhi Tofaili, who heads Hezbollah, or Party of God, in
east Lebanon's Bekaa Valley, spoke in an interview with The
Associated Press in south Beirut.
   Hezbollah has repeatedly denied involvement in the kidnappings.
But Western intelligence sources and and local reports frequently
described the Shiite Moslem faction as backing Islamic Jihad, the
umbrella organization for underground groups believed to be holding
most of the 14 foreigners missing in Lebanon.
   ``We haven't practiced kidnapping because of our conviction it is
inappropriate,'' said Tofaili, who recently returned from a trip to
Tehran after the death of revolutionary patriarch Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini.
   ``We do not believe the abduction is a good method.''
   But he made it plain that for now the party was not ready to
intervene to help secure the hostages' release ``because the ...
issue is political.''
   The hostages include nine Americans. The longest held is Terry
Anderson, 41, chief Middle East correspondent for the AP. He was
kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   Tofaili's statement came a week after Hezbollah spokesman Ibrahim
Amin said: ``It is possible that we might feel some acts might have
involved a very big mistake. But we have to face our mistakes in the
way that preserves and respects our society.''
</TEXT>
