<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0626 07-05 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0626,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Jets Bomb Guerrilla Positions at Jalalabad</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS 3 grafs after 7th, `Amani said both...' with release
of prisoners by guerrilla; picks up 8th pvs, `Diplomatic sources...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The air force bombed Moslem guerrilla
positions around Kabul and the eastern city of Jalalabad on
Wednesday, and the insurgents fired at least seven rockets into the
capital, the government said.
   Mohamad Nabi Amani, the Foreign Ministry spokesman, also reported
army counterattacks around the provincial towns of Khost, Kandahar
and Herat, but gave no details.
   He said 53 people had killed in all the operations, including 37
rebels.
   Amani said nine people were killed by the rockets in Kabul. Two
exploded in a residential area about 1,000 yards from the
Continental Hotel.
   On Tuesday, the government claimed the insurgents were preparing
major assaults on Kabul and other cities.
   A statement by the Supreme Defense Council on Wednesday said the
army was countering a ``heinous plan'' by Pakistan to aid the
guerrillas at Jalalabad, which has been under siege since March 7.
   Amani said both air force and artillery units were involved in
the fighting at Jalalabad, an important provincial capital 75 miles
east of Kabul and 45 miles from the border with Pakistan.
   On a former government tree farm at Ghaziabad, 25 miles east of
Jalalabad, the guerrilla faction led by Younis Khalis released 40
Afghan soldiers on Wednesday.
   Guerrillas have been accused of killing prisoners, and insurgent
leaders fear that has made many soldiers reluctant to change sides,
even though the Afghan army's desertion rate is high.
   ``They are not convinced ... we will not shoot them,'' said Aoul
Gul, the commander holding Ghaziabad. He said the prisoners were
freed to ``counter propaganda that we are killing the people we
get.''
   Diplomatic sources and witnesses said Wednesday's air strikes
were the most intensive in weeks.
   Fighter-bombers were seen leaving Kabul and the nearby Baghram
air base in groups of two and three for the Paghman Mountains, a
guerrilla sanctuary northwest of the capital.
   Thirty to 35 aircraft took part in operations that began at dawn
and lasted about 90 minutes, witnesses reported.
   Some aircraft headed for Nangarhar province, of which Jalalabad
is the capital. The assault on Jalalabad was the first major
guerrilla attack after the withdrawal of Soviet military forces from
Afghanistan was completed Feb. 15.
   Jalalabad, the country's fifth-largest city, is considered
strategically important because of its nearness to Pakistan, where
the main guerrilla groups are based. The United States and Pakistan
provide most of the support for the insurgents.
   The Soviet-sponsored government claims it broke the siege of
Jalalabad last month, but official Kabul radio has reported fighting
around the city for two weeks. It said shells and rockets fired into
residential areas Tuesday killed four people, including two
children, and wounded eight.
   On Tuesday, the government said insurgents planned simultaneous
``massive attacks'' on Kabul and other major cities in mid-July. It
asked the United Nations to intervene.
   Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil said: ``The grave consequences,
which will include bloodshed ... and destruction, will be shouldered
by the Pakistani militarists and overseas designers of the attack.''
   Moslem guerrillas began fighting after a communist coup in April
1978 and Soviet military forces entered the country in December
1979. An estimated 115,000 Red Army soldiers were in Afghanistan
when the U.N.-mediated withdrawal began in May 1988.
</TEXT>
