<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Environment     07-05 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Environment,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, at European Summit, Will Note Environmental Commitment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, anxious not to be overshadowed
by the European allies on tackling environmental problems, will
emphasize ``steady, long-term commitments'' to those issues during
next week's economic summit meeting in Paris, a top adviser said
Wednesday.
   Bush intends to discuss a variety of U.S. environmental concerns,
including atmospheric ozone depletion, ocean dumping, deforestation,
international air pollution and global warming, said William Reilly,
administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency.
   Without going into detail, Reilly said Bush will make specific
proposals, including in Hungary and Poland, which the president will
visit before the July 13-17 summit.
   Reily said the environment will take on an unprecedented priority
at the Paris sessions.
   ``There is even something of a race on by some of the economic
summit participants, leaders, to be the `greenest' of all on this
issue,'' Reilly told reporters. ``I would expect that our posture
will be one that emphasizes that restoring the environment is not a
sprinter's game; it's going to require steady, long-term commitments
to reverse accumulated environmental problems which have reached
very serious proportions in many parts of the world.''
   Reilly said that as Bush indicated in a May 31 speech in Mainz,
West Germany, the president will ``make some proposals on the
environment both in Poland and in Hungary'' and will show ``an
interest in making available to Eastern Europe ... some of the
benefits of U.S. experience.''
   Reilly would not elaborate on what those proposals would be or
whether they involved the economic incentives that Bush has promised
Hungary and Poland in response to their democratization reforms.
   In the Mainz speech, Bush said that the United States and Western
Europe should work together on environmental problems and extend ``a
hand to the East.''
   At that time, he said the West could offer ``technical training
and assistance in drafting laws and regulations and new
technologies'' for tackling environmental problems.
   The United States is expected to work against moves toward what
Reilly called a ``large, new United Nations bureacracy'' to oversee
air pollution rules.
   Such a U.N. role was envisioned in a pact signed by leaders from
24 nations in March at an ozone conference in Holland. The pact
asked the United Nations to police efforts to curtail
ozone-destroying chemicals and other air pollutants. French
President Francois Mitterand was among the signers.
   Reilly said that he did not expect the issue to dominate the
environmental talks, but said that discussion of ozone-depleting
chloroflourocarbons was expected to be a hot topic.
   He said he did not anticipate ``specific treaties'' or ``signed
ratified instruments'' on the environment to come from the summit.
   Reilly said the summit will more likely produce ``an affirmation
of the major issues on the environment, particularly those that
intersect importantly with economic development.''
   ``There is likely to be a focus on sustainable development and
perhaps what that means for the world environment.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890705-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 2027EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Burma     07-05 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Rally Draws 10,000 in Burma</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 10,000 Burmese attended a
pro-democracy rally held in defiance of martial law, and the
nation's military leader indicated the army was prepared to quell
further demonstrations.
   Diplomats in Rangoon said the crowd that gathered Wednesday in
the center of the city was the largest in Burma since the army
crushed pro-democracy protests in September.
   ``Defiance and confrontation are extremely dangerous in the
establishment of democracy. ... We (the army) have contingency plans
to handle any situation,'' the army commander, Gen. Saw Maung, told
a news conference.
   He said communists had infiltrated opposition political parties.
   The rally defied martial law regulations that forbid public
meetings of more than five people, but witnesses reported a subdued
army presence.
   Ma Theingi, personal secretary to opposition leader Aung San Suu
Kyi, said in a telephone interview that Ms. Suu Kyi spoke at the
rally and reiterated demands for democratic change. Ms. Suu Kyi also
protested the harassment and arrest of opposition members.
   The spokeswoman said authorities on Tuesday arrested Win Tin, 60,
a member of the nine-man executive committee of the National League
for Democracy. About 1,000 league members have been arrested since
the military took power in September, she said.
   Saw Maung repeated the military's  league, is the most outspoken
critic of military rule.
   Confrontation has increased recently between the army and the
league, the largest opposition group to emerge from the uprising.
   In August and September, millions of people took the streets
across Burma demanding democracy and an end to years of one-party
rule and authoritarian repression. Thousands were killed before Saw
Maung's troops finally crushed protests on Sept. 18 and he took
control of the government.
   Many Burmese remain skeptical that the army will hand over power.
</TEXT>
