<FIRST>r i AM-Gorbachev-Baptism     07-05 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev-Baptism,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Confirms He Was Baptized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev, secretary-general of the
officially atheistic Soviet Communist Party, told reporters
Wednesday he had been baptized.
   ``I was baptized. I was christened, and I think this is quite
normal,'' the Soviet president said in response to a question at a
news conference.
   Despite the greater openness in the Soviet Union, much is still
not known about the 58-year-old Kremlin leader's past or personal
life. Such topics are generally off-limits to his country's
state-run media.
   During a visit to Britain in 1984, Gorbachev said that his
grandparents kept icons at home but that they kept them behind
portraits of Lenin and Stalin to hide them from authorities.
   Gorbachev has said his grandparents once took him to church but
that he felt no need to return after the first visit.
   Gorbachev's mother, Maria Panteleyevna, is said to attend a
Russian Orthodox Church not far from her home in Privolnoye, a rural
village in southern Russia where Gorbachev was born.
</TEXT>
