<FIRST>u w AM-S&amp;Ls     07-05 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>S&amp;L Withdrawals Continue to Ease</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Net withdrawals from the nation's savings and
loans eased in May for the fourth consecutive month, the government
said Wednesday.
   Federal Home Loan Bank Board Chairman M. Danny Wall, speaking on
the eve of the board's formal release of May figures for the
nation's 2,934 S&amp;Ls, said there was only a ``slight outflow'' of
deposits in May compared with a $5.4 billion exodus in April.
   Including interest credited to accounts, deposits for the month
rose slightly for the first time since December, Wall said.
   Meanwhile, Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said three former
Dallas S&amp;L executives pleaded guilty to fraud and other charges of
insider abuse. A new indictment also was handed up Wednesday.
   The three executives are:
   _John H. Roberts Jr., former president of Summit Savings
Association of Dallas. Roberts used a nominee borrower to obtain a
$4.5 million loan from the institution to provide an airplane for
Roberts' use. He faces a maximum jail term of 10 years and a $15,000
fine.
   _Joseph R. Smith, former vice president at Sunbelt Savings
Association in Dallas, who pleaded guilty to conspiring to defraud
the bank board and the IRS. He faces a maximum jail sentence of five
years and a fine up to $250,000.
   _Kenneth C. Hood, former vice presdient of Western Savings
Association in Dallas. He was charged with attempting to defraud the
IRS by creating artificial losses and by making a false statement in
connection with a $11.3 million loan from Sunbelt. He faces a
maximum sentence of seven years in prison and a fine of $500,000.
   Indicted Wednesday was Bob R. Franks, former president of
Northpark Savings Association in Richardson, Texas.
   Franks is accused of illegally diverting $138,000 of Northpark
funds to make an interest payment on a $2.95 million loan from
Centennial Savings Association of Greenville, Texas. If convicted,
he could be sentenced to up to 15 years in prison and fined up to
$500,000.
   Thornburgh attributed the three convictions, as well as the new
indictment, to the Dallas Bank Fraud Task Force.
   The task force, a joint effort of the Justice Department, the
bank board, the FBI and the Internal Revenue Service, has brought
indictments against 50 people for S&amp;L or bank fraud and obtained 32
convictions in two years. More than 100 other people have been
convicted for bank or S&amp;L fraud under indictments sought by the U.S.
attorney's office in Dallas.
   However, Thornburgh said he opposed a provision in the House S&amp;L
bailout bill that would require the Justice Department to maintain
the task force in Dallas and establish a similar one in Southern
California, the two areas of the country with the biggest backlogs
of thrift fraud cases.
   ``What we prefer to do is have the flexibility to move our
resources where they are necessary,'' Thornburgh said.
</TEXT>
