<FIRST>r a AM-HelmsleyTrial     07-05 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helmsley Trial,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor: Hotel Queen Thought She Was Above the Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leona Helmsley wrote off jade figurines worth
$500,000, an outdoor sound system patterned after one at Disney
World and other household purchases as business expenses to avoid
taxes, a prosecutor charged Wednesday.
   In opening arguments at her federal trial on tax evasion,
conspiracy and extortion charges, Mrs. Helmsley's attorney asked
jurors not to hold her personality against her.
   Mrs. Helmsley, 69, and her husband, Harry, head a $5 billion real
estate and hotel empire.
   The couple ``acted as if they were above the law,'' said
Assistant U.S. Attorney James DeVita. ``They used their position in
society to evade one of the most important responsibilities ... to
pay their fair and accurate share of taxes.''
   Helmsley, 80, indicted in April 1988 with his wife, was dropped
as a defendant in the U.S. District Court trial after being found
mentally incompetent.
   Mrs. Helmsley is on trial with former Helmsley hotel executive
Frank Turco and Joseph Licari, who was a top aide to Harry Helmsley.
   DeVita said that in addition to charging the renovation of the
couple's Greenwich, Conn., mansion to Helmsley-controlled companies,
Mrs. Helmsley used her hotels and businesses as ``a personal piggy
bank'' for other purchases.
   He said these included everything from a $45,000 silver clock for
her husband ``right down to her shoes and underwear.''
   DeVita also detailed instances when Mrs. Helmsley yelled at
employees and had them fired if they did not not go along with the
scheme.
   Mrs. Helmsley's attorney, Gerald Feffer, downplayed the charge
Mrs. Helmsley did not pay $1 million in federal taxes from 1983 to
1985. He said the Helmsleys paid $57.8 million in federal, state and
local taxes during that time.
   Feffer told the jury he would prove Helmsley companies were
entitled to pay part of the cost of renovating, decorating and
operating the mansion, which the Helmsleys bought for $11 million in
1983.
   Feffer also addressed the issue of Mrs. Helmsley's personality,
which he said would be a critical part of the case.
   ``They are going to try to get you to hate her by the end of the
trial,'' he said, adding that prosecutors would try to prejudice the
jury by giving details of the Helmsleys' extravagant lifestyle.
   ``In the United States we don't put people in jail for being
unpopular,'' Feffer said.
   He said Mrs. Helmsley has a ``mania'' for running the best hotels
in the world. ``If she should stumble on a speck of dust, or God
forbid, a roach in a hotel room, Mrs. Helmsley will blow up.''
   Mrs. Helsmley appears in national advertisements billing her as
the ``queen of the Helmsley Hotels.''
   During DeVita's arguments, Mrs. Helmsley shook her head ``no''
several times and her face became red. She jotted notes on a legal
pad.
   DeVita said the Helmsleys avoided paying for the estate's
renovation by submitting phony invoices and records to make it
appear the expenses were incurred by 19 companies in their empire.
   He said the cost of enclosing one of two swimming pools at the
mansion and installing a marble dance floor on its roof was $2
million, half of which was paid for by Helmsley companies.
   He said a sound system that piped music to a gazebo and barbecue
pit was installed after Mrs. Helmsley admired a similar one at
Disney World. DeVita called it ``a musical paradise underwritten in
part by Uncle Sam.''
   The two jade figurines, bought from a dealer for $500,000, were
charged to four hotels and listed on the invoices as antique
furniture, DeVita said.
</TEXT>
