<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 2045EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia-US     07-05 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia-US,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Minister Summons U.S. Ambassador Over Congressional Measure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Budimir Loncar
called in U.S. Ambassador Warren Zimmermann on Wednesday to protest
a congressional amendment alleging human rights abuses against
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo province.
   The measure, adopted by the House of Representatives last week,
expresses concern over the state of human rights in Yugoslavia,
especially in Kosovo, where a state of emergency was introduced in
February to quell ethnic unrest.
   Loncar told Zimmermann the human rights situation here was shown
in a ``false and biased way,'' according to the state Tanjug news
agency. He reportedly told Zimmermann the amendment ``encourages
nationalist and separatist elements in Kosovo and is contrary to
American statements in support of the territorial integrity of
Yugoslavia.''
   The measure passed by the House was merely advisory. It stressed
that ``the United States continues to support the independence,
unity and territorial integrity of Yugoslavia.''
   The measure was one of several amendments to the foreign aid bill
adopted on a voice vote with no objection June 28.
   Communist Yugoslavia has maintained close relations with the
United States since Belgrade's break with the Soviet bloc in 1948.
   Ethnic Albanians make up 85 percent of Kosovo's population. As a
province of Yugoslavia's republic of Serbia, Kosovo enjoyed broad
autonomy under the 1974 constitution. That autonomy was curbed when
control of police, judiciary and education passed to the Serbian
capital of Belgrade in March.
   Members of the Serbian minority in Kosovo claim they are being
driven out of their ancient heartland by harassment from ethnic
Albanians.
   Last March, protests by ethnic Albanians led to bloody clashes
with security forces in which at least 25 people died.
</TEXT>
