<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 1952EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Panama     07-05 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panama Blocks Entrance to U.S. Base</HEAD>
<HEAD>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 150 Panamanian paramilitary
troopers blocked the entrance to a large U.S. Army base on Wednesday
to protest what they called ``lack of respect by the United States
for Panama.''
   No incidents occurred during the nearly one hour that members of
the so- called Dignity Battalion blocked the entrance to Fort
Clayton, home of Brig. Gen. Mark Cisneros, commander of U.S. Army
South.
   Earlier Wednesday, the Foreign Ministry accused the U.S. Army of
``provocations and intimidation'' through weekend military maneuvers
in civilian areas near the Panama Canal.
   Cisneros said he ordered the exercises and they would continue.
His forces are in charge of defending the canal.
   The development was the latest in the confrontation between
Washington and the government controlled by Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, commander of the Defense Forces.
   Noriega is under U.S. indictment on drug trafficking charges,
which he denies. The United States also accuses him of domestic
repression and considers him a possible threat to the canal.
   The Dignity Battalion was formed and trained by the Defense
Forces and is made up of civilians who support the forces and
Noriega.
   Its members, carrying Panamanian flags and chanting anti-American
slogans, stood blocking the access roads leading to the main gate of
the base.
   The group commander, Benjamin Colamarco, and others went to the
gate and delivered a letter to Provost Marshal Maj. Alan Mansfield.
   He urged them to clear the area because ``you are violating the
Panama Canal Treaties.''
   ``You do not represent an authority in Panama,'' Colamarco
replied.
   Mansfield then talked to Lt. Johnny Rivera, a Panamanian who is
the liaison officer with the U.S. Forces.
   Rivera told him he understood ``that they want a letter delivered
to Cisneros.''
   ``The letter has been delivered ,'' Mansfield said.
   Minutes later, the protesters left.
   Just inside the gate U.S. soldiers in riot gear stood ready to
intervene.
   The U.S. government says that under the Canal Treaties of 1977
signed by President Jimmy Carter and the late Panamanian dictator
Omar Torrijos, U.S. forces can travel freely on Panamanian roads and
carry out training exercises in designated areas near the canal to
prepare for their mission.
</TEXT>
