<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 2014EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-LaborCosts 1stLd-Writethru   07-05 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Labor Costs, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0707,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Labor Costs Rising Slower than in Most Competing Countries</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS two grafs to give all 12 percentage changes.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor costs rose more slowly last year in the
United States than in all but one of the nation's 11 major economic
competitors, the Labor Department said
   The rise in U.S. labor costs _ 0.3 percent from 1987 to 1988 _
was dwarfed by such increases as 17 percent in Taiwan and 11.2
percent in South Korea.
   Of the 11 competitors, only France bettered the U.S. performance,
recording a decline of 0.8 percent, the Bureau of Labor Statistics
said.
   While American workers were still earning more than employees in
most of the other countries, the fall in the value of the dollar
meant that a Japanese worker was catching up fast to his U.S.
counterparts.
   The average Japanese worker cost the employer $13.14 an hour in
1988, a 10.5 percent increase over 1987. The average in the United
States was $13.90.
   In eight western European countries, the costs were already
higher than in the United States: $19.43 in Norway, for example, and
$18.07 in West Germany.
   In South Korea, however, the cost of an average hour's labor was
only $2.45 and, in Taiwan, $2.71.
   That is, an employer could hire more than five Taiwanese or South
Korean workers for the cost of hiring one American. This helps
explain why some factories have moved production lines out of the
United States to those Pacific Rim countries.
   Not all labor costs go to workers as wages. The Labor Department
figures include employer contributions to private plans and payroll
taxes for social services, such as pensions and health care, from
which workers benefit. These expenses are generally higher in
western Europe than in the United States, and higher in the United
States than in the countries on the Pacific rim.
   Here are the percentage changes for each of the 12 countries
surveyed _ increases for all but France. The bureau did not give the
1988 cost for an hour's labor in all. The increases are bases on
costs measured in dollars. Because of exchange-rate fluctuations,
the percentages might be different for costs measured in local
currencies.
   Taiwan, 17 percent; Britain, 11.8 percent; South Korea, 11.2
percent; Canada, 10.9 percent; Japan, 10.5 percent; Sweden, 7.9
percent; Denmark, 3.4 percent; Italy, 2.9 percent; West Germany, 1.8
percent; The Netherlands, 1 percent; the United States, 0.3 percent;
France, minus 0.8 percent.
</TEXT>
