<FIRST>r a AM-Hank'sDaughter     07-05 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hank's Daughter,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rules Hank Williams' Illegitimate Daughter Can Inherit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILLIP RAWLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The illegitimate daughter of the late
Hank Williams Sr. should share in the country music legacy of
lucrative songwriting royalties, the state Supreme Court ruled
Wednesday.
   The court, in a 5-2 decision, said Cathy Deupree Adkinson can
share in the income, interest and copyright royalties _ estimated to
be worth more than $500,000 a year _ from the time she filed her
initial claim on Aug. 5, 1985.
   The court said Mrs. Adkinson's interests were not properly
represented when Williams' estate was settled 21 years ago.
   ``For 35 years of her life, she's got the short end of the stick.
But in the last two weeks, she's won major victories,'' said her
attorney, David Cromwell Johnson of Birmingham.
   The Supreme Court ruling came one week after Mrs. Adkinson
reached an out-of-court settlement of her separate lawsuit seeking a
share of the $600,000 estate of her adopted mother in Mobile.
   Mary Deupree left her adopted daughter out of the will she wrote
in 1987 when dying with cancer. Mrs. Adkinson's attorneys claimed
Mrs. Deupree was a drug addict who was pressured by others to cut
out the adopted daughter.
   Ms. Adkinson of Washington, D.C., is a budding country music
singer whose stage name, Jett Williams, combines the names of her
father, the late country music entertainer, and her late mother,
Bobbie Jett, a Nashville, Tenn., secretary who lived with Hank
Williams Sr. in the summer of 1952.
   Johnson said his client was away from her home Wednesday and was
unaware of the ruling.
   He estimated the royalties from songs such as ``Your Cheatin'
Heart,'' ``Kowliga'' and ``I Saw the Light'' are worth ``at least a
half million a year and maybe close to a million a year.''
   Richard Frank, a Nashville attorney representing Williams'
publishers, said the ruling was complicated by an earlier federal
court ruling in New York that rejected Mrs. Adkinson's claim to a
share of the copyright royalties.
   Johnson said the case must go back to Montgomery County Circuit
Court for settlement, but anticipated Ms. Adkinson would get
one-third of the estate, which has been controlled by Williams' son
from his first marriage, country music entertainer Hank Williams Jr.
and the second wife of Williams Sr.
   Williams died on Jan. 1, 1953. His daughter was born five days
later and, because of an agreement the country singer had with Ms.
Jett, the child was raised by Williams' mother, Lillian Stone, until
her death on Feb. 26, 1955.
   Williams' sister, Irene Smith, had originally agreed to take the
child if something happened to Mrs. Stone, but changed her mind and
the child was placed for adoption by the state welfare agency, the
Supreme Court said..
   On April 23, 1959, the child, known as Cathy Yvonne Stone, was
adopted by George and Mary Deupree of Mobile, who, according to
court records, wanted to conceal her past and declined efforts by an
attorney to have the child involved in the settlement of her
father's estate in 1967-68.
   While a student at the University of Alabama, Mrs. Adkinson
became aware she might have a famous father. She started seeking
closed court records about her paternity.
   Hank Williams Jr. filed a lawsuit in 1985 to keep the court
records secret, prompting a long legal battle.
   Mrs. Adkinson won a lower court ruling that she was the daughter
of Hank Williams Sr., but the court said she could not inherit. The
Supreme Court reversed that part of the ruling, but said she could
inherit only from the time she made the complaint in 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
