<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 2214EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan     07-05 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Military Junta Sends Delegation For Talks With Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of Sudan's new military junta
Wednesday said he would send a military delegation to talk with
southern rebels who have waged a six-year war against the government.
   Late Tuesday, in a second peace overture since seizing power last
week, the 15-member military council decreed a one-month unilateral
cease-fire in the war with the People's Liberation Army and proposed
a general amnesty.
   The amnesty would apply to the 50,000-60,000 rebels who have
taken up arms against the government since the rebellion led by
turncoat army Col. John Garang began in three southern provinces.
   Bashir said that on Thursday a military delegation would be sent
to the rebels' southern headquarters in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, for
talks with Garang.
   State-run television quoted Bashir as telling reporters his peace
measures proved his ``June revolution'' was serious in seeking a
paeceful settlement for the war.
   Also Wednesday, the junta agreed to allow relief operations to
continue in the south, the Sudan News Agency quoted Bashir as
telling an army rally in Gabal Awlia, south of this capital.
   Both sides stilled their guns in May and June in response to a
unilateral cease-fire proposed by Garang to allow the United Nations
to move 120,000 tons of relief supplies to the south to ward off
famine this summer.
   Despite Bashir's repeated peace vows, spokesmen for the Sudan
People's Liberation Army have refrained from comment, saying they
were closely watching developments in Khartoum.
   Residents of the capital city have expressed cautious approval of
the new military leadership, which has lowered the prices of basic
goods while cracking down on corruption.
   ``His crackdown on the black market is slowly working,'' said
Younis Abdallah, a taxi driver. ``There is bread and petroleum. Many
merchants are afraid of his threat to punish by execution those
found guilty of hoarding and black marketeering,'' said Abdallah.
   Soon after a military coup on Friday overthrew Prime Minister
Sadek Mahdi, Bashir issued decrees dissolving parliament, political
parties and trade and professional unions. He withdrew newspaper
licenses and arrested about 45 political figures and others
suspected of corruption.
   A barrel of cooking oil now sells for the equivalent to $12.5,
down from $28. A loaf of bread costs 1 cent, down from 4 cents, and
the government set the price of meat at $1.60-$2 a pound.
   But a nighttime curfew remained in effect in Khartoum.
   ``Many Sudanese are very simple people who just want to find
enough to eat,'' said a western diplomat on condition of anonymity.
``If they find bread and cooking oil, they are willing to give up
political parties and a hoard of daily newspapers.''
   Prime Minister Mahdi remains at large.
   Al-Ittihad newspaper in the United Arab Emirates reported a junta
member, Brig. Ibrahim Nayel as saying Mahdi had sent word asking for
a guarantee for personal safety before turning hismelf in.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
