<FIRST>r i AM-Peru-Soviets 1stLd-Writethru a0680 07-05 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru-Soviets, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0680,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Bomb Bus Carrying Soviet Sailors, 20 Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To UPDATE with police report on six people killed in other attacks,
SUBS 4th graf, `Gen. Oswaldo...' with two grafs. Pickup 4th pvs, `Gen.
Oswaldo...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected leftist guerrillas Wednesday bombed a
bus carrying sailors from a Soviet fishing fleet on shore leave in
Lima, injuring 20 seamen, police said.
   The 12-pound bomb exploded as the 49 fishermen were boarding the
bus after leaving a handicrafts store, according to police and
witnesses. Eight were in serious condition, with injuries and burns
on their lower bodies, police said.
   No group claimed responsibility for the bombing, but police said
it had the characteristics of an attack by the Shining Path, a
left-wing guerrilla group that has targeted Soviet diplomats and
citizens in the past.
   Police also blamed the rebels for the deaths of six people they
said were killed in three attacks Tuesday in the region around
Huancavelica, a mining town in the central Andes about 150 miles
southeast of Lima. Police said the dead included an engineer for the
state electrical company and two women traveling in his truck, a
village mayor, a peasant and his mother.
   Gen. Oswaldo Diaz Salvador, the Lima police chief, said two young
men were seen placing a package under the bus carrying the Soviets
and then racing off as the bomb exploded. He said the police were
seeking four people in connection with the bombing.
   Two smaller buses, each carrying 35 Soviet fishermen, were
damaged by the mid-morning explosion, police said. But all of the
injured were on the larger bus. A group of 66 Soviets had just left
the area to sightsee in downtown Lima.
   The buses are owned by a tourism service company.
   The explosion also damaged the three-story building where the
fishermen had been shopping at a store that caters exclusively to
Soviets.
   An agreement between Peru and the Soviet Union allows 20 Soviet
trawlers to fish in Peruvian waters in exchange for a percentage of
the catch. The fleet uses the port of Callao, five miles west of
Lima, as a resupply point.
   When their vessels are in port, the fishermen often take shopping
trips, and a number of stores have opened that cater exclusively to
the Russian-speaking clients.
   On June 3, Shining Path guerrillas blew up a bus carrying palace
guards to a ceremony in downtown Lima, killing six people.
   In 1986, a Shining Path guerrilla was killed when the bomb he
carried after breaking into the grounds of the Soviet embassy
exploded. Also in 1986, Soviet fishermen were injured when a bomb
went off in a store in Callao.
   The Shining Path, which follows the ideology of Mao Tse-tung,
views the Soviet government as a traitor to Marxist theory. It
regards the Soviets as enemies because they have been a major
supplier of arms to Peru for the past two decades.
   The Shining Path has been fighting to topple Peru's elected
government since 1980. More than 15,000 people, including police,
soldiers, rebels and civilians, have died in the violence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
