<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Art     07-05 0150</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Art,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>Murillo Record at Old Masters Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A painting of the Virgin and Child by the 17th
century Spanish artist Bartolome Esteban Murillo sold for $2.7
million to a Japanese dealer Wednesday, Sotheby's said.
   ``The Virgin of the Swaddling Clothes'' fetched an auction record
for Murillo.
   The buyer was Umeda Art Boeki of Osaka. The seller was not
identified.
   The painting is reputed to have been bought in a street opposite
Seville Cathedral in 1819 and it once belonged to Louis Philippe,
the French king who abdicated in the 1848 revolution.
   Murillo has been regarded for many years as too sentimental for
modern taste.
   The painting was in an old masters sale that brought nearly $23
million for 83 paintings.
   ``That's a lot for an old masters sale after the dominance of the
market by Impressionists and modern masters,'' said Fiona Ford, the
auctioneers' spokeswoman.
</TEXT>
