<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 2303EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NavyDeserter     07-05 0756</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navy Deserter,0779</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sentencing of Sailor Who Deserted 20 Years Ago</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TREASURE ISLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military judge on Wednesday
ordered a bad conduct discharge and suspended sentence for a Navy
deserter who led a normal life for two decades without revealing his
past.
   ``I couldn't ask for anything more,'' said Charles Smith, 43, a
seaman apprentice who walked away from his post at Treasure Island
in September 1969 after being ordered to report to an Alaskan
outpost.
   Although it was the Vietnam era, Smith said it was a marriage
gone sour and resentment of authority rather than politics that made
him desert. ``They gave me a lot of harassment,'' Smith said his
18-month tour. ``We're even now.''
   Smith, who pleaded guilty during his court-martial, was sentenced
to four months in the brig, suspended; reduced to the lowest rank;
and ordered to forfeit $1,000 in Navy pay.
   If he does not violate any laws for a year, the brig time will be
lifted.
   Smith, who kept his name and lived less than 10 miles from the
base during his desertion, was among the longest of the Navy's
recent cases.
   Because of a new enforcement program, desertions dropped from
14,000 in 1987 to 2,485, said Lt. Cmdr. Kaye Roberts, head of the
Navy Deserter Apprehension Program in Washington D.C.
   Smith faced up to one year for desertion, life imprisonment for
unauthorized absence and two years for using marijuana, detected by
urinalysis after his May 3 surrender, said his attorney, Howard
DeNike of San Francisco.
   Prosecutor Lt. Dennis Hoffman portrayed Smith as a ``problem
child'' who never grew up, but Smith's employer and the pastor of
his church testified he was a dependable worker and family man.
   Community groups and his current wife, Mary, who said she knew
nothing of the desertion, gathered 600 signatures from Smith's
friends, business associates and others asking that Smith get only
an administrative discharge.
   Mary Smith said she was ``overwhelmed'' by the sentence and
called it ``especially important when you've had somebody who's been
a constructive member of society.''
   Smith even garnered support from a veterans organization with
members from every U.S. war and major conflict since the 1930s. The
group asked the military to grant Smith clemency.
   Smith turned himself after getting a 5 a.m call from Navy
investigators, who tracked him through a routine credit check. After
several days in the brig, Smith has reported daily to Treasure
Island for duty on a maintenance unit.
   He is likely to be placed on leave without pay within a few weeks
and then discharged. That means the government probably won't get
the $1,000 he was ordered to forfeit, because it was to be taken out
of his next four monthly paychecks.
   In a previous interview, Smith said he had considered turning
himself in several times. ``But it was hard; I had a new life _
wife, kids, and I couldn't risk that.''
   ``I didn't want to hide,'' he said. ``I just wanted to put
everything behind me and get on with my life.''
   Smith's desertion meant he severed ties with his first wife, a
son, his parents and a sister, who at the time lived in Ohio. He has
not talked to them since and never obtained a divorce from his first
wife.
   DeNike said Smith deserted because he believed his first wife was
unfaithful and because he resented the rigidity of military life.
Smith enlisted in March 1968, and left the service without
permission twice before his final desertion.
   He remarried in 1975, had five children, bought a suburban house
in San Pablo and became active in the local Episcopal church. He
also worked 12 years as a manager at Kardum Paint Co. of San
Francisco, where he earned $24,000 yearly. Smith has been earning
$750 a month at his Navy job.
   DeNike said he assumes Smith's first wife either annulled the
marriage or received a divorce.
   Because he left during what the military technically considered
wartime, there is no statute of limitations to the charges. Congress
never declared war in the Vietnam conflict, but the military
previously ruled in desertion cases that wartime laws apply, said
DeNike.
   The record for Navy deserters who turned themselves in belongs to
a now-deceased sailor who jumped ship in 1926 and turned himself in
to Navy authorities last year, said Lt. Cmdr. Roberts, who would not
reveal the man's identity.
   The longest unresolved desertion case involves a sailor who left
his base in 1962, she added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
