<FIRST>r a AM-Navajo-Means     07-05 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navajo-Means,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Indian Activist After Altercation with BIA Official</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDOW ROCK, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian activist Russell Means was
arrested by police Wednesday after saying he was going to make a
citizen's arrest of a Bureau of Indian Affairs official and
wrestling that man to the floor.
   Means was pulled off BIA Navajo Office Area Director James
Stevens by BIA and tribal police in the room where Stevens had been
meeting with supporters of suspended Navajo Chairman Peter MacDonald.
   Tribal Police Chief George John said Means was arrested and
accused of assault and battery on Stevens. Means would appear
Thursday before a judge, John said.
   Stevens told The Associated Press later by telephone that he
planned to press charges against Means. ``Other than a few scratches
and a torn shirt, I'm OK,'' Stevens said.
   Means, a leader of the American Indian Movement, is a Lakota
Sioux from the Pine Ridge Reservation in South Dakota. He married a
Navajo woman three years ago and has lived in Chinle on the Navajo
Reservation for about a year.
   Stevens had agreed to meet Wednesday afternoon with Means and
seven other MacDonald supporters. Means and about 60 MacDonald
supporters, members of a group called Pro-Dine Voters, marched on
the federal building in Gallup, N.M., Wednesday morning. ``Dine'' is
Navajo for ``the people.''
   The altercation occured about 30 minutes into the meeting which
began with MacDonald supporters questioning Stevens on his actions
and the Navajo Tribal Council's having put MacDonald on paid
administrative leave.
   Stevens, a San Carlos Apache transferred to the Navajo
reservation on Nov. 14, denied he'd interfered in Navajo affairs and
said he had followed decisions of a majority of the Navajo Tribal
Council and of the Navajo Supreme Court.
   Means was involved in a 1972 takeover of BIA offices in
Washington. He was also present a year later when AIM held off
federal agents and national guardsmen during a seizure of Wounded
Knee in South Dakota.
   A majority of the Tribal Council voted in February to place
MacDonald on leave after a U.S. Senate subcommittee heard testimony
alleging he took kickbacks on tribal contracts and profited from a
tribal land purchase.
   MacDonald was re-elected tribal chairman in 1986, four years
after he lost a bid for a fourth straight term. Tribal finances
under his latest chairmanship have been the subject of a federal
grand jury investigation in Phoenix.
</TEXT>
