<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 2335EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DEAMurders     07-05 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DEA Murders,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Convicted Of Murder In Shooting Deaths Of Drug Agents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Taiwanese man was convicted Wednesday
of fatally shooting two federal drug agents and wounding a third
during an undercover heroin deal that turned into an attempted
robbery.
   The Superior Court jury deliberated for four days before finding
Wei Wen Wang guilty of murder, attempted murder and robbery in the
deaths of Drug Enforcement Administration agents Paul Seema and
George Montoya.
   Wang could also face the death penalty at his sentencing because
the jury found the special circumstances of murder during a robbery
and multiple murder. The penalty phase of his trial begins July 24.
   Seema, 52, and Montoya, 34, were shot to death when they were
double-crossed by Wang and his alleged associates during a February
1988 drug deal staged as part of an undercover operation,
authorities said.
   DEA agent Jose Martinez, 24, was wounded in the shooting, and two
of Wang's associates were killed in a subsequent shootout with
agents and police.
   A third man, Su Re ``Michael'' Chia, 21, has been convicted of
murder and attempted murder and sentenced to 61 years in prison.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Steven D. Clymer portrayed Wang as the
trigger-man in the attack, but defense attorney Morton Philip
Borenstein said that Wang had thought he was involved with dangerous
drug dealers, not federal agents.
   Seema, a 14-year DEA agent, was posing as a drug dealer when he
arranged to buy two pounds of heroin for $80,000 from Wen Huei Kow
for Montoya and Martinez, who were posing as buyers, authorities
alleged.
   Kow rode with the agents in their car to a home where the sale
was supposed to be made, but the agents were told to pull over on a
Pasadena street where they came under fire from Kow and Wang,
authorities alleged.
   Kow and Michael Sun, another man allegedly at the scene of the
shooting, were killed in the shootout that followed. Authorities say
Chia delivered one of the murder weapons the night before and knew
about the robbery plan.
</TEXT>
