<FIRST>r a AM-Cuomo-Abortion     07-05 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuomo-Abortion,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuomo Says He Still Opposes Removing Medicaid Funding for Abortions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo, saying the U.S. Supreme
Court follows a ``lower standard,'' promised his continued support
Wednesday for Medicaid funding in New York to pay for poor women's
abortions.
   Thus far, efforts to eliminate such abortion funding from New
York's state budgets have failed.
   Democrat Cuomo, a Roman Catholic, said nothing in the court's
Monday decision ``changes my opinion about the right to abortion or
the right of poor people to receive funding.''
   It was Cuomo's first statement on the Supreme Court's ruling on
the Missouri case Webster v. Reproductive Health Services, where the
divided top court upheld Missouri's attempt to place more
restrictions on abortions.
   New York state's abortion law, one of the most liberal in the
country, allows abortions during the first 24 weeks of pregnancy and
after that if a woman's life is in danger.
   Despite personally opposing abortion, Cuomo has included in his
budget each year Medicaid funds that can be used by poor women to
pay for abortions. Cuomo, who's said poor women shouldn't be denied
abortions that others can pay for, said he'll continue the practice
in his 1990 budget proposal.
   ``In this case, as in the case of the death penalty where the
Supreme Court would allow us to execute children and the mentally
retarded, we in New York will choose what we believe to be a higher
and better way,'' Cuomo said in a statement distributed by aides.
   Cuomo said he will ``oppose the inevitable attempt by some
legislators to deny fairness to poor people because the Supreme
Court follows a lower standard.''
   Cuomo also said he'd oppose any attempts to put any other
limitations enumerated in the Webster decision into state law, such
as a prohibition against abortions being held in public hospitals.
   But he would not say how he would act if presented with a bill
requiring parental consent if minors seek abortions.
   The governor said both the strongest Supreme Court supporter of
the 1973 Roe v. Wade decision legalizing abortion, Justice Harry
Blackmun, and the most outspoken critic, Justice Antonin Scalia,
both said the Webster decision breaks no legal ground.
   Anti-abortion lawmakers in both the Republican-controlled Senate
and Democratic-controlled Assembly already have said they will
attempt again next year to remove Medicaid funding from the budget.
Such moves have repeatedly failed in the past.
</TEXT>
