<DOCNO> AP890705-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 0820EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-Greece-Tourism Adv11   07-05 0889</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greece-Tourism, Adv 11,0917</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs July 11 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tourism Down in Greece Because of Image It Is Too Easy on Terrorists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This land of ancient ruins and sun-splashed
islands is troubled by its reputation as a country too cozy with
terrorists.
   While Greece angrily denies it, the image persists with painful
consequences for tourism, its largest industry. Many American
tourists who once flocked to its shores now go elsewhere.
   ``It's strange that Greece has to suffer such accusations,'' said
Costas Skouras, the secretary-general of the Greek National Tourist
Organization.
   ``Let's face reality. We know that international terrorism is not
a new phenomenon and especially air terrorism. These incidents can
happen any time, any place.''
   However, the most common complaint is what critics call the loose
and easy style that Premier Andreas Papandreou's socialist
government demonstrated in dealing with terrorists who come to
Greece after attacks elsewhere. The socialists lost their majority
in elections last month.
   In December, a Palestinian arrested in Greece was put on a plane
to Libya although he was wanted in Italy for a hand grenade attack
on Rome's main synagogue in October 1982. The attack killed a
2-year-old boy and wounded 37 other people.
   ``Other countries would give a Palestinian terrorist who killed a
baby the chair, the noose or life behind bars. Greece gave him a
plane ticket to freedom,'' the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai
B'rith charged in an advertisement in The New York Times.
   Greece has repeatedly delayed ruling on a U.S. extradition
request for another Palestinian accused of planting a bomb on a Pan
Am jetliner.
   Last year, the United States accused Greece of allowing the Abu
Nidal terror group to open a logistics office in Athens in exchange
for a promise not to launch any attacks in Greece.
   Skouras contends such allegations are unfair and says Greece
often finds itself caught in the middle.
   ``Some Arab and Palestinian countries accuse the Israeli mission
of being a place where many terrorists, Israeli terrorists, are
hiding,'' he said. ``And they ask our government to give these
Israeli terrorists to the Arabs and close the mission.''
   Vassilis Fillias, a Greek sociologist and newspaper columnist,
said one problem is the the widespread pro-Palestinian feeling in
Greece makes it difficult for the government to take a strong stand
against Arabs or Palestinians.
   Although the Supreme Court approved it, Papandreou's justice
minister, Vassilis Rotis, blocked the extradition of Abdel Osama
al-Zomar, the Palestinian wanted for the Rome attack and whose
detention in Greece may have triggered the massacre of the City of
Poros cruise ship near Athens last July. Terrorists killed nine
people aboard the ship. No one has been arrested for the attack.
   Rotis explained his decision by saying al-Zomar ``was acting in
the struggle for the reacquisition of his country.''
   ``We consider it outrageous,'' Justin J. Finger, the associate
national director of the Anti-Defamation League, said in a telephone
interview from New York. ``If other nations followed Greece's
example it would ... increase terrorism rather than dampen its
activity,''
   Italy protested Greece's refusal to extradite al-Zomar and on May
23 an Italian court convicted him in absentia of organizing the
synagogue attack and sentenced him to life in prison.
   Skouras contends some allegations against Greece are distortions
aimed at intentionally hurting its tourist industry. He declined to
elaborate except to say, ``I cannot find any other explanation
except that this country has enemies somewhere, perhaps competitors
in the tourism field or in some other field.'' Official government
figures _ which tour operators dispute _ indicate overall tourism
has increased every year since 1983. Last year, the figures show,
8.2 million tourists came, leaving Greece with almost $2.5 billion
in foreign exchange.
   The tour operators say the figures are deceiving.
   ``All this terrorism has dramatically affected our business in
Greece,'' said Dimitris Mantzios, the general manager of a large
Greek travel agency with offices in the United States, Japan and
Canada.
   He said his American business has fallen by 50 percent in five
years. There are more Europeans and Japanese coming to Greece, but
he said they don't stay as long or spend as much.
   ``Americans spend maybe $2,000 while the Europeans $500 to
$1,000,'' he said.
   Andreas Potamianos, the president of Epirotiki Lines, said
Americans fell from 60 percent of the passengers on his line to just
3 percent by 1986.
   ``It mainly occurred in 1985 after the hijacking of the TWA
airplane. Then the United States issued a travel advisory asking
Americans not to come to Greece. That travel advisory had an immense
effect,'' he said.
   That hijacking June 14, 1985, of an Athens to Rome flight ended
in Beirut where a U.S. Navy diver was killed and 38 people were held
captive for 17 days.
   The travel advisory was lifted six weeks later after Greece
increased security at its airports.
   ``But it was lifted in a very silent way and imposed in a very
pompous way with high publicity,'' complained Potamianos. ``When it
was lifted, it was two lines on an inside page.''
   Government statistics indicate 295,000 Americans traveled to
Greece in 1988 as opposed to the 360,000 Greece expected and less
than half the number who came 10 years ago.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs July 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
