<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 1056EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-OntheMoney Adv06   07-05 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-On the Money, Adv 06,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thursday July 6</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Niceties of Investment Advice</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When savers and investors turn to financial
professionals for advice, they usually look for two words _ ``buy''
or ``sell.''
   Experience shows, however, that they get far more than that. Even
if the words are printed in black and white, the vocabulary of
investment savants is rich in varying shades of gray.
   ``Hold'' is a familiar, and often perplexing, favorite. When
something isn't good enough to buy, what makes it worth hanging onto
just because you happen to own it?
   And if that gives you trouble, what to make of ``accumulate,''
``buy on weakness,'' ``switch,'' or ``use as a source of funds?''
   Faced with such choices, newcomers to the challenge of money
management often grow apprehensive, concerned that their ignorance
will be exposed when the natives see they don't speek the local
language.
   Cynics with longer experience, on the other hand, dismiss much of
what they hear in this vein as nothing more than mumbo-jumbo.
   The cynics have a point. Making investment recommendations is a
hazardous game and those who want to survive in the business for
long have a natural tendency to protect their flanks.
   Still, in fairness to these advisers, they are dealing with
questions that don't often yield clear yes-or-no answers for every
member of their audience. And many of the terms they use can be
translated into everyday English, with a little practice.
   Consider ``hold,'' for starters. A typical definition comes from
Donoghue's Moneyletter, an advisory service that uses a
buy-hold-sell system for rating mutual funds:
   ``If a `buy' fund dips in performance, it receives a `hold'
signal. If your fund becomes a `hold,' don't invest new money in
that fund, but don't sell it either. Although it's no longer a top
performer, it still compares favorably with other funds tracked in
Moneyletter.''
   For the long-term investor in particular, ``hold'' is often a
more sensible idea than either ``buy'' or ``sell.''
   Even if you should succeed in the nigh-impossible mission of
jumping from one hot investment to another at frequent intervals,
you have to consider the tax bills and transaction costs you might
ring up along the way.
   All that having been said, many veterans of the financial wars
still interpret a downgrading of a recommendation from buy to hold
as an adviser's gentle way of steering his or her clients away from
a given investment.
   Many other entries in the modern lexicon of investment
recommendations have evolved with the growing dominance of investing
institutions.
   Managers at these funds compete in a short-term performance derby
and are much less concerned with taxes or transaction costs than
individual investors must be. Because many of them are operating on
a large scale, they also cannot just ``buy'' or ``sell'' as readily
as the small investor can.
   Thus, ``accumulate'' translates as a sort of tepid buy
recommendation. In a meeting of an investment committee operating
under legal constraints of prudence, ``use as a source of funds'' is
a handy, if stuffy, way of saying ``sell this loser as judiciously
as you can and put the money someplace else.''
   No matter how you go about translating investment jargon, it is
always important to consider the source. If it comes from anybody
working on commission, you have every reason to expect to hear what
lawyers call ``dealers' talk.''
   Example in a recent midyear commentary from a research official
at a leading Wall Street firm: ``Stay well diversified in stocks,
bonds and cash, but do a little fine-tuning. Sell off big
stock-market winners, and recycle money back into undervalued
issues.''
   For a commission broker, there is money in selling and money in
buying. But there is no money in ``hold.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday July 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
