<FIRST>s a BC-PersonalFile-Tyson Adv09   07-05 0953</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Tyson, Adv 09,0982</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday July 9 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tyson Foods Chairman Practices `Patience' During Takeover</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on financial wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT CHARTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGDALE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   During his protracted battle to corner a
quarter of the nation's poultry market, chicken king Don Tyson drew
inspiration from a word he scribbled on the mirror in his private
bathroom.
   ``Patience,'' Tyson impulsively wrote in black felt-tip Oct. 5,
as he battled with ConAgra Inc. to absorb rival poultry giant Holly
Farms.
   The chairman of Tyson Foods wanted a reminder during the long and
agonizing takeover war to slow down and analyze developments that
stood to double the worth of his $2 billion company.
   ``Every time I stepped in the bathroom, I faced this word,'' the
59-year-old Tyson said as he pointed to the looping cursive on the
mirror.
   ``Patience. That was the key. We were just looking for time.''
   Patience _ and a sweetened bid _ paid off June 23 when Tyson
Foods and Holly Farms agreed to a merger deal worth $1.4 billion. On
July 18, Springdale-based Tyson's is to pay $70 per share for stock
in Holly Farms.
   ``If it hadn't been such a perfect fit, we would have gone off.
But it was just such a perfect fit with our company, productwise and
geographically,'' Tyson said of Holly Farms, which is headquartered
at Memphis, Tenn.
   The combination has prospects for huge profits, Tyson said, since
the company that bears his name emphasizes wholesale and
institutional service, with some supermarket sales, and Holly Farms
is a force in grocery stores, taking 40 percent of the fresh-poultry
market in New York City and Washington, D.C.
   The combination also promises to provide Tyson with the chickens
he needs to keep his company growing at the pace that has raised
annual revenues from $660 million to $1.9 billion in five years.
   The deal will give Tyson 25 percent of the fresh-poultry market
in the United States.
   When he first considered uniting with Holly Farms more than two
decades ago, the numbers were not so impressive. Tyson had one
poultry operation in the Ozarks, and Fred Lovette's Holly Farms was
about the same size.
   ``He was the first one to pre-package poultry and deliver it to
the supermarket, which was a major change,'' Tyson said of Lovette.
``And he was nice enough to show that to me 24 years ago, and we
talked then about maybe our companies should get together.''
   But the friendly discussion went nowhere, nor did conversations
Tyson initiated about six years ago with R. Lee Taylor II, Holly
Farms' president and chief executive officer.
   Last summer, Tyson asked the Stephens Inc. investment banking
firm at Little Rock to analyze how the companies might fit.
   ``Then I started visiting with Lee again. When it was obvious we
weren't going to get together, friendly, we had to tell Lee, `Hey,
we're going to go to your stockholders and ask them if they'd like
for us to get together.' That started this whole process,'' Tyson
said.
   The eight-month fight with ConAgra to gain control of Holly Farms
ranks as one of the nation's longest-running takeover wars.
   After the final agreement was reached, a janitor at the Tyson
Foods corporate complex was allowed to wipe clean her boss's
bathroom mirror.
   Last week, Tyson filled his red mug with coffee and settled into
a chair at his huge conference table to reflect on the takeover.
   ``I'm up to my neck in debt,'' he said, then laughed and added
that he has been there before.
   ``All of us are waking up with a better feeling every morning,''
said Tyson. ``Every time we look at this company, it's better than
we thought it was when we bought it.''
   Didn't he get upset when his offers were repeatedly spurned by
the Holly Farms executives and board?
   ``Just privately,'' Tyson said, ``because we were trying to
figure out a strategy. And we had a strategy, and then it didn't
work, and when the strategy didn't work, I was mad at myself.
   ``But then I remembered what my dad told me _ it costs money to
get mad.''
   It also cost money to settle with Holly Farms' other suitor,
whose advances threw a wrench into Tyson's strategy. ConAgra, of
Omaha, Neb., is to get $50 million for its trouble.
   Taylor, who will get $15.6 million for his Holly Farms shares,
will not stay on. ``He said something about taking a round-the-world
cruise, 'cause he's got enough money to,'' Tyson said.
   Tyson also took it easy after the agreement, flying to Alaska for
five days of salmon fishing. He said the fishing camp was 45 miles
from a road, and nowhere near a telephone.
   July's schedule is filled with meetings to push the merger along,
and accepting bids on two divisions of Holly Farms _ rendering and
flour _ that Tyson plans to sell to raise cash.
   Tyson, who joined his father in the business in 1952 and took
over the reins in 1967, also will keep looking for acquisitions,
which he compares to his beloved fishing excursions, saying,
``You've always got your hook in the water.''
   ``Of course, we've got our work cut out for us here for a couple
of years. Our boat's loaded. We're going to divest and we have a
goal by Sept. 30 of this year that we will pay back $500 million of
this debt. We'll do that,'' he said.
   ``They asked me how many chickens I wanted. I said, `Well,
General Motors at one time had 51 percent of the car business,' and
I thought that was fair.
   ``I'm patient.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday July 9</NOTE>
