<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 0757EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Picture-PerfectCrops     07-05 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Picture-Perfect Crops,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Computer Images of Plants Could Help Farmers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   University of Illinois researchers say
farmers' plants ought to be in pictures, and they want to take some
of the uncertainty out of farmers' decisions with the help of
computer vision technology.
   ``Farmers are constantly dealing with problems they can't control
_ they plant, pray and wait to harvest,'' researcher Ken Tarbell, a
University of Illinois graduate student, said recently. ``If we can
take technology and make their lives less stressful, that's what
we're here for.''
   Tarbell and UI agricultural engineer John Reid say
picture-perfect plants, photographed and displayed on a computer
screen, may give scientists a better idea of how healthy crops grow.
   He said once the system is perfected, farmers could take
photographs of their corn or soybeans at regular intervals, feed the
images into a computer, and find out quickly if their crops were
healthy or sick.
   ``Between planting and harvest, farmers rely on experience and
field history to make management decisions,'' said Tarbell. ``Our
goal is to give them timely information about their crops.''
   Tarbell selects three plants from his test field every day, puts
them in pots and photographs them in a studio next to a scale that
helps a computer analyze size and color. The color slides are
transferred to a high-resolution computer screen.
   One thing the computer studies is the leaf area, making its
calculations much more quickly and accurately than the traditional
method of hand measuring each leaf. Healthy plants have broader
leaves that capture more energy from the sun and help the crop yield
more at harvest.
   ``Scientists now get about 20 to 30 different measurements to
describe the condition of a plant in the field,'' said Tarbell. ``A
picture is worth a thousand words and they're only using a small
fraction of them.''
   ``The computer can spot trouble early,'' said Tarbell. ``It's a
lot more sensitive. A computer can see 256 shades of green and
people are lucky to be able to see 10.''
   For example, a lack of nitrogen fertilizer or an attack by
rootworms would put corn under stress and leaves would begin to
change from a healthy green to yellow. The computer could spot the
clue immediately, while there still was time to correct the problem.
   Farmers also might use the computer system to predict more
accurately how much grain they will have to market after harvest.
   Tarbell said the secret to good yields is keeping plants in ``an
optimum growth pattern.''
   ``We want to be able to tell farmers how to keep them there, or
if it's cost effective,'' said Tarbell.
   The computer system also could help scientists who are doing
things like developing new hybrids with drought resistance, he said.
The new variety of plant would be grown next to the existing hybrid,
and water would be limited.
   ``If the old hybrid starts to brown, they could measure the
damage exactly and the drought resistance of the new hybrid,'' said
Tarbell. ``You could do that without a computer but this machine
loves numbers and eliminates margin for error.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
