<FIRST>r f PM-Hanson-GoldFields 1stLd-Writethru f0011 07-05 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hanson-Gold Fields, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0011,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gold Fields Board Recommends Acceptance of New Hanson Bid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with board recommending Hanson's offer.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board of Consolidated Gold Fields PLC has
unanimously recommended that shareholders accept a new offer worth
$5.53 billion for the mining giant from British conglomerate Hanson
Trust PLC.
   The new 3.5 billion pound bid, which consists of cash, stock
warrants and an extra dividend payment, was announced Tuesday night
by Lord Hanson, the chairman of Hanson Trust.
   It was immediately supported by Consolidated Gold Fields'
chairman and chief executive, Rudolf Agnew, and later Tuesday night
gained the backing of the board.
   On June 22, Hanson in a move that took the stock market by
surprise offered 3.1 billion pounds, then worth $4.8 billion, for
Consolidated Gold Fields.
   But on that occasion, Agnew advised Consolidated Gold Fields'
shareholders not to accept, saying the offer undervalued the assets
of the company.
   Consolidated Gold Fields is primarily involved in mining South
African gold and platinum. It also has interests in U.S.
construction materials and owns a 49.3 percent stake in Newmont
Mining Corp., the largest U.S. gold miner.
   Hanson Trust is Britain's fourth largest company with interests
ranging from bricks and Ever Ready batteries to tobacco and light
industry. Among its American brands are Smith Corona typewriters,
Durkee spices and Farberware cookware.
   Last April, a U.S. court blocked a merger bid for Consolidated
Gold Fields from South African-controlled Minorco SA, an investment
group.
   Minorco's bid was worth 3.65 billion pounds, equivalent at the
time to $6.2 billion.
   A majority of Consolidated Gold Fields' shareholders indicated
that they wanted to accept Minorco's bid. But the U.S. court refused
to lift an injunction against a Minorco takeover arising from an
antitrust suit.
   U.S. courts had ruled that Minorco had ambitions to create a
world gold monopoly.
   One of the first shareholders to back the Hanson bid was Minorco
itself, which has pledged its 29.9 percent holding in Consolidated
Gold Fields to Hanson.
   Minorco had threatened to sack all of Consolidated Gold Fields'
management above the level of operations manager if its bid
succeeded.
   But Hanson said Tuesday night that he looked forward to welcoming
Agnew as a non-executive director of Hanson Trust if the Hanson
Trust bid is accepted.
</TEXT>
