<HEAD>Elliott and Executives Close to Bid for Elders IXL</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elders IXL Ltd chairman John Elliott
and other executives said Wednesday they were close to completing a
buyout bid for the brewing company through their privately held
firm, Harlin Holdings Pty Ltd.
   Elliott said at a shareholders meeting that Harlin is close to
arranging financing for a Part C stock exchange offer to all
shareholders at 3 Australian dollars, or about $2.30, which values
the company at 5.31 billion australian dollars, or $4.08 billion.
   Elliott said Harlin would only make an offer if it could arrange
financing and received consent from the National Companies and
Securities Commission.
   He said Harlin expected to make an announcement before an
extraordinary general meeting of Elders shareholders to be held on
July 27.
   Harlin, which is controlled by Elliott and other senior
executives, currently has 18.5 percent of Elders' ordinary shares,
which amounts to about 34 percent on a fully diluted basis.
   Elders, which has interests in brewing, agriculture, finance and
resources, is one of Australia's biggest companies. It owns the
Courage breweries in Britain, Carling O'Keefe breweries in Canada,
financial-services companies in Asia, grain-trading businesses in
the United States and natural resources interests in New Zealand.
   Elders says it is the seventh-largest brewer in the world. Its
main brand is Fosters Lager.
