<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 0955EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-SouthKorea-Grapefruit     07-05 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-South Korea-Grapefruit,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nationwide Consumer Group Launches Boycott of U.S. Grapefruit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korean consumer groups launched a
nationwide boycott Wednesday against imported U.S. grapefruit,
claiming it is chemically tainted and unsafe to eat.
   The U.S. Embassy and a spokesman for Florida growers who export
the fruit said the boycott is another salvo in a grapefruit war that
started over a huge misunderstanding.
   The Citizens Alliance for Consumer Protection of Korea said 10
leading consumer groups in Seoul and 60 others around the country
are not satisfied that U.S. grapefruit is safe and are launching a
nationwide campaign to warn people not to eat it.
   Grapefruit sales have plunged. Ads placed by grapefruit importers
appeared in Korean newspapers Tuesday headlined: ``Grapefruit has no
cancer-causing substance. We are sorry consumers have been worried.''
   At issue is the interpretation of a Korean laboratory report that
consumer advocates claimed shows Florida grapefruit contains
daminozide (Alar), a suspected cancer-causing agent.
   The U.S. Embassy and a citrus expert from Florida issued
statements and then held a news conference June 26 to say that the
scientific nature of the test was misinterpreted by laymen.
   ``Alar is not used on, and has never been used on grapefruit,''
said Dan L. Gunter, executive director of the Florida Department of
Citrus in Lakeland. ``We're concerned and hopeful the matter will be
clarified promptly.''
   The test, performed by the government's Agricultural Chemical
Research Institute, estimated Alar at 0.5 parts per million on the
peel and flesh of grapefruit. Gunter said that since the lab test
could not measure below 0.5 PPM, the report was ``equivalent to a
finding of no Alar.''
   A few days later the lab clarified the report and agreed that
could be the case. But then consumers demanded an explanation of
other chemicals used in the production of grapefruit.
   The Korean Women's Association asked for a second test, but the
lab refused and the National Health Institute said it did not have
the equipment.
   Korean farmers use pesticides and chemicals, and consumers are
increasingly concerned about their effect on food products. Some
growers also use Alar.
   ``As a Korean consumer, all we want is safe fruit,'' said Song
Bo-kyung of the Citizens Alliance. ``We are not convinced American
grapefruit is safe.''
   ``If the grapefruit businessmen accepted our concerns and made
efforts to improve, we would wait. But when they don't listen,
consumers have only one choice, a boycott,'' she said.
   Consumer organizations said the boycott is targeting 43 local
trading firms that are major importers and sellers of grapefruit.
Grapefruit has disappeared from some major markets but is available
in food stalls and back street stores.
   Grapefruit imports to South Korea have tripled every year for the
last four years and now total $10 million annually. Grapefruit is
imported from California, Texas and Arizona, but about
three-quarters comes from Florida.
   Florida, which produces one-half of the world's grapefruit, has
exported 300,000 boxes each weighing 85 pounds so far this year.
About 14 million boxes, a quarter of the state's production, is
exported annually to world markets, Gunter said.
   A spokesman for the grapefruit industry said the fruit can be
stored in cool containers for a few weeks, but unused fruit
eventually would spoil and have to be destroyed. He had no figures
for lost sales. South Korea does not produce grapefruit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
