<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   07-05 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Soar on Dry Forecasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices surged in early
trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade with some corn and
soybean markets up their permitted daily limits on forecasts for dry
Midwestern weather.
   The buying stemmed from a National Weather Service six-to-10-day
forecast, issued after the close of trading Monday, predicting
below-normal rainfall in the Corn Belt right through the middle of
next week.
   The soybean market also was buoyed by ideas that the extremely
wet conditions in the Southeast will prevent planting of soybean
crops there. But analysts said the dry forecast was the overriding
influence in early trading.
   ``The only way you can get the markets limit-up in July is almost
always weather,'' said Cathy Leow, a vice-president and grain-market
analyst with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York.
   Drier-than-normal conditions also are forecast for most U.S.
wheat areas, which would help get the winter wheat harvest back on
track in the Great Plains but could threaten the vulnerable spring
wheat crop in the North.
   In early trading, wheat was 4{ cents lower to 10} cents higher
with the contract for delivery in July at $4.03 a bushel; corn was 5
cents to the limit 10 cents higher with July at $2.82 a bushel; oats
were 10 cents to 12 cents higher with July at $1.69 a bushel;
soybeans were 21{ cents to the limit 30 cents higher with July at
$7.62 a bushel.
   Hog and pork-belly futures were trading at or near their lower
limits on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange in a continuing reaction
to Friday's quarterly Agriculture Department hogs-and-pigs
inventory, which showed fewer animals than traders had expected.
Cattle futures also were lower in early trading.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .30 cents lower with August at
69.55 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .45 cent to .67 cent lower
with August at 79.80 cents a pound; hogs were 1.40 cent lower to .13
cent higher with July at 47.30 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were locked down the 2-cents-a-pound limit across the board with
July at 31.85 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled sharply lower on Monday with
all pork futures down their daily limits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890705-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 1204EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-737Engines     07-05 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-737 Engines,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigation Targets Recent Model of Workhorse Engine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jet engine that remains the workhorse of the
Boeing 737 fleet is under close inspection because of problems that
led to the temporary grounding of 34 Boeing jets last month.
   Taken out of service after fan blades broke apart in flight on
two planes within three days, the jets were later returned to the
air with new or modified CFM56-3 engines.
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer reported today that industry
insiders say the problem could be the design, manufacture or
materials used in the latest model of the engine _ the CFM56-3C,
introduced on the 737 in October.
   Snecma in France and General Electric in Ohio are testing the
engines to see what went wrong. The two companies manufacture the
engines jointly under the name CFM International.
   GE officials declined to be interviewed. A spokesman for GE said
that its engineers are going over the engines thoroughly and will
not comment until they know the cause of the problem.
   The company has stressed that the engine has a history of
reliability, with an inflight shut-down rate of one in every 20,000
hours of flight, a performance record the industry considers healthy.
   Boeing also has declined to speculate publicly on what caused the
fan blades to break off.
   The CFM56-3C took the basic design of the CFM56-3 and increased
the thrust to 23,500 pounds, 1,500 pounds more than the CFM56-3B
model. Since the problems were discovered, the engines have been
rated to run at the lower thrust level.
   The engines contain 38 titanium fan blades, almost five feet in
diameter, which turn at 5,330 revolutions per minute. Tremendous
stress is put on the blades and the disks that hold them together, a
stress level the CFM56-C3 apparently could not withstand under some
conditions.
   It was a CFM56-3C that failed on a British Midlands jet in
January in a crash that killed 47 people. While the 737 is designed
to be able to fly on one engine, it is thought the pilot shut off
his good engine by mistake after the other caught fire.
Investigators have not yet disclosed what caused the engine to fail
in that plane.
   On June 9 a Dan-Air 737 en route to Minorca, Spain, was forced to
return to London's Gatwick airport because of severe engine
vibration. Two days later a British Midlands 737 flying from London
to Belfast, Northern Ireland, made an emergency landing because of
the same problem.
   While problems with fan blades are not uncommon, insiders say so
many problems so soon in a model's operating history is cause for
concern, the newspaper said.
   On June 13 Boeing took the unprecedented step of asking airlines
to ground planes to check their engines and replace damaged parts.
Airlines also were instructed to reduce the thrust to 22,000 pounds.
The grounding was simultaneously made mandatory for planes under the
jurisdiction of the British Civil Aviation Authority and
subsequently by the Federal Aviation Administration for U.S. planes.
   Inspections showed severe cracking of the fan blades, and in at
least one case, the fan disks.
   ``You just don't expect to have this kind of problem these days
on an operational engine,'' said a professor of aeronautics at a
major U.S. university. ``Normally, problems like this one are
detected during inspections and acted on immediately and fixed
without appearing in the newspaper.''
   This leads insiders to speculate that the breakage was not caused
simply by increased thrust, but by a set of unanticipated conditions
that caused too much vibration, the Post-Intelligencer said.
   Vibration in the fan blades, a harmonic oscillation similar to
the phenomenon of flutter in an airplane's wing, is caused by the
way the air moves around the metal. It is a result of how hard the
engine is run, its temperature and altitude.
   The fact that the fan blades broke during the climb at between
25,000 and 29,000 feet, is therefore also significant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890705-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 1206EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-McCaw-LIN     07-05 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-McCaw-LIN,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>McCaw Extends Offer for LIN, May Amend Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. said
today it will extend its $120-per-share hostile takeover bid for LIN
Broadcasting Corp. until July 20.
   McCaw said it was considering whether to adjust that offer and
will announce its decision next week. The company reserved the right
to extend the offer beyond July 20.
   The offer was due to expire at midnight Thursday.
   A revision of the takeover bid would reflect LIN's legal loss to
Metromedia Inc. last week over the right to buy Metromedia's
interests in cellular telephone systems in Philadelphia and New
York, McCaw said.
   ``Because the decision appears to bring the Metromedia litigation
to an unfavorable end for LIN, and because its $120-per-share offer
price for LIN stock reflects the possibility of a LIN victory, McCaw
... is now considering whether an adjustment in the offer price
would be appropriate,'' the company said in a prepared statement.
   McCaw said that only a ``nominal percentage'' of outstanding LIN
shares have been tendered to date.
   McCaw's current offer for LIN's outstanding shares is worth $5.85
billion.
   LIN Broadcasting rejected the $120-per-share offer in June.
</TEXT>
