<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morrison Knudsen Corp. and a joint venture
associate have been awarded a contract worth nearly $50 million to
construct an office building in downtown Tokyo, Morrison Knudsen
said Wednesday.
   William Agee, Morrison Knudsen president, chairman and chief
executive officer, said in a statement that the contract was awarded
to Morrison-Knudsen International Co. and Hazama-Gumi by Shuwa Corp.
of Japan.
   Work on the 18-story Kamiyacho building is scheduled to begin
immediately, with completion expected within 20 months.
   ``Our winning Shuwa Corporation as a client is a major step in
MK's return to the international marketplace and continues our plan
to develop global markets for our services and products,'' Agee said.
   Shuwa Corp. owns dozens of buildings in the United States,
including the Arco Plaza complex in Los Angeles and the ABC building
in New York.
   Morrison Knudsen is a worldwide construction and engineering
company based in Boise.
