<FIRST>d f BC-Britain-ChinaTrade     07-05 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-China Trade,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Business Groups Reconsidering China Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government ordered two private trade groups
Wednesday to reconsider sales-promotion trips to China because of
that country's recent bloody crackdown of pro-democracy
demonstrators.
   The Department of Trade and Industry and two private trade groups
had said they spent 12 months preparing the sales drives and saw no
reason to break normal commercial links with China.
   But Foreign Office Minister Lord Glenarthur, responding to
widespread criticism from government and opposition lawmakers, told
the House of Lords the visits were being reconsidered.
   After the crackdown by Chinese troops in Tiananmen Square on June
4, the European Economic Community banned ``ministerial and
high-level contacts'' with China.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher ruled out full economic
sanctions, but banned arms sales and told the House of Commons
``normal business could not continue with China.''
   Organizers of the two trade missions, which include leaders of
industry and banking, insisted they were not breaking the law but
angry lawmakers criticized the missions and demanded the government
withdraw its support.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
