<DOCNO> AP890705-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 1724EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     07-05 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise While Gasoline Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude and home heating oil prices gained while
gasoline prices skidded Wednesday as the energy futures market was
moved largely by supply concerns.
   The August contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, rose 52 cents to close at $20.79 a barrel on
the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   The August contract for home heating oil spurted 1.17 cents a
gallon higher to close at 51.06 cents, while wholesale unleaded
gasoline for August delivery dropped 0.35 cent to settle at 57.42
cents a gallon.
   Jim Fiedler, an analyst with E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures
Inc., said crude prices rose on concerns that the flow of oil from
the North Sea could be disrupted by labor problems between oil
companies and maintenance workers and helicopter pilots.
   In the heating oil market, traders bid up contracts believing
that stockpiles have not kept pace with demand, Fiedler said.
   He said gasoline prices fell because the summer driving season
has not been as strong as anticipated and traders were expecting
supply reports _ issued by the American Petroleum Institute after
the close of trading _ to show strong inventories of gas.
</TEXT>
