<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 1750EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-GoldFields-Newmont     07-05 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gold Fields-Newmont,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stake in Nation's Largest Gold Mining Firm Likely to Change Hands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A planned $5.53 billion buyout of Newmont Mining
Corp.'s biggest shareholder likely will mean that nearly half of
Newmont's stock will be up for sale soon, analysts said Thursday.
   British conglomerate Hanson Trust PLC announced late Tuesday that
it had tentatively agreed to acquire Consolidated Gold Fields PLC,
which owns a 49.3 percent stake in Newmont, the biggest U.S. gold
producer.
   Gold Fields raised its holdings in Newmont to 49.3 percent from
26.2 percent in a two-day ``street sweep'' in September 1987 to help
block a hostile takeover by a group led by oilman T. Boone Pickens
Jr. Pickens later dropped his bid for the company following the
purchase and court rulings that supported it.
   The board of directors for Gold Fields, which is involved mainly
in mining and road construction, recommended Tuesday that
shareholders accept the offer by Hanson, which sweetened its
proposal from an initial $4.8 billion bid made June 22.
   Hanson's varied interests include construction materials, the
likely source of the company's interest in Gold Fields, said William
Siedenburg, a New York-based analyst for the investment firm Smith,
Barney.
   ``Hanson doesn't know beans about mining,'' Siedenburg said,
calling it a ``minor possibility'' that Hanson would decide to keep
Gold Fields' Newmont assets, particularly because Newmont recorded
$1.2 billion in debt last year and its income was sagging.
Siedenburg said Hanson more likely would try to sell the Newmont
stake.
   Newmont rose 50 cents to $39.75 a share Wednesday on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   Newmont posted a profit of $9.4 million, or 14 cents a share, in
revenue of $132.2 million in the first quarter of this year. That
compared with a profit of $114.4 million _ including $30.3 million
in one-time gains _ or $1.70 a share on revenue of $92.4 million a
year earlier.
   The company recently announced a complex restructuring of its
Peabody Holding unit, the nation's biggest coal company, that
effectively will transfer some of its debt to Peabody while moving
$500 million in cash from the coal company to Newmont.
   Analyst Ronald Shorr at Bear, Stearns in New York noted that
Hanson had a history of breaking up companies it had acquired, in
order to keep the businesses it considered most useful.
   Consolidated's construction assets ``would fit nicely into some
niche that they (Hanson) have. The mining things do not. It is
likely that they would sell.''
   But, said Shorr, ``It's also true of Hanson that they've not
necessarily been in any great rush to sell things.'' Furthermore,
gold prices are relatively low, so Hanson might prefer to hang on to
Newmont for awhile, he said.
   Under a standstill agreement between Newmont and Gold Fields, the
British company may dispose of its stake in a widely placed public
offering to prevent raiders from acquiring the block and mounting a
new takeover threat.
   Both Shorr and Siedenburg said several parties expressed an
interest in purchasing a stake in Newmont earlier this year when the
South African-controlled Minorco SA investment group made a hostile
bid for Gold Fields.
   A U.S. judge blocked Minorco's bid in April, after Gold Fields
and Newmont filed an antitrust lawsuit to prevent the takeover, and
Minorco later agreed to sell its 29.9 percent stake in Gold Fields
to Hanson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890705-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 2127EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f AM-Times-Chinese     07-05 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Times-Chinese,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Los Angeles Times Distributes Chinese Language Section Statewide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese translation of a special 12-page Los
Angeles Times section ``The Shattered Dream: China 1989'' will be
distributed without charge in California Chinese communities, the
newspaper said Wednesday.
   ``We felt that it was well worth undertaking the logistics of
translation and distribution, given the importance of recent events
in Beijing to the people in Chinese communities throughout the
state,'' said Noel Greenwood, a Times deputy managing editor.
   The news section, distributed June 25 in English, provides
background on events leading up to the recent student protests and
massacre in Tiananmen Square, as well as analysis of the prospects
for China's political future.
   It was the first special news section translated into Chinese by
the Times, Greenwood said.
   Five interpreters spent two days translating the section, which
was then sent to Taiwan via facsimile transmission for typesetting
using a computer that allows high quality generation of Chinese
characters, the paper said.
   The composed pages were then flown to Los Angeles for printing at
the Times plant on July 2.
   Some 55,000 copies of the translated section will be distributed,
starting Thursday, in restaurants, book stores, libraries, grocery
stores and other outlets in Los Angeles, San Francisco, San Jose and
Oakland.
   Another 10,000 copies will be mailed to Chinese community leaders
in Southern California.
</TEXT>
