<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 1816EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     07-05 0777</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0804</SECOND>
<HEAD>Surging Corn and Soybeans Lead Broad Rise In Commodity Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn, soybean and oat futures prices soared their permitted daily
limits amid crop-threatening weather forecasts Wednesday, leading a
broad rise in commodity prices on U.S. futures exchanges.
   Prices for future deliveries of wheat, cattle, coffee, precious
metals, and crude oil also rose sharply.
   The exceptions to the rule were just as dramatic: pork and sugar
futures prices plunged.
   On the Chicago Board of Trade, most corn contracts settled up the
10-cents-a-bushel limit with the contract for delivery in July,
which is not bound by the price limit, finishing 11} cents higher at
$2.83} a bushel; soybeans were up the 30-cent limit across the board
except for the July contract, which rose 36 cents to $7.76{; oats
were 10 cents to 11 cents higher with July at $1.68 a bushel; wheat
was 5 cents to 9{ cents higher with July at $4.04 a bushel.
   The Board of Trade announced after the close that because of the
limit-up closes in corn, soybeans and oats, the price limits in
those markets would be expanded by 50 percent Thursday through
Monday in accordance with the exchange's rules.
   The run-up extended a rally begun on Monday _ the markets were
closed Tuesday _ and stemmed from a National Weather Service
six-to-10-day forecast issued after the close of trading Monday,
predicting below-normal rainfall in the Corn Belt.
   Analysts said the likelihood of temperatures in the 90s in the
Midwest later this week also bodes ill for the corn crop, which has
entered its pollination phase and requires cooler, wetter conditions.
   ``Extreme heat with no moisture is an absolute no-no for corn
this time of year,'' said Jerry Zusel, Balfour Maclaine Corp.'s
manager of trading-floor operations at the Board of Trade.
   Dry heat won't do much harm to the soybean crop in its current
stage of development, he said, but the strong rally in corn
triggered heavy buying in all of the neighboring grain pits.
   Soybean prices also were supported by the growing perception that
extremely wet field conditions in the South and Southeast will
prevent farmers from planting soybeans on land from which winter
wheat is now being harvested, a common practice called
``double-cropping.''
   A new six-to-10 day forecast issued after Wednesday's close
called for the hot, dry pattern in the Corn Belt to continue through
the end of next week.
   Frozen pork futures closed limit-down for the second consecutive
session on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange as the market continued
to reel from last Friday's quarterly Agriculture Department
hogs-and-pigs inventory, which showed fewer animals than the market
had expected.
   Philip Stanley, an independent livestock trader, said the
pork-belly market was likely to drop the 2-cents-a-pound limit at
the start of trading Thursday because of a high number of unfilled
sell orders .
   Live cattle futures rallied late in the session, partly in line
with the surging grain market and partly in a technical rebound from
the losses it had sustained in sympathy with the pork market.
   Live cattle settled .78 cent to 1.28 cents higher with August at
70.60 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .27 cent
higher with August at 80.62 cents a pound; hogs were the limit 1.50
cent lower to 1.15 cents higher with July at 47.15 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were 2 cents lower across the board with July at
31.85 cents a pound.
   Raw coffee futures rebounded on New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa
Exchange, where prices had sunk to eight-year lows Monday following
the collapse of the International Coffee Organization's
price-support system.
   Coffee settled 1.50 cents lower to 3.98 cents higher with July at
$1 a pound.
   Sugar futures fell in technically inspired selling in New York.
Contracts settled .50 cent to 1.01 cents lower with October at 13.46
cents a pound.
   Gold and silver futures staged a strong rally on New York's
Commodity Exchange, reacting to the inflationary cues of higher
commodity prices and to the dollar's pronounced weakness Wednesday
against other major currencies.
   Gold settled $7.30 to $8 higher with August at $388.40 a troy
ounce; silver was 16.3 cents to 18 cents higher with July at $5.393
a troy ounce.
   Crude-oil futures advanced on the New York Mercantile Exchange
amid labor uncertainties in the North Sea oil field.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 21 cents to 52 cents
higher with August at $20.79 a barrel; heating oil was .90 cent to
1.17 cents higher with August at 51.06 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .05 cent to .35 cent lower with August at 57.42 cents a
gallon.
</TEXT>
