<FILEID>AP-NR-07-05-89 2122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-U.S.Construction 2ndLd-Writethru f0260 07-05 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-U.S. Construction, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0260,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Construction Firm Wins Contract in Japan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT number of floors to 18 sted 16.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major U.S. construction firm signed a contract
Wednesday to join in a $47.9 million building project in downtown
Tokyo.
   Morrison-Knudsen International Co. will join with Hazama-Gumi
Ltd., one of Japan's largest civil engineering firms, to build an
18-story office and residential tower for Shuwa Corp., a large
Japanese real estate firm.
   The company, a division of Boise, Idaho-based Morrison-Knudsen
Corp., has established an office in Tokyo and obtained a Japanese
construction permit, which the Ministry of Construction says only
nine U.S. construction firms currently possess.
   Amid complaints that Japan's construction market was closed to
foreign companies, the Japanese government signed an agreement in
May 1988 to allow U.S. companies to participate in public works
projects here.
   Richard E. Kohne, chairman and chief executive officer of
Morrison-Knudsen, said this will be his firm's first project in
Japan, although it has operated in many countries abroad. He said
Morrison-Knudsen would receive between 15 and 35 percent of the work
in the project.
   In looking for a Japanese partner, he added, Morrison-Knudsen
interviewed a dozen potential contractors and chose Hazama because
``they are the closest in traditions and culture with our company.''
   Shuwa President Shigeru Kobayashi said his company had promised
former U.S. Commerce Secretary C. William Verity it would help U.S.
firms participate in the Japanese market.
   During the last two years, Shuwa has actively sought U.S. clients
with the help of the U.S. Department of Commerce and the U.S.
Embassy in Japan, Toshihiko Okino, a spokesman for Shuwa, said.
   The office tower project is Shuwa's second contract with a U.S.
firm for work in Japan. In March, it awarded an 11.2 billion yen,
$80 million, contract to a joint venture between the Turner Corp.
and Kumagai Gumi of Japan.
   Shuwa plans at least two more projects in which it will invite
U.S. firms to participate, Okino added.
   Shuwa also owns $2.5 billion in office and hotel space in the
United States, making it one of the largest Japanese owners of U.S.
real estate.
 
</TEXT>
